WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.700
Introduction to the Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus, translated

00:00:19.700 --> 00:00:20.700
by George Long.

00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:26.500
Introduction Marcus Arnius Verus was born in Rome in AD

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:32.400
121 and assumed the name of Marcus Aurelius Antoninus, by which he is known to history

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:36.000
on his adoption by the Emperor T. Aurelius Antoninus.

00:00:36.740 --> 00:00:41.860
He succeeded to the imperial throne in 161 and ruled till his death in 180.

00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:47.620
His reign, though marked by justice and moderation at home, was troubled by constant warfare

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:52.340
on the frontiers of the empire, and Aurelius spent much of his later years in the uncongenial

00:00:52.340 --> 00:00:56.360
task of commanding armies that no longer proved irresistible against the barbarian

00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:57.510
hordes.

00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:03.320
Marcus Aurelius was educated by the orator Fronto, but turned aside from rhetoric to

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:07.760
study of the Stoic philosophy, of which he was the last distinguished representative.

00:01:08.580 --> 00:01:12.840
The meditations, which he wrote in Greek, are among the most noteworthy expressions

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:16.240
of this system and exhibit it favourably on its practical side.

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:21.940
His own precepts he carried out with singular consistency, and both in his public and his

00:01:21.940 --> 00:01:24.660
private life he was in the highest degree conscientious.

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:30.620
He and his predecessor are noted as the only Roman emperors who can be said to have ruled

00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:32.840
with a single eye to the welfare of their subjects.

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:39.580
During his reign, Rome was visited by severe pestilence, and this, with reverses suffered

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:44.300
by his armies, threw the populace into a panic and led them to demand the sacrifice of the

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:47.840
Christians whom they regarded as having brought down the anger of the gods.

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:54.180
Aurelius seems to have shared the panic, and his record is stained by his sanction of the

00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:55.060
cruel persecution.

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:00.920
This incident in the career of the last and one of the loftiest of the pagan moralists

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:06.880
may be regarded as symbolic of the dying effort of heathenism to check the advancing tide

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:07.640
of Christianity.

00:02:08.540 --> 00:02:13.200
The meditations picture with faithfulness the mind and character of this noblest of

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:14.280
the emperors.

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:19.980
Simple in style and sincere in tone, they record for all time the height reached by

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:25.520
pagan aspirations in its effort to solve the problem of conduct, and the essential agreement

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:31.380
of his practice with his teaching proved that even in a palace life may be led well.

00:03:11.517 --> 00:03:16.957
1. For my grandfather Verus, I learned good morals and the government of my temper.

00:03:18.077 --> 00:03:23.457
2. From the reputation and remembrance of my father, modesty and a manly character.

00:03:24.497 --> 00:03:30.157
3. For my mother, piety and beneficence and abstinence, not only from evil deeds,

00:03:30.457 --> 00:03:34.337
but even from evil thoughts, and further simplicity in my way of living,

00:03:34.617 --> 00:03:39.757
far removed from the habits of the rich. 4. For my great grandfather,

00:03:39.757 --> 00:03:44.017
not to have frequented public schools, and to have had good teachers at home,

00:03:44.237 --> 00:03:47.777
and to know that on such things a man should spend liberally.

00:03:48.717 --> 00:03:53.777
5. For my governor, to be neither of the green nor of the blue party at the games in the circus,

00:03:54.177 --> 00:03:59.137
nor partisan either of the Parmularius or the Scutarius at the gladiator's fights.

00:03:59.677 --> 00:04:04.717
From him too I learned endurance of labor, and to want little and to work with my own hands,

00:04:04.977 --> 00:04:09.177
and not to meddle with other people's affairs, and not to be ready to listen to slander.

00:04:10.477 --> 00:04:16.497
6. From Diognatus, not to busy myself about trifling things, and not to give credit to what

00:04:16.497 --> 00:04:21.857
was said by miracle-workers and jugglers about incantations and the driving away of demons

00:04:21.857 --> 00:04:27.377
and such things, and not to breed quails for fighting, nor to give myself up passionately

00:04:27.377 --> 00:04:32.837
to such things, and to endure freedom of speech, and to have become intimate with philosophy,

00:04:33.417 --> 00:04:38.037
and to have been a hearer first of Bacchaeus, then of Tandassus and Marcianus,

00:04:38.037 --> 00:04:43.057
and to have written dialogues in my youth, and to have desired a plank, bed and skin,

00:04:43.457 --> 00:04:46.197
and whatever else of the kind belongs to the Grecian discipline.

00:04:47.437 --> 00:04:51.377
7. From Rusticus I received the impression that my character required improvement

00:04:51.377 --> 00:04:56.677
and discipline, and from him I learned not to be led astray to sophisticated emulation,

00:04:56.997 --> 00:05:01.857
nor to writing on speculative matters, nor to delivering little oratory orations,

00:05:02.257 --> 00:05:05.517
nor to showing myself off as a man who practices much discipline,

00:05:05.517 --> 00:05:10.197
or does benevolent acts in order to make a display, and to abstain from rhetoric,

00:05:10.557 --> 00:05:15.417
and poetry, and fine writing, and not to walk about in the house in my outdoor dress,

00:05:15.837 --> 00:05:19.657
nor to do other things of the kind, and to write my letters with simplicity,

00:05:20.097 --> 00:05:25.437
like the letter which Rusticus wrote from Senuisa to my mother, and with respect to those who have

00:05:25.437 --> 00:05:31.417
offended me by words or done me wrong, to be easily disposed to be pacified and reconciled

00:05:31.417 --> 00:05:35.597
as soon as they have shown a readiness to be reconciled, and to read carefully,

00:05:35.837 --> 00:05:40.537
and not to be satisfied with the superficial understanding of a book, nor hastily to give

00:05:40.537 --> 00:05:45.617
my assent to those who talk over much, and I am indebted to him for being acquainted with the

00:05:45.617 --> 00:05:49.897
discourses of Epictetus which he communicated to me out of his own collection.

00:05:51.337 --> 00:05:56.637
8. From Apollonius I learned freedom of will and undeviating steadiness of purpose,

00:05:56.637 --> 00:06:02.317
and to look to nothing else, not even for a moment, except to reason, and to be always the

00:06:02.317 --> 00:06:08.417
same in sharp pains, on the occasion of the loss of a child, and in long illness, and to see clearly

00:06:08.417 --> 00:06:14.137
in a living example that the same man can be both most resolute and yielding, and not peevish in

00:06:14.137 --> 00:06:19.257
giving his instruction, and to have had before my eyes a man who clearly considered his experience

00:06:19.257 --> 00:06:23.797
and his skill in expounding philosophical principles as the smallest of his merits.

00:06:23.797 --> 00:06:28.397
And from him I learned how to receive from friends what are esteemed favours

00:06:28.397 --> 00:06:32.417
without being either humbled by them or letting them pass unnoticed.

00:06:33.757 --> 00:06:39.457
From Sextus a benevolent disposition, and the example of a family governed in a fatherly manner,

00:06:39.957 --> 00:06:45.977
and the idea of living conformably to nature, and gravity without effectation, and to look carefully

00:06:45.977 --> 00:06:50.897
after the interests of friends, and to tolerate ignorant persons, and those who form opinions

00:06:50.897 --> 00:06:56.697
without consideration. He had the power of readily accommodating himself to all, so that intercourse

00:06:56.697 --> 00:07:01.957
with him was more agreeable than any flattery, and at the same time he was most highly venerated by

00:07:01.957 --> 00:07:07.437
those who associated with him, and he had the faculty both of discovering and ordering in an

00:07:07.437 --> 00:07:12.697
intelligent and methodical way the principles necessary for life, and he never showed anger

00:07:12.697 --> 00:07:18.597
or any other passion, but was entirely free from passion, and also most affectionate, and he could

00:07:18.597 --> 00:07:24.277
express approbation without noisy display, and he possessed much knowledge without ostentation.

00:07:26.017 --> 00:07:31.937
From Alexander, the grammarian, to refrain from fault-finding, and not in a reproachful way to

00:07:31.937 --> 00:07:37.917
chide those who uttered any barbarous or soloistic or strange-sounding expression, but dexterously

00:07:37.917 --> 00:07:42.837
to introduce the very expression which ought to have been used, and in the way of answer or giving

00:07:42.837 --> 00:07:48.577
confirmation or joining in an enquiry about the thing itself, not about the word, or by some other

00:07:48.577 --> 00:07:56.137
fit suggestion. 11. From Fronto I, I learned to observe what envy and duplicity and hypocrisy are

00:07:56.137 --> 00:08:01.397
in a tyrant, and that generally those among us who are called patricians are rather deficient

00:08:01.397 --> 00:08:08.097
in paternal affection. 12. From Alexander the Platonic, not frequently nor without necessity

00:08:08.097 --> 00:08:18.557
to say to anyone, or to write in a letter, that I have no leisure, nor continually to excuse the

00:08:18.557 --> 00:08:26.197
urgent occupations. 13. From Catullus, not to be indifferent when a friend finds fault, even if he

00:08:26.197 --> 00:08:31.857
should find fault without reason, but to try to restore him to his usual disposition, and to be

00:08:31.857 --> 00:08:39.417
ready to speak well of teachers, as it is reported of Demetius and Athanadotus, and to love my children truly.

00:08:41.257 --> 00:08:48.377
14. From my brother Severus, to love my kin, and to love truth, and to love justice, and through him

00:08:48.377 --> 00:08:56.577
I learned to know Thracia, Helvidius, Cato, Dion, Brutus. And from him I received the idea of a polity

00:08:56.577 --> 00:09:02.277
in which there is the same law for all, a polity administered with regard to equal rights and equal

00:09:02.277 --> 00:09:07.617
freedom of speech, and the idea of a kingly government which respects most of all the freedom

00:09:07.617 --> 00:09:14.177
of the governed. I learned from him also consistency and undeviating steadiness in my regard for

00:09:14.177 --> 00:09:20.197
philosophy, and a disposition to do good, and to give to others readily, and to cherish good hopes,

00:09:20.637 --> 00:09:25.697
and to believe that I am loved by my friends. And in him I observed no concealment of his

00:09:25.697 --> 00:09:30.617
opinions with respect to those whom he condemned, and that his friends had no need to conjecture

00:09:30.617 --> 00:09:38.317
what he wished or did not wish, but it was quite plain. 15. From Maximus I learned self-government,

00:09:38.597 --> 00:09:43.417
and not to be led aside by anything, and cheerfulness in all circumstances, as well as

00:09:43.417 --> 00:09:49.777
an illness, and a just admixture in the moral character of sweetness and dignity, and to do

00:09:49.777 --> 00:09:54.857
what was set before me without complaining. I observed that everybody believed that he thought

00:09:54.857 --> 00:10:01.157
as he spoke, and that in all that he did he never had any bad intention, and he never showed amazement

00:10:01.157 --> 00:10:06.977
and surprise, and was never in a hurry, and never put off doing a thing, nor was perplexed, nor

00:10:07.657 --> 00:10:12.717
dejected, nor did he ever laugh to disguise his vexation, nor on the other hand was he ever

00:10:12.717 --> 00:10:18.137
passionate or suspicious. He was accustomed to do acts of beneficence, and was ready to forgive,

00:10:18.557 --> 00:10:23.737
and was free from all falsehood. And he presented the appearance of a man who could not be diverted

00:10:23.737 --> 00:10:29.217
from right rather than of a man who had been improved. I observed too that no man could ever

00:10:29.217 --> 00:10:34.737
think that he was despised by Maximus, or ever ventured to think himself a better man. He had

00:10:34.737 --> 00:10:42.677
also the art of being humorous in an agreeable way. 16. In my father, I observed mildness of

00:10:42.677 --> 00:10:47.917
temper, and unchangeable resolution in the things which he had determined after due deliberation,

00:10:48.637 --> 00:10:54.097
and no vainglory in those things which men call honours, and a love of labour and perseverance,

00:10:54.777 --> 00:10:58.377
and a readiness to listen to those who had anything to propose for the common wheel,

00:10:59.437 --> 00:11:04.997
an undeviating firmness in giving to every man according to his deserts, and a knowledge

00:11:04.997 --> 00:11:10.597
derived from experience of the occasions for vigorous action and for remission. And I observed

00:11:10.597 --> 00:11:16.357
he had overcome all passion for joys, and he considered himself no more than any other citizen,

00:11:16.797 --> 00:11:21.857
and he released his friends from all obligation to sup with him or to attend him of a necessity

00:11:21.857 --> 00:11:27.297
when he went abroad. And those who failed to accompany him by reason of any urgent circumstances

00:11:27.297 --> 00:11:33.277
always found him the same. I observed too his habit of careful inquiry in all matters of

00:11:33.277 --> 00:11:38.497
deliberation, and his persistency, and that he never stopped his investigation through being

00:11:38.497 --> 00:11:43.597
satisfied with appearances which first present themselves, and that his disposition was to keep

00:11:43.597 --> 00:11:48.657
his friends and not to be soon tired of them, nor yet to be extravagant in his affection,

00:11:49.537 --> 00:11:55.357
and to be satisfied on all occasions and cheerful, and to foresee things a long way off and to

00:11:55.357 --> 00:12:01.317
provide for the smallest without display, and to check immediately popular applause and flattery,

00:12:01.317 --> 00:12:05.957
and to be ever watchful over the things which were necessary for the administration of the empire,

00:12:05.957 --> 00:12:11.097
and to be a good manager of the expenditure, and patiently to endure the blame which he got

00:12:11.097 --> 00:12:17.317
for such conduct. And he was neither superstitious with respect to the gods, nor did he court men by

00:12:17.317 --> 00:12:23.037
gifts or by trying to please them, or by flattering the populace. But he showed sobriety in all things

00:12:23.037 --> 00:12:29.437
and firmness, and never any mean thoughts or action, nor love of novelty. And the things which

00:12:29.437 --> 00:12:34.317
conduce in any way to the commodity of life, and of which fortune gives an abundant supply,

00:12:34.317 --> 00:12:40.137
he used without arrogance and without excusing himself, so that when he had them he enjoyed them

00:12:40.137 --> 00:12:46.377
without affectation, and when he had them not he did not want them. No one could ever say of him

00:12:46.377 --> 00:12:52.517
that he was either a sophist or a homebred flippant slave or patent, but everyone acknowledged him to

00:12:52.517 --> 00:12:58.397
be a man ripe, perfect, above flattery, able to manage his own and other men's affairs.

00:12:59.017 --> 00:13:03.737
Besides this he honoured those who were true philosophers, and he did not reproach those who

00:13:03.737 --> 00:13:09.677
tended to be philosophers, nor yet was he easily led by them. He was also easy in conversation,

00:13:09.997 --> 00:13:15.397
and he made himself agreeable without any offensive affectation. He took a reasonable care of his

00:13:15.397 --> 00:13:20.797
body's health, not as one who was greatly attached to life, nor out of regard to personal appearance,

00:13:21.297 --> 00:13:26.357
nor yet in a careless way, but thus so that, through his own attention, he very seldom stood

00:13:26.357 --> 00:13:32.617
in need of the physician's art or of medicine or external applications. He was most ready to give

00:13:32.617 --> 00:13:38.617
envy to those who possessed any particular faculty, such as that of eloquence or knowledge of the law

00:13:38.617 --> 00:13:44.137
or of morals or of anything else, and he gave them his help that each might enjoy reputation

00:13:44.137 --> 00:13:49.717
according to his deserts. And he always acted conformably to the institutions of his country

00:13:49.717 --> 00:13:55.997
without showing any affectation of doing so. Further, he was not fond of change nor unsteady,

00:13:56.317 --> 00:14:00.577
but he loved to stay in the same places and to employ himself about the same things,

00:14:00.577 --> 00:14:05.817
and after his paroxysms of headache he came immediately fresh and vigorous to his usual

00:14:05.817 --> 00:14:12.437
occupations. His secrets were not many, but very few and very rare, and these only about public

00:14:12.437 --> 00:14:17.237
matters, and he showed prudence and economy in the exhibition of the public spectacles

00:14:17.237 --> 00:14:22.477
and the construction of public buildings, his donations to the people, and in such things,

00:14:22.697 --> 00:14:26.877
for he was a man who looked to what ought to be done, not to the reputation which is

00:14:26.877 --> 00:14:32.977
not by a man's act. He did not take the bath at unseasonable hours. He was not fond of building

00:14:32.977 --> 00:14:38.537
houses, nor curious about what he eat, nor about the texture and colour of his clothes, nor about

00:14:38.537 --> 00:14:44.437
the beauty of his slaves. His dress came from lorium, his villa on the coast, and from linovium

00:14:44.437 --> 00:14:49.837
generally. We know how he behaved to the toll collector at Tusculum, who asked his pardon,

00:14:50.357 --> 00:14:56.417
and such was all his behaviour. There was in him nothing harsh nor implacable nor violent

00:14:56.417 --> 00:15:01.737
nor, as one may say, anything carried to the sweating point. But he examined all things

00:15:01.737 --> 00:15:06.537
severally as if he had abundance of time, and without confusion, in an orderly way,

00:15:06.817 --> 00:15:11.857
vigorously and consistently. And that might be applied to him which is recorded of Socrates,

00:15:12.277 --> 00:15:17.297
that he was able both to abstain from and to enjoy those things which many are too weak to

00:15:17.297 --> 00:15:23.017
abstain from and cannot enjoy without excess. But to be strong enough both to bear the one

00:15:23.017 --> 00:15:28.017
and to be sober in the other is the mark of a man who has a perfect and invincible soul,

00:15:28.457 --> 00:15:35.677
such as he showed in the illness of Maximus. 17. To the gods I am indebted for having good

00:15:35.677 --> 00:15:42.317
grandfathers, good parents, a good sister, good teachers, good associates, good kinsmen and

00:15:42.317 --> 00:15:47.897
friends, nearly everything good. Further, I owe it to the gods that I was not hurried into any

00:15:47.897 --> 00:15:52.917
offence against any of them, though I had a disposition which, if opportunity had offered,

00:15:53.217 --> 00:15:58.757
might have led me to do something of this kind. But, through their favour, there never was such

00:15:58.757 --> 00:16:04.617
a concurrence of circumstances as put me to the trial. Further, I am thankful to the gods that I

00:16:04.617 --> 00:16:09.557
was not longer brought up with my grandfather's concubine, and that I preserved the flower of my

00:16:09.557 --> 00:16:14.537
youth, and that I did not make proof of my virility before the proper season, but even

00:16:14.537 --> 00:16:19.737
referred to the time, that I was subjected to a ruler and a father who was able to take away all

00:16:19.737 --> 00:16:24.717
pride from me, and to bring me to the knowledge that it is possible for a man to live in a palace

00:16:24.717 --> 00:16:30.177
without wanting either guards, or embroidered dresses, or torches and statues, and such like

00:16:30.177 --> 00:16:35.697
show. But it is in such a man's power to bring himself very near to the fashion of a private

00:16:35.697 --> 00:16:40.717
person, without being for this reason either meaner in thought or more remiss in action,

00:16:40.717 --> 00:16:45.977
with respect to the things which must be done for the public interest in a manner that befits a ruler.

00:16:46.957 --> 00:16:51.757
I thank the gods for giving me such a brother who was able by his moral character to rouse me to

00:16:51.757 --> 00:16:57.197
vigilance over myself, and who, at the same time, pleased me by his respect and affection,

00:16:57.717 --> 00:17:03.277
that my children have not been stupid nor deformed in body, that I did not make more proficiency in

00:17:03.277 --> 00:17:08.077
rhetoric, poetry, and the other studies in which I should perhaps have been completely engaged

00:17:08.077 --> 00:17:13.257
if I had seen that I was making progress in them, that I made haste to place those who

00:17:13.257 --> 00:17:17.817
brought me up in the station of honor which they seemed to desire without putting them off with

00:17:17.817 --> 00:17:23.697
hope of my doing it some time after, because they were then still young, that I knew Apollonius,

00:17:23.937 --> 00:17:29.497
Rusticus, Maximus, that I received clear and frequent impressions about living according to

00:17:29.497 --> 00:17:35.317
nature, and what kind of a life that is, so that, so far as depended on the gods, and their gifts

00:17:35.317 --> 00:17:40.677
and help, and inspirations, nothing hindered me from forthwith living according to nature,

00:17:41.117 --> 00:17:45.517
though I still fall short of it through my own fault, and through not observing the admonitions

00:17:45.517 --> 00:17:51.717
of the gods, and I may almost say their direct instructions, that my body is held out so long

00:17:51.717 --> 00:17:57.157
in such a kind of life, that I never touched either Benedicta or Theodotus, and that, after

00:17:57.157 --> 00:18:03.117
having fallen into amatory passions, I was cured, and though I was often out of humor with Rusticus,

00:18:03.117 --> 00:18:08.197
I never did anything of which I had occasion to repent, that, though it was my mother's fate to

00:18:08.197 --> 00:18:13.877
die young, she spent the last years of her life with me, that, whenever I wished to help any man

00:18:13.877 --> 00:18:19.097
in his need, or in any other occasion, I was never told that I had not the means of doing it,

00:18:19.577 --> 00:18:23.757
and that to myself the same necessity never happened, to receive anything from another,

00:18:24.757 --> 00:18:30.357
that I have such a wife so obedient and so affectionate and so simple, that I had abundance

00:18:30.357 --> 00:18:34.817
of good masters for my children, and that remedies have been shown to me by dreams,

00:18:34.997 --> 00:18:39.937
both others, and against blood-spitting and giddiness, and that, when I had an inclination

00:18:39.937 --> 00:18:45.437
to philosophy, I did not fall into the hands of any sophist, and that I did not waste my time on

00:18:45.437 --> 00:18:50.437
writers of histories, or in the resolution of syllogisms, or occupy myself about the

00:18:50.437 --> 00:18:55.197
investigation of appearances in the heavens, for all these things require the help of the gods

00:18:55.197 --> 00:18:56.257
and fortune.

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:48.320
I shall meet with the busy body, the ungrateful, arrogant, deceitful, envious, unsocial.

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:53.060
All these things happen to them by reason of their ignorance of what is good and evil.

00:19:53.700 --> 00:19:58.740
But I who have seen the nature of the good that is beautiful, and of the bad that it is ugly,

00:19:59.180 --> 00:20:04.920
and the nature of him who does wrong, that it is akin to me, not only of the same blood or seed,

00:20:05.260 --> 00:20:09.680
but that it participates in the same intelligence and the same portion of the divinity,

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:14.640
I can neither be injured by any of them, for no one can fix on me what is ugly,

00:20:15.100 --> 00:20:18.300
nor can I be angry with my kinsman, nor hate him.

00:20:18.960 --> 00:20:26.420
For we are made for cooperation, like feet, like hands, like eyelids, like the rows of the upper and lower teeth.

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:33.540
To act against one another then is contrary to nature, and it is acting against one another to be vexed and to turn away.

00:20:35.240 --> 00:20:41.100
2. Whatever this is that I am, it is a little flesh and breath, and the ruling part.

00:20:41.740 --> 00:20:45.840
Throw away thy books, no longer distract thyself, it is not allowed.

00:20:46.360 --> 00:20:51.680
But as if thou wast now dying, despise the flesh, it is blood and bones and a network,

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:54.720
a conjecture of nerves, veins and arteries.

00:20:55.580 --> 00:21:00.200
See the breath also, what kind of a thing it is, air and not always the same,

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:03.080
but every moment sent out and again sucked in.

00:21:03.640 --> 00:21:08.700
The third then is the ruling part. Consider thus, thou art an old man,

00:21:09.060 --> 00:21:14.760
no longer let this be a slave, no longer be pulled by the strings like a puppet to unsocial movements,

00:21:15.240 --> 00:21:19.600
no longer be either dissatisfied with thy present lot or shrink from the future.

00:21:20.720 --> 00:21:24.160
3. All that is from the gods is full of providence.

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:32.360
That which is from fortune is not separated from nature or without an interweaving and involution with the things which are ordered by providence.

00:21:32.940 --> 00:21:36.760
From thence all things flow, and there is besides necessity,

00:21:37.240 --> 00:21:41.060
and that which is for the advantage of the whole universe, of which thou art a part.

00:21:41.660 --> 00:21:47.460
But that is good for every part of nature which the nature of the whole brings, and what serves to maintain this nature.

00:21:48.220 --> 00:21:51.540
Now the universe is preserved, as by the changes of the elements,

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:54.600
so by the changes of things compounded of the elements.

00:21:55.220 --> 00:21:59.180
Let these principles be enough for thee, let them always be fixed opinions,

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:03.600
but cast away the thirst after books, that thou mayest not die murmuring,

00:22:03.860 --> 00:22:07.820
but cheerfully, truly, and from thy heart thankful to the gods.

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:12.900
4. Remember how long thou hast been putting off these things,

00:22:13.060 --> 00:22:18.280
and how often thou hast received an opportunity from the gods, and yet dost not use it.

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:22.220
Thou must now at last perceive of what universe thou art a part,

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:25.940
and of what administrator of the universe thy existence is in a flux,

00:22:26.420 --> 00:22:28.880
and that a limit of time is fixed for thee,

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:32.760
which if thou dost not use for clearing away the clouds from thy mind,

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:36.160
it will go, and thou wilt go, and it will never return.

00:22:37.780 --> 00:22:43.180
5. Every moment think steadily as a Roman, and a man to do what thou hast in hand,

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:48.800
with perfect and simple dignity, and feeling of affection, and freedom, and justice,

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:51.980
and to give thyself relief from all other thoughts.

00:22:51.980 --> 00:22:58.060
6. And thou wilt give thyself relief, if thou doest every act of thy life as if it were the last,

00:22:58.440 --> 00:23:02.840
laying aside all carelessness and passionate aversion from the commands of reason,

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:08.660
and all hypocrisy, and self-love, and discontent with the portion which has been given to thee.

00:23:09.380 --> 00:23:13.520
7. Thou seest how few the things are, though which if a man lays hold of,

00:23:13.660 --> 00:23:18.220
he is able to live a life which flows in quiet, and is like the existence of the gods.

00:23:18.220 --> 00:23:23.500
For the gods in their part will require nothing more from him who observes these things.

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:29.060
6. Do wrong to thyself, do wrong to thyself, my soul,

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:32.480
but thou wilt no longer have the opportunity of honoring thyself.

00:23:33.720 --> 00:23:37.240
Every man's life is sufficient, but thine is nearly finished,

00:23:37.620 --> 00:23:43.060
though thy soul reverences not itself, but places thy felicity in the souls of others.

00:23:44.380 --> 00:23:48.340
7. Do the things external which fall upon thee distract thee?

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:53.000
Give thyself time to learn something new and good, and cease to be whirled about.

00:23:53.620 --> 00:23:56.800
But then thou must also avoid being carried about the other way,

00:23:57.120 --> 00:24:00.920
for those too are triflers who have wearied themselves in life by their activity,

00:24:01.460 --> 00:24:06.440
and yet have no object to which to direct every movement, and in a word, all their thoughts.

00:24:07.840 --> 00:24:11.360
8. Through not observing what is in the mind of another man

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:13.520
has seldom been seen to be unhappy.

00:24:14.260 --> 00:24:19.080
But those who do not observe the movements of their own minds must of necessity be unhappy.

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:26.380
9. This thou must always bear in mind, what is the nature of the whole, and what is my nature,

00:24:26.820 --> 00:24:31.680
and how this is related to that, and what kind of a part it is of what kind of a whole,

00:24:32.380 --> 00:24:36.400
and that there is no one who hinders thee from always doing and saying the things

00:24:36.400 --> 00:24:39.520
which are according to the nature of which thou art a part.

00:24:40.660 --> 00:24:44.700
10. Theophrastus, in his comparison of bad acts,

00:24:45.100 --> 00:24:48.760
such a comparison as one would make in accordance with the common notions of mankind,

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:53.820
says, like a true philosopher, that the offences which are committed through desire

00:24:53.820 --> 00:24:56.960
are more blamable than those which are committed through anger.

00:24:57.520 --> 00:25:00.920
For he who is excited by anger seems to turn away from reason

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:03.560
with a certain pain and unconscious contraction.

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:07.880
But he who offends through desire, being overpowered by pleasure,

00:25:07.880 --> 00:25:12.260
seems to be in a manner more intemperate and more womanish in his offences.

00:25:13.100 --> 00:25:17.000
Rightly then, and in a way worthy of philosophy, he said that the offence

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.400
which is committed with pleasure is more blamable than that which is committed with pain.

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:25.980
And on the whole the one is more like a person who has been first wronged

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:27.980
and through pain is compelled to be angry.

00:25:28.460 --> 00:25:31.240
But the other is moved by his own impulse to do wrong,

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:34.080
being carried toward doing something by desire.

00:25:35.860 --> 00:25:40.620
11. Since it is possible that thou mayest depart from life this very moment,

00:25:41.160 --> 00:25:43.400
regulate every act and thought accordingly.

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:48.800
But to go away from among men, if there are gods, is not a thing to be afraid of,

00:25:49.060 --> 00:25:51.160
for the gods will not involve thee in evil.

00:25:51.700 --> 00:25:56.240
But if indeed they do not exist, or if they have no concern about human affairs,

00:25:56.740 --> 00:26:01.100
what is it to me to live in a universe devoid of gods or devoid of providence?

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:05.620
But in truth they do exist, and they do not care for human things,

00:26:05.900 --> 00:26:10.640
and they have put all the means in man's power to enable him not to fall into real evils.

00:26:11.300 --> 00:26:15.800
And as to the rest, if there was anything evil, they would have provided for this also,

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:20.000
that it should be altogether in a man's power not to fall into it.

00:26:20.720 --> 00:26:24.940
Now, that which does not make a man worse, how can it make a man's life worse?

00:26:25.380 --> 00:26:27.940
But neither through ignorance, nor having the knowledge,

00:26:27.940 --> 00:26:30.920
but not the power to guard against or correct these things,

00:26:31.060 --> 00:26:34.260
it is possible that the nature of the universe has overlooked them.

00:26:34.900 --> 00:26:37.620
Nor is it possible that it has made so great a mistake,

00:26:37.880 --> 00:26:40.200
either through want of power or want of skill,

00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:44.260
that good and evil should happen indiscriminately to the good and the bad.

00:26:45.040 --> 00:26:49.260
But death certainly, and life, honor and dishonor, pain and pleasure,

00:26:49.580 --> 00:26:52.660
all these things equally happen to good men and bad,

00:26:53.020 --> 00:26:55.740
being things which make us neither better nor worse.

00:26:55.740 --> 00:26:58.780
Therefore, they are neither good nor evil.

00:26:59.640 --> 00:27:02.660
Twelve. How quickly all these things disappear,

00:27:03.020 --> 00:27:07.360
in the universe the bodies themselves, but in time the remembrance of them.

00:27:08.120 --> 00:27:10.040
What is the nature of all sensible things,

00:27:10.280 --> 00:27:13.240
and particularly those which attract with the bait of pleasure,

00:27:13.640 --> 00:27:17.460
or terrify by pain, or are noised about by vapoury fame?

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:23.400
How worthless and contemptible and sordid and perishable and dead they are.

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:27.300
All this it is the part of the intellectual faculty to observe.

00:27:28.180 --> 00:27:32.160
To observe, too, who these are whose opinions and voices give reputation.

00:27:32.900 --> 00:27:36.880
What death is, and the fact that, if a man looks at it in himself,

00:27:37.180 --> 00:27:40.820
and by the abstract of power reflection, resolves into their parts

00:27:40.820 --> 00:27:44.040
all the things which present themselves to the imagination in it,

00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:47.800
he will then consider it to be nothing else than an operation of nature.

00:27:48.400 --> 00:27:52.020
And if anyone is afraid of an operation of nature, he is a child.

00:27:52.720 --> 00:27:55.560
This, however, is not only an operation of nature,

00:27:55.940 --> 00:27:59.260
but it is also a thing which conduces to the purposes of nature.

00:27:59.960 --> 00:28:02.660
To observe, too, how man comes near to the deity,

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:06.960
and by what part of him, and when this part of man, is so disposed.

00:28:08.840 --> 00:28:13.860
Thirteen. Nothing is more wretched than a man who traverses everything in a round,

00:28:14.300 --> 00:28:17.440
and prides into things beneath the earth, as the poet says,

00:28:17.800 --> 00:28:21.120
and seeks by conjecture what is in the minds of his neighbours,

00:28:22.020 --> 00:28:25.380
perceiving that it is sufficient to attend to the demon within him,

00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:27.200
and to reverence it sincerely.

00:28:28.080 --> 00:28:31.660
And reverence of the demon consists in keeping it pure from passion,

00:28:32.100 --> 00:28:36.300
and thoughtlessness, and dissatisfaction with what comes from gods and men.

00:28:37.080 --> 00:28:40.140
For the things from gods merit veneration for their excellence,

00:28:40.720 --> 00:28:44.220
and the things from men should be dear to us by reason of kinship,

00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:49.980
and sometimes even in a manner they move our pity by reason of men's ignorance of good and bad.

00:28:49.980 --> 00:28:54.360
This defect being not less than that which deprives us of the power

00:28:54.360 --> 00:28:57.360
of distinguishing things that are white and black.

00:28:59.060 --> 00:29:02.700
Fourteen. Though thou shouldest be going to live three thousand years,

00:29:02.820 --> 00:29:04.960
and as many times ten thousand years,

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:09.500
still remember that no man loses any other life than this which he now lives,

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:12.760
nor lives any other than this which he now loses.

00:29:13.440 --> 00:29:16.220
The longest and shortest are thus brought to the same,

00:29:16.580 --> 00:29:18.400
for the present is the same to all,

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:21.060
though that which perishes is not the same.

00:29:21.500 --> 00:29:24.300
And so that which is lost appears to be a mere moment.

00:29:25.080 --> 00:29:27.900
For a man cannot lose either the past or the future.

00:29:28.260 --> 00:29:31.320
For what a man has not, how can anyone take this from him?

00:29:32.020 --> 00:29:34.300
These two things then thou must bear in mind.

00:29:34.520 --> 00:29:38.020
The one, that all things from eternity are of like forms,

00:29:38.180 --> 00:29:40.940
and come round in a circle, and that it makes no difference

00:29:40.940 --> 00:29:44.240
whether a man shall see the same things during a hundred years,

00:29:44.480 --> 00:29:46.680
or two hundred, or an infinite time.

00:29:46.680 --> 00:29:51.500
And the second, that the longest-liver and he who will die soonest

00:29:51.500 --> 00:29:52.980
lose just the same.

00:29:53.620 --> 00:29:56.960
For the present is the only thing of which a man can be deprived,

00:29:57.460 --> 00:30:00.360
if it is true that this is the only thing which he has,

00:30:00.600 --> 00:30:03.380
and that a man cannot lose a thing if he has it not.

00:30:04.940 --> 00:30:07.400
Fifteen. Remember that all is opinion.

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:10.540
For what was said by the Cynic Monomus is manifest,

00:30:11.100 --> 00:30:13.560
and manifest, too, is the use of what was said,

00:30:13.560 --> 00:30:17.600
if a man receives what may be gut out of it as far as it is true.

00:30:19.220 --> 00:30:22.100
Sixteen. The soul of man does violence to itself,

00:30:22.580 --> 00:30:25.960
first of all when it becomes as abscess, and, as it were,

00:30:26.140 --> 00:30:28.680
a tumor on the universe, so far as it can.

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:33.320
For to be vexed at anything which happens is a separation of ourselves from nature,

00:30:33.860 --> 00:30:36.980
in some part of which the natures of all other things are contained.

00:30:37.900 --> 00:30:42.460
In the next place the soul does violence to itself when it turns away from any man,

00:30:42.460 --> 00:30:45.620
or even moves towards him with the intention of injuring,

00:30:45.860 --> 00:30:48.100
such as of the souls of those who are angry.

00:30:48.660 --> 00:30:51.480
In the third place the soul does violence to itself

00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:55.220
when it is overpowered by pleasure or by pain.

00:30:56.080 --> 00:31:00.700
Fourthly, when it plays a part and does or says anything insincerely and untruly.

00:31:01.820 --> 00:31:06.600
Fifthly, when it allows any act of its own and any movement to be without an aim,

00:31:07.080 --> 00:31:10.760
and does anything thoughtlessly and without considering what it is,

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:14.660
being right that even the smallest things be done with reference to an end.

00:31:15.500 --> 00:31:21.200
And the end of rational animals is to follow the reason and the law of the most ancient city and polity.

00:31:22.960 --> 00:31:28.160
Seventeen. Of human life the time is a point, and the substance is in a flux,

00:31:28.680 --> 00:31:32.960
and the perception dull, and the composition of the whole body subject to putrefaction,

00:31:33.920 --> 00:31:39.460
and the soul of a whirl, and fortune hard to divine, and fame a thing devoid of judgment.

00:31:39.460 --> 00:31:44.780
And to say all in a word, everything which belongs to the body is a stream,

00:31:45.300 --> 00:31:48.260
and what belongs to the soul is a dream and vapor,

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:54.660
and life is a warfare and a stranger's sojourn, and after fame is oblivion.

00:31:55.540 --> 00:32:01.140
What then is that which is able to conduct a man? One thing and only one, philosophy.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:06.420
But this consists in keeping the demon within a man free from violence and unharmed,

00:32:06.420 --> 00:32:12.520
superior to pains and pleasures, doing nothing without a purpose, nor yet falsely and with hypocrisy,

00:32:13.420 --> 00:32:16.980
not feeling the need of another man's doing or not doing anything.

00:32:17.580 --> 00:32:21.040
And besides, accepting all that happens and all that is allotted,

00:32:21.380 --> 00:32:25.240
as coming from thence, wherever it is, from whence he himself came.

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:28.940
And finally, waiting for death with a cheerful mind,

00:32:29.260 --> 00:32:34.300
as being nothing else than a dissolution of the elements of which every living being is compounded.

00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:39.640
But, if there is no harm to the elements themselves in each continually changing into another,

00:32:40.060 --> 00:32:44.480
why should a man have any apprehension about the change and dissolution of all the elements?

00:32:45.120 --> 00:32:49.420
For it is according to nature, and nothing is evil which is according to nature.

00:32:51.820 --> 00:32:52.860
This incarnuntum.

00:33:26.548 --> 00:33:31.008
We ought to consider not only that our life is daily wasting away, and a smaller part

00:33:31.008 --> 00:33:36.248
of it is left, but another thing also must be taken into account, that if a man should

00:33:36.248 --> 00:33:41.188
live longer, it is quite uncertain whether the understanding will still continue sufficient

00:33:41.188 --> 00:33:46.168
for the comprehension of things, and retain the power of contemplation which strives to

00:33:46.168 --> 00:33:48.488
acquire the knowledge of the Divine and the human.

00:33:49.388 --> 00:33:54.948
For if he shall begin to fall into dotage, perspiration and nutrition, and imagination

00:33:54.948 --> 00:33:58.628
and appetite, and whatever else there is of the kind, will not fail.

00:33:58.628 --> 00:34:04.028
But the power of making use of ourselves, and filling up the measure of our duty, and

00:34:04.028 --> 00:34:09.248
clearly separating all appearances, and considering whether a man should now depart from life,

00:34:09.668 --> 00:34:14.988
and whatever else of the kind absolutely requires a disciplined reason, all this is already

00:34:14.988 --> 00:34:15.728
extinguished.

00:34:16.248 --> 00:34:20.848
We must make haste then, not only because we are daily nearer to death, but also because

00:34:20.848 --> 00:34:24.048
the conception of things and the understanding of them cease first.

00:34:25.108 --> 00:34:30.628
2. We ought to observe also that even the things which follow after the things which

00:34:30.628 --> 00:34:35.888
are produced according to nature, contain something pleasing and attractive. For instance,

00:34:36.208 --> 00:34:41.428
when bread is baked some parts are split at the surface, and these parts which thus open

00:34:41.428 --> 00:34:45.928
and have a certain fashion contrary to the purpose of the baker's art, are beautiful

00:34:45.928 --> 00:34:52.048
in a manner, and in a peculiar way excite a desire for eating. And again figs, when

00:34:52.048 --> 00:34:57.488
they are quite ripe, gape open, and in the ripe olives the very circumstance that they

00:34:57.488 --> 00:35:02.988
are being near to rottenness adds a peculiar beauty to the fruit. And the ears of corn

00:35:02.988 --> 00:35:08.468
bending down, and the lion's eyebrows, and the foam which flows from the mouth of wild

00:35:08.468 --> 00:35:13.768
boars, and many other things, though they are far from being beautiful, if a man should

00:35:13.768 --> 00:35:19.128
examine them severally, still, because they are consequent upon the things which are formed

00:35:19.128 --> 00:35:26.368
by nature, help to adorn them, and they please the mind. So that if a man should have a feeling

00:35:26.368 --> 00:35:31.908
and a deeper insight with respect to the things which are produced in the universe, there

00:35:31.908 --> 00:35:37.148
is hardly one of those which follow by way of consequence which will not seem to him

00:35:37.148 --> 00:35:44.348
to be in a manner disposed so as to give pleasure. And so he will see even the real gaping jaws

00:35:44.348 --> 00:35:49.768
of wild beasts with no less pleasure than those which painters and sculptors show by

00:35:49.768 --> 00:35:55.408
imitation. And in an old woman and an old man he will be able to see a certain maturity

00:35:55.408 --> 00:36:00.908
and comeliness, and the attractive loveliness of young persons he will be able to look on

00:36:00.908 --> 00:36:06.148
with chaste eyes, and many such things will present themselves, not pleasing to every

00:36:06.148 --> 00:36:11.188
man, but to him only who has become truly familiar with nature and her works.

00:36:12.308 --> 00:36:19.688
3. Hippocrates, after curing many diseases, himself fell sick and died. The Childi foretold

00:36:19.688 --> 00:36:26.708
them deaths of many and then fate caught them too. Alexander and Pompeius and Caius Caesar,

00:36:27.168 --> 00:36:32.268
after so often completely destroying whole cities and in battle cutting to pieces many

00:36:32.268 --> 00:36:38.628
tens of thousands of cavalry and infantry, themselves too at last departed from life.

00:36:39.968 --> 00:36:45.288
Heraclitus, after so many speculations on the conflagration of the universe, was filled

00:36:45.288 --> 00:36:51.408
with water internally and died smeared all over with mud. And lice destroyed Democritus

00:36:51.408 --> 00:36:57.988
and other lice killed Socrates. What means all this? Thou hast embarked, thou hast made

00:36:57.988 --> 00:37:04.528
the voyage, thou art come to shore, get out. If indeed to another life there is no want

00:37:04.528 --> 00:37:11.188
of gods, not even there. But it to state without sensation, thou wilt cease to be held by

00:37:11.188 --> 00:37:16.688
pains and pleasures, and to be a slave to the vessel which is as much inferior as that

00:37:16.688 --> 00:37:23.468
which serves it is superior. For the one is intelligence and deity, the other is earth

00:37:23.468 --> 00:37:29.448
and corruption. 4. Do not waste the remainder of thy life

00:37:29.448 --> 00:37:34.868
in thoughts about others, when thou dost not refer thy thoughts to some object of common

00:37:34.868 --> 00:37:40.488
utility, for thou losest the opportunity of doing something else when thou hast such thoughts

00:37:40.488 --> 00:37:46.448
as these. What is such a person doing, and why, and what is he saying, and what is he

00:37:46.448 --> 00:37:51.028
thinking of, and what is he contriving, and whatever else of the kind makes us wander

00:37:51.028 --> 00:37:56.808
away from the observation of our own ruling power? We ought then to check in the series

00:37:56.808 --> 00:38:01.788
of our thoughts everything that is without a purpose and useless. But most of all the

00:38:01.788 --> 00:38:06.888
over-curious feeling and the malignant, and a man should use himself to think of those

00:38:06.888 --> 00:38:12.508
things only about which if one should suddenly ask, What hast thou now in thy thoughts? With

00:38:12.508 --> 00:38:17.848
perfect openness thou mightest immediately answer, This or that, so that from thy words

00:38:17.848 --> 00:38:22.568
it should be plain that everything in thee is simple and benevolent, and such as befits

00:38:22.568 --> 00:38:27.688
a social animal, one that cares not for thoughts about pleasure or sensual enjoyments at all,

00:38:27.848 --> 00:38:33.448
nor has any rivalry or envy and suspicion, or anything else for which thou wouldst blush

00:38:33.448 --> 00:38:40.208
if thou shouldst say that thou hadst it in thy mind. For the man who is such and no longer

00:38:40.208 --> 00:38:44.988
delays being among the number of the best, is like a priest and minister of the gods,

00:38:45.608 --> 00:38:51.128
using to the deity which is planted within him, which makes the man uncontaminated by

00:38:51.128 --> 00:38:57.268
pleasure, unharmed by any pain, untouched by any insult, feeling no wrong, a fighter

00:38:57.268 --> 00:39:03.608
in the noblest fight, one who cannot be overpowered by any passion, died deep with justice, accepting

00:39:03.608 --> 00:39:08.468
with all his soul everything which happens and is assigned to him as his position, and

00:39:08.468 --> 00:39:13.948
not even, nor yet without great necessity and for the general interest, imagining what

00:39:13.948 --> 00:39:20.788
another says or does or thinks. For it is only what belongs to himself that he makes

00:39:20.788 --> 00:39:26.888
the matter for his activity, and he constantly thinks of that which is allotted to himself

00:39:26.888 --> 00:39:32.288
out of the sum total of things, and he makes his own act fair, and he is persuaded that

00:39:32.288 --> 00:39:37.568
his own portion is good. For the lot which is assigned to each man is carried along with

00:39:37.568 --> 00:39:42.048
him and carries him along with it, and he remembers also that every rational animal

00:39:42.048 --> 00:39:48.128
is his kinsman, and that to care for all men is according to man's nature, and a man should

00:39:48.128 --> 00:39:54.188
hold on to the opinion not of all but of those only who confessedly live according to nature.

00:39:55.188 --> 00:39:59.568
But as to those who live not so, he always bears in mind what kind of men they are both

00:39:59.568 --> 00:40:06.388
at home and from home, both by night and by day, and what they are and with what men they

00:40:06.388 --> 00:40:11.388
live an impure life. Accordingly, he does not value at all the praise which comes from

00:40:11.388 --> 00:40:14.128
such men, since they are not even satisfied with themselves.

00:40:16.608 --> 00:40:23.168
5. Labour not unwillingly, nor without regard to common interest, nor without due consideration,

00:40:23.648 --> 00:40:29.808
nor with destruction, nor let studied ornaments set off thy thoughts, and be not either a

00:40:29.808 --> 00:40:35.768
man of many words or busy about too many things, and further let the deity which is in thee

00:40:35.768 --> 00:40:41.608
be the guardian of a living being, manly and of ripe age and engaged in matter political,

00:40:41.608 --> 00:40:47.188
and a Roman and a ruler who has taken his post like a man waiting for the signal which

00:40:47.188 --> 00:40:53.368
summons him from life and ready to go, having need neither of oath nor of any man's testimony.

00:40:54.248 --> 00:41:00.168
Be cheerful also, and seek not external help nor the tranquillity which others give. A

00:41:00.168 --> 00:41:03.268
man must stand erect, not be kept erect by others.

00:41:06.428 --> 00:41:13.788
6. If thou findest in human life anything better than justice, truth, temperance, fortitude,

00:41:14.128 --> 00:41:18.948
and in a word anything better than thy own mind's self-satisfaction in the things which

00:41:18.948 --> 00:41:23.568
it enables thee to do according to right reason and in the condition that is assigned to thee

00:41:23.568 --> 00:41:30.028
without thy own choice. If, I say, thou seest anything better than this, turn to it with

00:41:30.028 --> 00:41:35.968
all thy soul, and enjoy that which thou hast found to be the best. But if nothing appears

00:41:35.968 --> 00:41:40.608
to be better than the deity which is planted in thee, which has subjected to itself all

00:41:40.608 --> 00:41:46.668
thy appetites and carefully examines all the impressions, and as Socrates said, has detached

00:41:46.668 --> 00:41:51.548
itself from the persuasions of sense, and has submitted itself to the gods and cares

00:41:51.548 --> 00:41:57.288
for mankind, if thou findest everything else smaller and of less value than this, give

00:41:57.288 --> 00:42:03.248
place to nothing else. For if thou dost once diverge and incline to it, thou wilt no longer

00:42:03.248 --> 00:42:08.368
without distraction be able to give the preference to that good thing which is thy proper possession

00:42:08.368 --> 00:42:15.068
and thy own. For it is not right that anything of any other kind, such as praise from the

00:42:15.068 --> 00:42:20.008
many, or power, or enjoyment of pleasure, should come into competition with that which

00:42:20.008 --> 00:42:26.588
is rationally and politically or practically good. All these things, even though they may

00:42:26.588 --> 00:42:32.688
seem to adapt themselves to the better things, in a small degree, obtain the superiority

00:42:32.688 --> 00:42:39.208
all at once and carry us away. But do thou, I say, simply and freely choose the better

00:42:39.208 --> 00:42:46.048
and hold to it. But that which is useful is better. Well then, if it is only useful to

00:42:46.048 --> 00:42:51.008
thee as a rational being, keep to it. But if it is only useful to thee as an animal,

00:42:51.308 --> 00:42:56.568
say so and maintain thy judgment without arrogance. Only take care that thou makest the inquiry

00:42:57.108 --> 00:42:58.488
by a sure method.

00:43:00.708 --> 00:43:07.468
7. Never value anything as profitable to thyself which shall compel thee to break thy promise.

00:43:08.228 --> 00:43:13.968
To lose thy self-respect, to hate any man, to suspect, to curse, to act the hypocrite,

00:43:14.508 --> 00:43:20.228
to desire anything which needs walls and curtains. For he who has preferred to everything else

00:43:20.228 --> 00:43:25.948
of his own intelligence and the demon and the worship of its excellence acts no tragic

00:43:25.948 --> 00:43:31.688
part, does not groan, will not need either solitude or much company. And what is chief

00:43:31.688 --> 00:43:37.948
of all, he will live without either pursuing or flying from death. But whether for a longer

00:43:37.948 --> 00:43:44.048
or a shorter time he shall have the soul enclosed in the body, he cares not at all. For even

00:43:44.048 --> 00:43:48.928
if he must depart immediately, he will go as readily as if he were going to do anything

00:43:48.928 --> 00:43:54.668
else which can be done with decency and order. Taking care of this only all through life,

00:43:55.848 --> 00:44:00.828
that his thoughts turn not away from anything which belongs to an intelligent animal and

00:44:00.828 --> 00:44:02.468
a member of a civil community.

00:44:04.168 --> 00:44:09.808
8. In the mind of one who is chastened and purified, thou wilt find no corrupt matter,

00:44:10.028 --> 00:44:15.688
no impurity, nor any sore skinned over. Nor is his life incomplete when fate overtakes

00:44:15.688 --> 00:44:20.608
him, as one may say of an actor who leaves the stage before ending and finishing the

00:44:20.608 --> 00:44:27.108
play. Besides, there is in him nothing servile, nor affected, nor too closely bound to other

00:44:27.108 --> 00:44:32.868
things, nor yet detached from other things. Nothing worthy of blame, nothing which seeks

00:44:32.868 --> 00:44:33.948
a hiding place.

00:44:35.348 --> 00:44:42.068
9. Reverence the faculty which produces opinion. On this faculty it entirely depends whether

00:44:42.068 --> 00:44:47.868
there shall exist in their ruling part any opinion inconsistent with nature and the constitution

00:44:47.868 --> 00:44:53.268
of the rational animal. And this faculty promises freedom from hasty judgment and friendship

00:44:53.268 --> 00:44:55.748
towards men, and obedience to the gods.

00:44:56.828 --> 00:45:03.288
10. Throwing away then all things, hold to these only which are few, and besides bear

00:45:03.288 --> 00:45:08.648
in mind that every man lives only his present time, which is an indivisible point, and that

00:45:08.648 --> 00:45:14.608
all the rest of his life is either past or it is uncertain. Short then is the time which

00:45:14.608 --> 00:45:19.748
every man lives, and small the nook of the earth where he lives, and short too the longest

00:45:19.748 --> 00:45:25.408
posthumous fame, and even this only continued by a succession of poor human beings who will

00:45:25.408 --> 00:45:30.728
very soon die, and who know not even themselves, much less him who died long ago.

00:45:32.568 --> 00:45:37.328
11. To the aides which have been mentioned, let this one still be added. Make for thyself

00:45:37.328 --> 00:45:42.768
a definition or description of the thing which is presented to thee, so as to see distinctly

00:45:42.768 --> 00:45:49.348
what kind of a thing it is in its substance, in its nudity, in its complete entirety, and

00:45:49.348 --> 00:45:55.008
tell thyself its proper name, and the names of the things of which it has been compounded,

00:45:55.028 --> 00:46:00.508
and into which it will be resolved. For nothing is so productive of elevation of mind as to

00:46:00.508 --> 00:46:04.428
be able to examine methodically and truly every object which is presented to thee in

00:46:04.428 --> 00:46:10.508
life, and always to look at things so as to see at the same time what kind of universe

00:46:10.508 --> 00:46:15.588
this is, and what kind of use everything performs in it, and what value everything has with

00:46:15.588 --> 00:46:20.748
reference to the whole, and what with reference to man, who is a citizen of the highest city,

00:46:21.008 --> 00:46:26.928
of which all other cities are like families, what each thing is, and of what it is composed,

00:46:27.368 --> 00:46:31.528
and how long it is the nature of this thing to endure which now makes an impression on

00:46:31.528 --> 00:46:38.748
me, and what virtue I have need of with respect to it, such as gentleness, manliness, truth,

00:46:39.108 --> 00:46:45.488
fidelity, simplicity, contentment and the rest. Wherefore on every occasion a man should

00:46:45.488 --> 00:46:51.428
say, this comes from God, and this is according to the appointment and spinning of the thread

00:46:51.428 --> 00:46:56.968
of destiny, and such like coincidence and chance, and this is from one of the same stock,

00:46:56.968 --> 00:47:02.288
and a kinsman and partner, one who knows not, however, what is according to his nature.

00:47:03.268 --> 00:47:08.608
But I know for this reason I behave towards him according to the natural law of fellowship

00:47:08.608 --> 00:47:14.088
with benevolence and justice. At the same time, however, in things indifferent I attempt

00:47:14.088 --> 00:47:15.688
to ascertain the value of each.

00:47:17.268 --> 00:47:24.188
12. If thou workest at that which is before thee, following right reasons seriously, vigorously,

00:47:24.188 --> 00:47:28.548
calmly, without allowing anything else to distract thee, but keeping thy divine part

00:47:28.548 --> 00:47:34.848
pure, as if thou shouldst be bound to give it back immediately, if thou holdest to this,

00:47:35.288 --> 00:47:40.048
expecting nothing, fearing nothing, but satisfied with thy present activity according to nature,

00:47:40.508 --> 00:47:45.288
and with heroic truth in every word and sound which thou utterest, thou wilt live happy,

00:47:45.428 --> 00:47:48.068
and there is no man who is able to prevent this.

00:47:49.968 --> 00:47:55.908
13. As physicians have always their instruments and knives ready for cases which suddenly

00:47:55.908 --> 00:48:00.488
require their skill, so do thou have principles ready for the understanding of things divine

00:48:00.488 --> 00:48:05.508
and human, and doing everything, even the smallest, with a recollection of the bond

00:48:05.508 --> 00:48:11.988
which unites the divine and human to one another, for neither wilt thou do anything well which

00:48:11.988 --> 00:48:17.948
pertains to man without at the same time having a reference to things divine, nor the contrary.

00:48:19.208 --> 00:48:25.728
14. No longer wander at hazard, for neither wilt thou read thy own memoirs, nor the acts

00:48:25.728 --> 00:48:30.208
of the ancient Romans and the Hellens, and the selections from books which thou wast

00:48:30.208 --> 00:48:36.528
reserving for thy old age. Hasten then to the end which thou hast before thee, and throwing

00:48:36.528 --> 00:48:43.488
away idle hopes, come to thy own aid, if thou carest at all for thyself, while it is in thy power.

00:48:45.208 --> 00:48:51.828
15. They know not how many things are signified by the words stealing, sewing, buying, keeping

00:48:51.828 --> 00:48:57.528
quiet, seeing what ought to be done, for this is not affected by the eyes, but by another

00:48:57.528 --> 00:48:58.508
kind of vision.

00:49:00.168 --> 00:49:07.588
16. Body, soul, intelligence. To the body belong sensations, to the soul appetites,

00:49:07.588 --> 00:49:14.168
to the intelligence principles. To receive the impressions of forms by means of appearances

00:49:14.168 --> 00:49:20.288
belongs even to animals, to be pulled by the strings of desires belongs both to wild beasts

00:49:20.288 --> 00:49:27.148
and to men who have made themselves into women, and to a philaris and a nero, and to have the

00:49:27.148 --> 00:49:36.048
intelligence that guides to the things which appear suitable belongs also to those who do not

00:49:36.048 --> 00:49:43.008
do good deeds when they have shut the doors. If then everything else is common to all that

00:49:43.008 --> 00:49:48.728
I have mentioned, there remains that which is peculiar to the good man, to be pleased

00:49:48.728 --> 00:49:54.748
and content with what happens, and with the thread which is spun for him, and not to defile

00:49:54.748 --> 00:49:59.408
the divinity which is planted in his breast, nor disturb it by a crowd of images, but to

00:49:59.408 --> 00:50:04.328
preserve it tranquil, following it obediently as a god, neither saying anything contrary

00:50:04.328 --> 00:50:10.168
to the truth, nor doing anything contrary to justice. And if all men refuse to believe

00:50:10.168 --> 00:50:15.828
that he lives a simple, modest and contented life, he is neither angry with any of them,

00:50:15.988 --> 00:50:20.928
nor does he deviate from the way which leads to the end of life, to which a man ought to

00:50:20.928 --> 00:50:25.408
come pure, tranquil, ready to depart, and without any compulsion perfectly reconciled

00:50:25.828 --> 00:50:26.448
to his lot.

00:51:06.578 --> 00:51:12.278
That which rules within, when it is according to Nature, is so affected with respect to

00:51:12.278 --> 00:51:18.278
the events which happen that it always easily adapts itself to that which is possible and

00:51:18.278 --> 00:51:24.098
is presented to it, for it requires no definite material, but it moves towards its purpose

00:51:24.098 --> 00:51:29.978
under certain conditions however, and it makes a material for itself out of that which opposes

00:51:29.978 --> 00:51:36.858
it as fire lays hold of what falls into it, but which a small light would have been extinguished.

00:51:36.858 --> 00:51:42.858
But when the fire is strong, it soon appropriates to itself the matter which is heaped on it,

00:51:42.918 --> 00:51:49.838
and consumes it, and rises higher by means of this very material. Let no act be done

00:51:49.838 --> 00:51:57.018
without a purpose, nor otherwise than according to the perfect principles of art. Men seek

00:51:57.018 --> 00:52:02.198
retreats for themselves, houses in the country, seashores, and the mountains,

00:52:02.778 --> 00:52:09.198
and thou too art wont to desire such things very much. But this is altogether a mark of the most

00:52:09.198 --> 00:52:16.198
common sort of men. For it is in thy power whenever thou shalt choose to retire into thyself. For

00:52:16.198 --> 00:52:21.998
nowhere, either with more quiet or more freedom from trouble, does a man retire than into his

00:52:21.998 --> 00:52:28.318
own soul, particularly when he has within him such thoughts that by looking into them he is

00:52:28.318 --> 00:52:33.478
immediately in perfect tranquillity. And I affirm that tranquillity is nothing else than the good

00:52:33.478 --> 00:52:39.398
ordering of the mind. Constantly, then, give to thyself this retreat, and renew thyself,

00:52:40.258 --> 00:52:46.098
and let thy principles be brief and fundamental, which, as soon as thou shalt recur to them,

00:52:46.598 --> 00:52:52.418
will be sufficient to cleanse the soul completely, and to send thee back free from all discontent

00:52:52.418 --> 00:53:00.258
with the things to which thou returnest. For with what art thou discontented? With the badness of

00:53:00.258 --> 00:53:07.298
men? Recall to thy mind this conclusion, that rational animals exist for one another, and that

00:53:07.298 --> 00:53:14.578
to endure is a part of justice, and that men do wrong involuntarily. And consider how many already,

00:53:14.578 --> 00:53:21.078
after mutual enmity, suspicion, hatred, and fighting, have been stretched dead,

00:53:21.638 --> 00:53:29.918
reduced to ashes, and be quiet at last. But perhaps thou art dissatisfied with that which

00:53:29.918 --> 00:53:36.758
is assigned to thee out of the universe. Recall to thy recollection this alternative. Either

00:53:36.758 --> 00:53:44.078
there is providence or atoms, fortuitous concurrence of things, or remember the arguments by which it

00:53:44.078 --> 00:53:50.758
has been proved that the world is a kind of political community, and be quiet at last. But

00:53:50.758 --> 00:53:57.858
perhaps corporeal things will still fasten upon thee. Consider then further that the mind mingles

00:53:57.858 --> 00:54:03.958
not with the breath, whether moving gently or violently, when it has once drawn itself apart,

00:54:04.158 --> 00:54:10.498
and discovered its own power. And think also of all that thou hast heard and assented to about

00:54:10.498 --> 00:54:17.378
pain and pleasure, and be quiet at last. But perhaps the desire of the thing called fame

00:54:17.378 --> 00:54:24.058
will torment thee. See how soon everything is forgotten, and look at the chaos of infinite

00:54:24.058 --> 00:54:31.118
time on each side of the present, and the emptiness of applause, and the changeableness and want of

00:54:31.118 --> 00:54:40.478
judgment in those who pretend to give praise, and the narrowness of the space within which it is

00:54:40.478 --> 00:54:47.238
for the whole earth is a point, and how small a nook in it is this thy dwelling place, and how

00:54:47.238 --> 00:54:54.158
few are there in it, and what kind of people are they who will praise thee. This then remains.

00:54:54.998 --> 00:55:02.858
Remember to retire into this little territory of thy own, and above all do not distract or strain

00:55:02.858 --> 00:55:13.138
thyself, but be free at look and things as a man, as a human being, as a citizen, as a mortal.

00:55:14.118 --> 00:55:20.498
But among the things readiest to thy hand to which thou shalt return, let there be these which are

00:55:20.498 --> 00:55:27.178
two. One is that things do not touch the soul, for they are external and remain immovable,

00:55:27.178 --> 00:55:33.578
but our perturbations come only from the opinion which is within. The other is that all these

00:55:33.578 --> 00:55:40.398
things which thou seest change immediately and will no longer be, and constantly bear in mind

00:55:40.398 --> 00:55:46.138
how many of these changes thou hast already witnessed. The universe is transformation,

00:55:46.858 --> 00:55:55.678
life is opinion. If our intellectual part is common, the reason also, in respect of which

00:55:55.678 --> 00:56:02.758
we are rational beings, is common. If this is so, common also is the reason which commands us what

00:56:02.758 --> 00:56:11.078
to do and what not to do. If this is so, there is a common law also. If this is so, we are fellow

00:56:11.078 --> 00:56:19.138
citizens. If this is so, we are members of some political community. If this is so, the world is

00:56:19.138 --> 00:56:25.418
in a manner, a state. For of what other common political community will anyone say that the whole

00:56:25.418 --> 00:56:32.078
human race are members. And from thence, from this common political community comes also our

00:56:32.078 --> 00:56:39.018
very intellectual faculty and reasoning faculty and our capacity for law, or whence do they come.

00:56:39.758 --> 00:56:46.038
For as my earthly part is a portion given to me from certain earth, and that which is watery from

00:56:46.038 --> 00:56:52.138
another element, and that which is hot and fiery from some peculiar source, for nothing comes out

00:56:52.138 --> 00:56:58.658
of that which is nothing, as nothing also returns to nonexistence. So also the intellectual part

00:56:58.658 --> 00:57:06.318
comes from some source. Death is such as generation is, a mystery of nature, a composition out of the

00:57:06.318 --> 00:57:12.978
same elements and a decomposition into the same, and altogether not a thing of which any man should

00:57:12.978 --> 00:57:20.318
be ashamed. For it is not contrary to the nature of a reasonable animal, and not contrary to the

00:57:20.318 --> 00:57:28.698
reason of our constitution. It is natural that these things should be done by such persons. It is

00:57:28.698 --> 00:57:35.158
a matter of necessity, and if a man will not have it so, he will not allow the fig tree to have juice.

00:57:36.338 --> 00:57:43.478
But by all means bear this in mind, that within a very short time both thou and he will be dead,

00:57:43.478 --> 00:57:51.138
and soon not even your names will be left behind. Take away thy opinion, and then there is taken

00:57:51.138 --> 00:57:57.278
away the complaint I have been harmed. Take away the complaint I have been harmed, and the harm is

00:57:57.278 --> 00:58:04.678
taken away. That which does not make a man worse than he was, also does not make his life worse,

00:58:05.738 --> 00:58:13.098
nor does it harm him either from without or from within. The nature of that which is universally

00:58:13.098 --> 00:58:21.578
useful has been compelled to do this. Consider that everything which happens, happens justly,

00:58:21.978 --> 00:58:28.838
and if thou observest carefully, thou wilt find it to be so. I do not say only with respect to the

00:58:28.838 --> 00:58:34.918
continuity of the series of things, but with respect to what is just, and as if it were done

00:58:34.918 --> 00:58:41.398
by one who assigns to each thing its value. Observe then that thou hast begun, and whatever

00:58:41.398 --> 00:58:47.938
thou doest, do it in conjunction with this, the being good, and in the sense in which a man is

00:58:47.938 --> 00:58:54.938
properly understood to be good. Keep to this in every action. Do not have such an opinion of things

00:58:54.938 --> 00:59:02.398
as he has who does thee wrong, or such as he wishes thee to have, but look at them as they are in truth.

00:59:03.778 --> 00:59:09.578
A man should always have these two rules in readiness, the one to do only whatever the reason

00:59:09.578 --> 00:59:16.638
of the ruling and legislating faculty may suggest for the use of men, the other to change thy opinion,

00:59:17.138 --> 00:59:22.778
if there is anyone at hand who sets thee right and moves thee from any opinion. But this change

00:59:22.778 --> 00:59:28.098
of opinion must proceed only from a certain persuasion, as of what is just or of common

00:59:28.098 --> 00:59:35.798
advantage and the like, not because it appears pleasant or brings reputation. Hast thou reason?

00:59:35.798 --> 00:59:44.418
I have. Why then dost not thou use it? For if this does its own work, what else dost thou wish?

00:59:45.598 --> 00:59:50.538
Thou hast existed as a part. Thou shalt disappear in that which produced thee,

00:59:50.698 --> 00:59:56.038
but rather thou shalt be received back into its seminal principle by transmutation.

00:59:57.678 --> 01:00:05.218
Many grains of frankincense on the same altar. One falls before, another falls after. But it

01:00:05.218 --> 01:00:13.278
makes no difference. Within ten days thou wilt seem a god to those to whom thou art now a beast

01:00:13.278 --> 01:00:21.098
and an ape, if thou wilt return to thy principles and to worship of reason. Do not act as if thou

01:00:21.098 --> 01:00:28.698
wert going to live ten thousand years. Death hangs over thee. While thou livest, while it is in thy

01:00:28.698 --> 01:00:36.838
power, be good. How much trouble he avoids who does not look to see what his neighbor says or

01:00:36.838 --> 01:00:44.518
does or thinks, but only to what he does himself, that it may be just and pure. Or, as Agathon says,

01:00:45.098 --> 01:00:51.198
look not round at the depraved morals of others, but run straight along the line without deviating

01:00:51.198 --> 01:00:57.898
from it. He who has a vehement desire for posthumous fame does not consider that every one of those who

01:00:57.898 --> 01:01:04.398
remember him will himself also die very soon. Then again also they who have succeeded them,

01:01:04.818 --> 01:01:08.918
until the whole remembrance shall have been extinguished as it is transmitted through men

01:01:08.918 --> 01:01:15.458
who foolishly admire and perish. Suppose that those who will remember are even immortal,

01:01:15.918 --> 01:01:21.978
and that the remembrance will be immortal. What then is this to thee? And I say not what is it

01:01:21.978 --> 01:01:28.418
to the dead, but what is it to the living? What is praise, except indeed so far as it has a certain

01:01:28.418 --> 01:01:36.918
utility? For thou now rejectest unseasonably the gift of nature, clinging to something else.

01:01:37.418 --> 01:01:43.418
Everything which is in any way beautiful is beautiful in itself, and terminates in itself,

01:01:43.838 --> 01:01:50.158
not having praise as a part of itself. Neither worse than nor better is a thing made by being

01:01:50.158 --> 01:01:56.378
praised. I affirm this also of the things which are called beautiful by the vulgar, for example,

01:01:56.658 --> 01:02:01.718
material things and works of art. That which is really beautiful has no need of anything,

01:02:02.498 --> 01:02:09.278
not more than law, not more than truth, not more than benevolence or modesty. Which of these things

01:02:09.278 --> 01:02:15.998
is beautiful because it is praised, or spoiled by being blamed? Is such a thing as an emerald

01:02:15.998 --> 01:02:23.438
made worse than it was, if it is not praised? Or gold, ivory, purple, a lyre, a little knife,

01:02:23.498 --> 01:02:31.578
a flower, a shrub? If souls continue to exist, how does the air contain them from eternity? But how

01:02:31.578 --> 01:02:37.058
does the earth contain the bodies of those who have been buried from time so remote? For as here

01:02:37.058 --> 01:02:42.578
the mutation of these bodies, after a certain continuance, whatever it may be, and their

01:02:42.578 --> 01:02:48.098
solution make room for other dead bodies. So the souls which are removed into the air after

01:02:48.098 --> 01:02:53.998
subsisting for some time are transmuted and diffuse, and assume a fiery nature by being

01:02:53.998 --> 01:02:59.918
received into the seminal intelligence of the universe. And in this way make room for the fresh

01:02:59.918 --> 01:03:05.678
souls which come to dwell there. And this is the answer which a man might give on the hypothesis

01:03:05.678 --> 01:03:11.218
of souls continuing to exist. But we must not only think of the number of bodies which are thus

01:03:11.218 --> 01:03:18.458
buried, but also of the number of animals which are daily eaten by us and the other animals. For

01:03:18.458 --> 01:03:24.058
what a number is consumed, and thus in a manner buried in the bodies of those who feed on them,

01:03:24.458 --> 01:03:30.938
and nevertheless this earth receives them by reason of the changes of these bodies into blood,

01:03:31.618 --> 01:03:38.558
and the transformations into the aerial or the fiery element. What is the investigation into the

01:03:38.558 --> 01:03:44.538
length of the matter? The division into that which is material, and that which is the cause

01:03:44.538 --> 01:03:51.618
of form, the formal. Do not be whirled about, but in every movement have respect to justice,

01:03:52.058 --> 01:03:57.918
and on the occasion of every impression maintain the faculty of comprehension or understanding.

01:03:59.018 --> 01:04:05.798
Everything harmonizes with me which is harmonious to thee, O universe. Nothing for me is too early

01:04:05.798 --> 01:04:11.598
nor too late which is in due time for thee. Everything is fruit to me which thy seasons

01:04:11.598 --> 01:04:19.098
bring, O nature. From thee are all things, in thee are all things, to thee all things return.

01:04:20.098 --> 01:04:29.318
The poet says, Dear city of sea-crops, and wilt not thou say, Dear city of Zeus. Occupy thyself

01:04:29.318 --> 01:04:35.718
with few things, says the philosopher, if thou wouldst be tranquil. But consider if it would not

01:04:35.718 --> 01:04:41.258
be better to say, Do what is necessary, and whatever the reason of the animal which is

01:04:41.258 --> 01:04:47.418
naturally social requires, and as it requires. For this brings not only the tranquility which

01:04:47.418 --> 01:04:53.518
comes from doing well, but also that which comes from doing few things. For the greatest part of

01:04:53.518 --> 01:04:59.658
what we say and do being unnecessary, if a man takes this away, he will have more leisure and

01:04:59.658 --> 01:05:06.018
less uneasiness. Accordingly, on every occasion a man should ask himself, Is this one of the

01:05:06.018 --> 01:05:12.238
unnecessary things? Now a man should take away not only unnecessary acts but also unnecessary

01:05:12.238 --> 01:05:19.658
thoughts, for thus superfluous acts will not follow after. Try how the life of a good man

01:05:19.658 --> 01:05:26.138
suits thee, the life of him who is satisfied with his portion out of the whole and satisfied

01:05:26.138 --> 01:05:34.678
with his own just acts and benevolent disposition. Hast thou seen those things? Look also at these.

01:05:35.098 --> 01:05:43.038
Do not disturb thyself. Make thyself all simplicity. Does anyone do wrong? It is to himself that he

01:05:43.038 --> 01:05:50.418
does wrong. Has anything happened to thee? Well, out of the universe from the beginning, everything

01:05:50.418 --> 01:05:57.978
which happens has been apportioned and spun out to thee. In a word, thy life is short. Thou must

01:05:57.978 --> 01:06:06.598
turn to profit the present by the aid of reason and justice. Be sober in thy relaxation. Are there

01:06:06.598 --> 01:06:13.578
it is a well-arranged universe or a chaos huddled together, but still a universe? But can a certain

01:06:13.578 --> 01:06:20.938
order subsist in thee and disorder in all? And this, too, when all things are so separated and

01:06:20.938 --> 01:06:30.038
diffused and sympathetic. A black character, a womanish character, a stubborn character, bestial,

01:06:30.478 --> 01:06:40.338
childish, annual, stupid, counterfeit, scurrilous, fraudulent, tyrannical. If he is a stranger to the

01:06:40.338 --> 01:06:45.618
universe who does not know what is in it, no less is he a stranger who does not know what is going

01:06:45.618 --> 01:06:53.898
on in it. He is a runaway who flies from social reason. He is blind who shuts the eyes of the

01:06:53.898 --> 01:06:59.658
understanding. He is poor who has need of another and has not from himself all things which are

01:06:59.658 --> 01:07:06.518
useful for life. He is an abscess on the universe who withdraws and separates himself from the reason

01:07:06.518 --> 01:07:11.798
of our common nature through being displeased with the things which happen. For the same nature

01:07:11.798 --> 01:07:18.338
produces this and has produced thee, too. He is a piece rent asunder from the state who tears his

01:07:18.338 --> 01:07:26.058
own soul from that of reasonable animals, which is one. The one is a philosopher without a tunic,

01:07:26.358 --> 01:07:33.298
and the other without a book. Here is another half-naked. Bread I have not, he says, and I

01:07:33.298 --> 01:07:41.398
reason, and I do not get the means of living out of my learning, and I abide by my reason.

01:07:42.998 --> 01:07:49.198
Love the art, poor as it may be, which thou hast learned, and be content with it, and pass

01:07:49.198 --> 01:07:55.258
through the rest of life like one who has entrusted to the gods with his whole soul all that he has,

01:07:55.258 --> 01:08:04.198
making himself neither the tyrant nor the slave of any man. Consider, for example, the times of

01:08:04.198 --> 01:08:10.638
Vespasian. Thou wilt see all these things, people marrying, bringing up children, sick, dying,

01:08:11.038 --> 01:08:17.378
warring, feasting, trafficking, cultivating the ground, flattering, obstinately arrogant, suspecting,

01:08:17.498 --> 01:08:22.678
plotting, wishing for some to die, grumbling about the present, loving, heaping up treasure,

01:08:22.678 --> 01:08:29.538
desiring consulship, kingly power. Well, then, that life of these people no longer exists at all.

01:08:30.398 --> 01:08:37.518
Again, removed to the time of Trajan, again all is the same. Their life, too, is gone. In like

01:08:37.518 --> 01:08:43.878
manner, view also the other epics of time and of whole nations, and see how many, after great

01:08:43.878 --> 01:08:49.978
efforts, soon fell and were resolved into the elements. But chiefly thou shouldst think of

01:08:49.978 --> 01:08:55.898
those whom thou hast thyself known distracting themselves about idle things, neglecting to do

01:08:55.898 --> 01:09:00.578
what was in accordance with their proper constitution, and to hold firmly to this,

01:09:00.678 --> 01:09:06.358
and to be content with it. And herein it is necessary to remember that the attention given

01:09:06.358 --> 01:09:13.678
to everything has its proper value and proportion. For thus thou wilt not be dissatisfied if thou

01:09:13.678 --> 01:09:20.018
applies thyself to smaller matters no further than is fit. The words which were formerly familiar

01:09:20.018 --> 01:09:27.318
are now antiquated. So also the names of those who were famed of old are now in a manner antiquated.

01:09:27.758 --> 01:09:35.118
Camillus, Caeso, Volasus, Leonidas, and a little after also Scipio and Cato, then Augustus, then

01:09:35.118 --> 01:09:42.078
also Hadrianus and Antoninus. For all things soon pass away and become a mere tale. In complete

01:09:42.078 --> 01:09:49.278
oblivion soon buries them. And I say this of those who have shown in a wondrous way. For the rest,

01:09:49.878 --> 01:09:55.398
as soon as they have breathed out their breath, they are gone and no man speaks of them. And to

01:09:55.398 --> 01:10:03.638
conclude the matter, what is even an eternal remembrance? A mere nothing. What then is that

01:10:03.638 --> 01:10:10.718
about which we ought to employ our serious pains? This one thing, thoughts just and acts social,

01:10:10.718 --> 01:10:17.058
and words which never lie, and a disposition which gladly accepts all that happens as necessary,

01:10:17.558 --> 01:10:27.198
as usual, as flowing from a principle and a source of the same kind. Willingly give thyself up to

01:10:27.198 --> 01:10:33.498
Clotho, one of the fates, allowing her to spin thy thread into whatever things she pleases.

01:10:35.258 --> 01:10:40.478
Everything is only for a day, both that which remembers and that which is remembered.

01:10:42.638 --> 01:10:47.818
Observe constantly that all things take place by change, and accustom thyself to consider that

01:10:47.818 --> 01:10:53.158
the nature of the universe loves nothing so much as to change the things which are, and to make

01:10:53.158 --> 01:10:59.458
new things like them. For everything that exists is in a manner the seed of that which will be,

01:10:59.458 --> 01:11:05.498
but thou art thinking only of seeds which are cast into the earth or into a womb. But this is a

01:11:05.498 --> 01:11:12.898
very vulgar notion. Thou wilt soon die, and thou art not yet simple, not free from perturbations,

01:11:13.278 --> 01:11:19.618
not without suspicion of being hurt by external things, nor kindly disposed toward all. Nor dost

01:11:19.618 --> 01:11:28.038
thou yet place wisdom only in acting justly. Examine men's ruling principles, even those of

01:11:28.038 --> 01:11:36.278
wise, what kind of things they avoid and what kind they pursue. What is evil to thee does not subsist

01:11:36.278 --> 01:11:42.518
in the ruling principle of another, nor yet in any turning and mutation of thy corporeal covering.

01:11:43.818 --> 01:11:49.898
Where is it then? It is in that part of thee in which subsists the power of forming opinions

01:11:49.898 --> 01:11:57.798
about evils. Let this power then not form such opinions, and all as well. And if that which is

01:11:57.798 --> 01:12:05.498
nearest to it, the poor body, is cut, burnt, filled with matter and rottenness, nevertheless,

01:12:05.998 --> 01:12:11.598
let the part which forms opinions about these things be quiet. That is, let it judge that

01:12:11.598 --> 01:12:17.458
nothing is either bad or good which can happen equally to the bad man and the good. For that

01:12:17.458 --> 01:12:23.418
which happens equally to him who lives contrary to nature, and to him who lives according to nature,

01:12:23.418 --> 01:12:30.958
is neither according to nature nor contrary to nature. Constantly regard the universe as one

01:12:30.958 --> 01:12:38.058
living being, having one substance and one soul, and observe how all things have reference to one

01:12:38.058 --> 01:12:44.458
perception, the perception of this one living being, and how all things act with one movement,

01:12:45.258 --> 01:12:51.558
and how all things are the cooperative causes of all things which exist. Observe, too, the continuous

01:12:51.558 --> 01:12:59.478
spinning of the thread and the contextual of the web. Thou art a little soul bearing about a corpse,

01:13:00.058 --> 01:13:06.298
as Epictetus used to say. It is no evil for things to undergo change, and no good for things to

01:13:06.298 --> 01:13:12.858
subsist in consequence of change. Time is like a river made up of the events which happened,

01:13:13.318 --> 01:13:19.578
and a violent stream. For as soon as a thing has been seen, it is carried away, and another comes

01:13:19.578 --> 01:13:27.198
in its place, and this will be carried away, too. Everything which happens is as familiar and well

01:13:27.198 --> 01:13:33.318
known as the rose in spring and the fruit in summer. For such is disease, and death, and calumny,

01:13:33.518 --> 01:13:39.778
and treachery, and whatever else delights fools or vexes them. In the series of things, those

01:13:39.778 --> 01:13:45.598
which follow are always aptly fitted to those which have gone before. For this series is not

01:13:45.598 --> 01:13:52.438
a mere enumeration of disjointed things, which only has a necessary sequence, but it is a rational

01:13:52.438 --> 01:13:59.438
connection, and as all existing things are arranged together harmoniously, so the things which come

01:13:59.438 --> 01:14:06.098
into existence exhibit no mere succession but a certain wonderful relationship. Always remember

01:14:06.098 --> 01:14:15.458
the saying of Heraclitus that the death of earth is to become water, and the death of water is to

01:14:15.458 --> 01:14:22.578
become fire, and reversely. And think too of him who forgets whither the way leads, and that men

01:14:22.578 --> 01:14:27.798
quarrel with that with which they are most constantly in communion, the reason which

01:14:27.798 --> 01:14:33.678
governs the universe. And the things which they daily meet with seem to them strange,

01:14:34.318 --> 01:14:39.978
and consider that we ought not to act and speak as if we were asleep, for even in sleep we seem

01:14:39.978 --> 01:14:46.838
to act and speak, and that we ought not, like children who learn from their parents, simply to

01:14:46.838 --> 01:14:55.098
act and speak as we have been taught. If any God told thee that thou shalt die tomorrow, or certainly

01:14:55.098 --> 01:15:00.958
on the day after tomorrow, thou wouldst not care much whether it was on the third day or on the

01:15:01.498 --> 01:15:06.418
morrow, unless thou wast in the highest degree mean-spirited, for how small is the difference.

01:15:06.418 --> 01:15:13.738
So think, it is no great thing to die after as many years as thou canst name rather than tomorrow.

01:15:14.798 --> 01:15:19.918
Think continually how many physicians are dead after often contracting their eyebrows over the

01:15:19.918 --> 01:15:25.658
sick, and how many astrologers after predicting with great pretensions the deaths of others,

01:15:26.178 --> 01:15:32.978
and how many philosophers after endless discourses on death or immortality, how many heroes after

01:15:34.198 --> 01:15:39.558
and how many tyrants who have used their power over men's lives with terrible insolence as if

01:15:39.558 --> 01:15:46.758
they were immortal, and how many cities are entirely dead, so to speak, Helis and Pompeii

01:15:46.758 --> 01:15:54.598
and Herculaneum, and others innumerable. Add to the reckoning all whom thou hast known, one after

01:15:54.598 --> 01:16:01.218
another. One man, after burying another, has been laid out dead, and another buries him,

01:16:01.218 --> 01:16:08.938
and all this in a short time. To conclude, always observe how ephemeral and worthless human things

01:16:08.938 --> 01:16:15.758
are, and what was yesterday a little mucus, tomorrow will be a mummy or ashes. Pass then

01:16:15.758 --> 01:16:22.558
through this little space of time conformably to nature, and end thy journey in content, just as

01:16:22.558 --> 01:16:28.298
an olive falls off when it is ripe, blessing nature who produced it, and thanking the tree

01:16:28.298 --> 01:16:35.258
on which it grew. Be like the promontory against which the waves continually break,

01:16:35.758 --> 01:16:42.738
but it stands firm and tames the fury of the water around it. Unhappy am I, because this has

01:16:42.738 --> 01:16:49.818
happened to me. Not so. But happy am I, though this has happened to me, because I continue free

01:16:49.818 --> 01:16:56.118
from pain, neither crushed by the present nor fearing the future. For such a thing as this might

01:16:56.118 --> 01:17:01.278
have happened to every man, but every man would not have continued free from pain on such an

01:17:01.278 --> 01:17:08.938
occasion. Why, then, is that rather a misfortune than this a good fortune? And dost thou in all

01:17:08.938 --> 01:17:16.058
cases call that a man's misfortune, which is not a deviation from man's nature? And does a thing

01:17:16.058 --> 01:17:21.178
seem to thee to be a deviation from man's nature, when it is not contrary to the will of man's

01:17:21.178 --> 01:17:28.898
nature? Well, thou knowest the will of nature. Will then this which has happened prevent thee

01:17:28.898 --> 01:17:35.678
from being just, magnanimous, temperate, prudent, secure against inconsiderate opinions and

01:17:35.678 --> 01:17:41.578
falsehoods? Will it prevent thee from having modesty, freedom, and everything else, by the

01:17:41.578 --> 01:17:49.158
presence of which man's nature obtains all that is its own? Remember, too, in every occasion which

01:17:49.158 --> 01:17:56.078
leads thee to vexation to apply this principle, not that this is a misfortune, but that to bear

01:17:56.078 --> 01:18:03.238
it nobly is good fortune. It is a vulgar but still a useful help towards contempt of death to pass

01:18:03.238 --> 01:18:09.858
and review those who have tenaciously stuck to life. What more, then, have they gained than those

01:18:09.858 --> 01:18:17.598
who have died early? Certainly they lie in their tomb somewhere at last. Cadicianus, Fabius,

01:18:17.598 --> 01:18:23.698
Julianus, Lepidus, or anyone else like them, who have carried out many to be buried, and then were

01:18:23.698 --> 01:18:30.578
carried out themselves. Altogether the interval is small between birth and death. And consider,

01:18:30.858 --> 01:18:36.398
with how much trouble, and in company with what sort of people, and in what a feeble body this

01:18:36.398 --> 01:18:43.168
interval is laboriously passed, do not then consider life a thing of any value. For look to the

01:18:43.768 --> 01:18:50.608
behind thee, and to the time which is before thee, another boundless space. In this infinity, then,

01:18:50.608 --> 01:18:55.148
what is the difference between him who lives three days and him who lives three generations?

01:18:56.068 --> 01:19:03.248
Always run the short way. And the short way is the natural. Accordingly say and do everything in

01:19:03.248 --> 01:19:09.248
conformity with the soundest reason. For such a purpose frees a man from trouble and warfare,

01:19:09.248 --> 01:19:13.408
and all artifice, and ostentatious this way.

01:19:46.865 --> 01:19:53.405
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus.

01:20:00.305 --> 01:20:06.145
In the morning, when thou risest unwillingly, let this thought be present.

01:20:06.925 --> 01:20:10.065
I am rising to the work of a human being.

01:20:10.745 --> 01:20:16.805
Why, then, am I dissatisfied if I am going to do the things for which I exist,

01:20:17.185 --> 01:20:19.305
and for which I was brought into the world?

01:20:20.285 --> 01:20:25.525
Or have I been made for this, to lie in the bedclothes and keep myself warm?

01:20:26.645 --> 01:20:27.985
But this is more pleasant.

01:20:28.925 --> 01:20:35.125
Dost thou exist, then, to take thy pleasure, and not at all for action or exertion?

01:20:35.785 --> 01:20:41.865
Dost thou not see the little plants, the little birds, the ants, the spiders, the bees,

01:20:42.585 --> 01:20:46.385
working together to put in order their several parts of the universe?

01:20:47.025 --> 01:20:50.445
And art thou unwilling to do the work of a human being?

01:20:51.185 --> 01:20:55.265
And dost thou not make haste to do that which is according to thy nature?

01:20:56.565 --> 01:20:59.385
But it is necessary to take rest also.

01:21:00.365 --> 01:21:01.785
It is necessary.

01:21:02.345 --> 01:21:05.805
However, nature has fixed bounds to this too.

01:21:06.205 --> 01:21:09.345
She has fixed bounds both to eating and drinking.

01:21:10.005 --> 01:21:14.685
And yet thou goest beyond these bounds, beyond what is sufficient.

01:21:15.685 --> 01:21:21.165
Yet in thy acts it is not so, but thou stoppest short of what thou canst do.

01:21:21.945 --> 01:21:24.225
So thou lovest not thyself.

01:21:24.625 --> 01:21:29.005
For if thou didst, thou wouldst love thy nature and her will.

01:21:30.045 --> 01:21:37.685
But those who love their several arts exhaust themselves in working at them, unwashed, and without food.

01:21:38.785 --> 01:21:44.445
But thou valuest thy known nature less than the turner values the turning art,

01:21:44.845 --> 01:21:49.645
or the dancer the dancing art, or the lover of money values his money,

01:21:50.305 --> 01:21:53.025
or the vainglorious man his little glory.

01:21:53.665 --> 01:21:57.825
And such men, when they have a violent affection to a thing,

01:21:58.385 --> 01:22:05.005
choose neither to eat nor to sleep, rather than to perfect the things which they care for.

01:22:05.725 --> 01:22:12.785
But are the acts which concern society more vile in thy eyes, and less worthy of thy labor?

01:22:14.485 --> 01:22:22.485
How easy it is to repel and to wipe away every impression which is troublesome or unsuitable,

01:22:22.645 --> 01:22:26.185
and immediately to be in all tranquillity.

01:22:27.825 --> 01:22:33.005
Judge every word and deed which are according to nature to be fit for thee,

01:22:33.445 --> 01:22:37.765
and be not diverted by the blame which follows from any people,

01:22:38.225 --> 01:22:39.605
nor by their words.

01:22:40.225 --> 01:22:46.245
But if a thing is good to be done or said, do not consider it unworthy of thee.

01:22:47.005 --> 01:22:53.705
For those persons have their peculiar leading principle, and follow their peculiar movement.

01:22:54.345 --> 01:22:58.285
Which things do not thou regard, but go straight on,

01:22:58.865 --> 01:23:05.145
following thy own nature and the common nature, and the way of both is one.

01:23:06.965 --> 01:23:13.125
I go through the things which happen according to nature, and I shall fall and rest,

01:23:13.585 --> 01:23:18.505
breathing out my breath into that element out of which I daily draw it in,

01:23:18.505 --> 01:23:23.605
and falling upon that earth out of which my father collected the seed,

01:23:24.185 --> 01:23:27.505
and my mother the blood, and my nurse the milk,

01:23:28.165 --> 01:23:33.165
out of which during so many years I have been supplied with food and drink,

01:23:33.765 --> 01:23:39.065
which bears me when I tread on it and abuse it for so many purposes.

01:23:40.825 --> 01:23:45.165
Thou sayest, men cannot admire the sharpness of thy wits.

01:23:45.845 --> 01:23:50.645
Be it so, but there are many other things of which thou canst not say,

01:23:51.025 --> 01:23:53.325
I am not formed for them by nature.

01:23:54.485 --> 01:23:58.565
Show those qualities, then, which are altogether in thy power,

01:23:59.245 --> 01:24:05.325
sincerity, gravity, endurance of labour, aversion to pleasure,

01:24:06.105 --> 01:24:12.645
contentment with thy portion and with few things, benevolence, frankness,

01:24:13.155 --> 01:24:18.345
no love of superfluity, freedom from trifling magnanimity.

01:24:19.185 --> 01:24:24.165
Dost thou not see how many qualities thou art immediately able to exhibit,

01:24:24.745 --> 01:24:29.345
in which there is no excuse of natural incapacity and unfitness,

01:24:29.925 --> 01:24:34.285
and yet thou still remainest voluntarily below the mark?

01:24:34.985 --> 01:24:39.545
Or art thou compelled through being defectively furnished by nature

01:24:39.545 --> 01:24:46.505
to murmur and to be stingy and to flatter and to find fault with thy poor body,

01:24:47.365 --> 01:24:53.785
and to try to please men and to make great display and to be restless in thy mind?

01:24:54.965 --> 01:25:00.665
No, by the gods, but thou mightest have been delivered from these things long ago.

01:25:01.725 --> 01:25:08.625
Only if in truth thou canst be charged with being rather slow and dull of comprehension,

01:25:08.625 --> 01:25:12.465
thou must exert thyself about this also,

01:25:12.845 --> 01:25:17.325
not neglecting it nor yet taking pleasure in thy dullness.

01:25:20.025 --> 01:25:23.085
One man, when he has done a service to another,

01:25:23.545 --> 01:25:27.825
is ready to set it down to his account as a favour conferred.

01:25:28.325 --> 01:25:35.045
Another is not ready to do this, but still in his own mind he thinks of the man as his debtor,

01:25:35.225 --> 01:25:37.105
and he knows what he has done.

01:25:37.865 --> 01:25:41.905
A third, in a manner, does not even know what he has done,

01:25:42.565 --> 01:25:45.385
but he is like a vine which has produced grapes,

01:25:45.885 --> 01:25:50.385
and seeks for nothing more after it has once produced its proper fruit.

01:25:51.125 --> 01:25:56.065
As a horse when he has run, a dog when he has tracked the game,

01:25:56.785 --> 01:26:02.865
a bee when it has made the honey, so a man when he has done a good act

01:26:02.865 --> 01:26:06.285
does not call out for others to come and see,

01:26:06.285 --> 01:26:08.985
but he goes on to another act,

01:26:09.505 --> 01:26:13.465
as a vine goes on to produce again the grapes in season.

01:26:14.845 --> 01:26:20.885
Must a man then be one of these who in a manner act thus without observing it?

01:26:21.625 --> 01:26:25.065
Yes, but this very thing is necessary,

01:26:25.405 --> 01:26:27.805
the observation of what a man is doing,

01:26:28.465 --> 01:26:32.845
for it may be said it is characteristic of the social animal

01:26:32.845 --> 01:26:36.525
to perceive that he is working in a social manner,

01:26:37.165 --> 01:26:41.545
and indeed to wish that his social partner also should perceive it.

01:26:42.905 --> 01:26:48.825
It is true what thou sayest, but thou dost not rightly understand what is now said,

01:26:49.645 --> 01:26:54.265
and for this reason thou wilt become one of those of whom I spoke before,

01:26:55.045 --> 01:26:58.885
for even they are misled by a certain show of reason.

01:26:59.835 --> 01:27:03.585
But if thou wilt choose to understand the meaning of what is said,

01:27:04.385 --> 01:27:09.465
do not fear that for this reason thou wilt omit any social act.

01:27:12.225 --> 01:27:14.425
A Prayer of the Athenians

01:27:15.225 --> 01:27:18.185
Rain, rain, O Dears Zeus,

01:27:18.865 --> 01:27:22.985
Down on the ploughed fields of the Athenians and on the plains.

01:27:23.985 --> 01:27:26.605
In truth we ought not to pray at all,

01:27:26.605 --> 01:27:31.245
or we ought to pray in this simple and noble fashion.

01:27:33.185 --> 01:27:40.125
Just as we must understand when it is said that Aesculapius prescribed to this man horse exercise,

01:27:40.725 --> 01:27:44.145
or bathing in cold water, or going without shoes,

01:27:45.005 --> 01:27:52.265
so we must understand it when it is said that the nature of the universe prescribed to this man

01:27:52.265 --> 01:27:57.285
disease, or mutilation, or loss, or anything else of the kind.

01:27:58.325 --> 01:28:02.505
For in the first case prescribed means something like this.

01:28:03.265 --> 01:28:08.505
He prescribed this for this man as a thing adapted to procure health,

01:28:09.325 --> 01:28:16.005
and in the second case it means that which happens to or suits every man

01:28:16.005 --> 01:28:20.405
is fixed in a manner for him suitably to his destiny.

01:28:21.365 --> 01:28:26.285
For this is what we mean when we say that things are suitable to us,

01:28:26.725 --> 01:28:31.205
as the workmen say of squared stones in walls or the pyramids,

01:28:31.505 --> 01:28:36.305
that they are suitable when they fit them to one another in some kind of connection.

01:28:37.665 --> 01:28:41.505
For there is altogether one fitness, harmony,

01:28:42.165 --> 01:28:48.705
and as the universe is made up out of all bodies to be such a body as it is,

01:28:49.405 --> 01:28:58.025
so out of all existing causes necessity, destiny, is made up to be such a cause as it is.

01:28:59.005 --> 01:29:03.705
And even those who are completely ignorant understand what I mean,

01:29:04.205 --> 01:29:10.225
for they say it, necessity, destiny, brought this to such a person.

01:29:11.225 --> 01:29:15.045
This then was brought and this was prescribed to him.

01:29:15.685 --> 01:29:20.805
Let us then receive these things as well as those which Aesculapius prescribes.

01:29:21.665 --> 01:29:27.305
Many, as a matter of course, even among his prescriptions, are disagreeable,

01:29:27.745 --> 01:29:30.225
but we accept them in the hope of health.

01:29:31.605 --> 01:29:37.925
Let the perfecting and accomplishment of the things which the common nature judges to be good

01:29:37.925 --> 01:29:42.465
be judged by thee to be of the same kind as thy health.

01:29:43.265 --> 01:29:51.305
And so accept everything which happens, even if it seem disagreeable, because it leads to this,

01:29:51.685 --> 01:29:58.205
to the health of the universe, and to the prosperity and felicity of Zeus, the universe.

01:29:59.065 --> 01:30:05.465
For he would not have brought on any man what he has brought, if it were not useful for the whole.

01:30:06.425 --> 01:30:13.365
Neither does the nature of anything, whatever it may be, cause anything which is not suitable

01:30:13.365 --> 01:30:15.785
to that which is directed by it.

01:30:16.405 --> 01:30:18.145
For two reasons then.

01:30:18.805 --> 01:30:22.565
It is right to be content with that which happens to thee.

01:30:23.525 --> 01:30:29.825
The one, because it was done for thee and prescribed for thee, and in a manner had

01:30:29.825 --> 01:30:36.025
reference to thee, originally from the most ancient causes spun with thy destiny.

01:30:36.925 --> 01:30:43.385
And the other, because even that which comes severly to every man is to the power which

01:30:43.385 --> 01:30:50.765
administers the universe a cause of felicity and perfection, nay, even of its very continuance.

01:30:51.665 --> 01:30:57.645
For the integrity of the whole is mutilated if thou cuttest off anything whatever from

01:30:57.645 --> 01:31:02.745
the conjunction and the continuity either of the parts or of the causes.

01:31:03.725 --> 01:31:09.565
And thou dost cut off, as far as it is in thy power, when thou art dissatisfied,

01:31:10.065 --> 01:31:13.865
and in a manner tryest to put anything out of the way.

01:31:15.505 --> 01:31:22.385
Be not disgusted, nor discouraged, nor dissatisfied, if thou dost not succeed

01:31:22.385 --> 01:31:25.645
in doing everything according to right principles.

01:31:26.385 --> 01:31:33.045
But when thou hast failed, return back again, and be content if the greater part

01:31:33.045 --> 01:31:36.765
of what thou doest is consistent with man's nature.

01:31:37.765 --> 01:31:44.765
And love this to which thou returnest, and do not return to philosophy as if she were a master,

01:31:45.305 --> 01:31:50.925
but act like those who have sore eyes and apply a bit of sponge and egg,

01:31:51.425 --> 01:31:55.985
or as another applies a plaster, or drenching with water.

01:31:56.605 --> 01:32:01.685
For thus thou wilt not fail to obey reason, and thou wilt repose in it.

01:32:02.285 --> 01:32:07.625
And remember that philosophy requires only the things which thy nature requires,

01:32:08.185 --> 01:32:11.965
but thou wouldst have something else which is not according to nature.

01:32:12.745 --> 01:32:18.265
It may be objected, why, what is more agreeable than this which I am doing?

01:32:19.145 --> 01:32:23.485
But is not this the very reason why pleasure deceives us?

01:32:24.325 --> 01:32:31.665
And consider if magnanimity, freedom, simplicity, equanimity, piety, are not more agreeable.

01:32:32.245 --> 01:32:37.725
For what is more agreeable than wisdom itself, when thou thinkest of the security,

01:32:38.025 --> 01:32:43.845
and the happy course of all things which depend on the faculty of understanding and knowledge?

01:32:45.685 --> 01:32:50.525
Things are in such a kind of envelopment that they have seemed to philosophers,

01:32:50.945 --> 01:32:55.785
not a few, nor those common philosophers, altogether unintelligible,

01:32:56.545 --> 01:33:00.505
nay, even to the Stoics themselves they seem difficult to understand.

01:33:01.445 --> 01:33:06.905
And all our ascent is changeable, for where is the man who never changes?

01:33:07.905 --> 01:33:13.625
Carry thy thoughts then to the objects themselves, and consider how short-lived they are,

01:33:13.625 --> 01:33:20.245
and worthless, and that they may be in the possession of a filthy wretch, or a whore, or a robber.

01:33:21.365 --> 01:33:27.685
Then turn to the morals of those who live with thee, and it is hardly possible to endure even

01:33:27.685 --> 01:33:33.365
the most agreeable of them, to say nothing of the man being hardly able to endure himself.

01:33:34.825 --> 01:33:42.325
In such darkness then, and dirt, and in so constant a flux, both of substance, and of time,

01:33:42.325 --> 01:33:50.005
and of motion, and of things moved, what there is worth being highly prized, or even an object

01:33:50.005 --> 01:33:58.905
of serious pursuit, I cannot imagine. But on the contrary, it is a man's duty to comfort himself,

01:33:59.365 --> 01:34:06.365
and to wait for the natural dissolution, and not to be vexed at the delay, but to rest in these

01:34:06.365 --> 01:34:13.945
principles only. The one that nothing will happen to me which is not conformable to the nature of

01:34:13.945 --> 01:34:22.125
the universe, and the other that it is in my power never to act contrary to my God and demon,

01:34:22.665 --> 01:34:26.265
for there is no man who will compel me to do this.

01:34:28.105 --> 01:34:35.285
About what am I now employing my own soul? On every occasion I must ask myself this question,

01:34:35.285 --> 01:34:42.245
and inquire, what have I now in this part of me which they call the ruling principle,

01:34:43.005 --> 01:34:50.185
and whose soul have I now, that of a child, or of a young man, or of a feeble woman,

01:34:50.805 --> 01:35:00.745
or of a tyrant, or of a domestic animal, or of a wild beast? What kind of things those are which

01:35:00.745 --> 01:35:07.885
appear good to the many, we may learn even from this. For if any man should conceive certain things

01:35:07.885 --> 01:35:16.625
as being really good, such as prudence, temperance, justice, fortitude, he would not after having first

01:35:16.625 --> 01:35:23.325
conceived these endure to listen to anything which should not be in harmony with what is really good.

01:35:24.165 --> 01:35:29.885
But if a man has first conceived as good the things which appear to the many to be good,

01:35:29.885 --> 01:35:36.285
he will listen and readily receive as very applicable that which was said by the comic

01:35:36.285 --> 01:35:44.185
writer. Thus even the many perceive the difference, for were it not so, this saying would not offend

01:35:44.185 --> 01:35:50.285
and would not be rejected in the first case, while we receive it when it is said of wealth

01:35:50.285 --> 01:35:58.905
and of the means which further luxury and fame, as said fitly and wittily. Go on then and ask

01:35:58.905 --> 01:36:05.225
if we should value and think those things to be good, to which after their first conception in

01:36:05.225 --> 01:36:12.545
the mind the words of the comic writer might be aptly applied, that he who has them through pure

01:36:12.545 --> 01:36:21.305
abundance has not a place to ease himself in. I am composed of the formal and the material,

01:36:22.025 --> 01:36:29.145
and neither of them will perish into nonexistence, as neither of them came into existence out of

01:36:29.145 --> 01:36:36.745
nonexistence. Every part of me then will be reduced by change into some part of the universe,

01:36:37.325 --> 01:36:45.525
and that again will change into another part of the universe, and so on forever. And by consequence

01:36:45.525 --> 01:36:53.085
such a change I too exist, and those who begot me, and so on forever in the other direction,

01:36:53.985 --> 01:37:00.445
for nothing hinders us from saying so, even if the universe is administered according to definite

01:37:00.445 --> 01:37:09.885
periods of revolution. Reason and the reasoning art, philosophy, are powers which are sufficient

01:37:09.885 --> 01:37:16.725
for themselves and for their own works. They move then from a first principle which is their own,

01:37:17.125 --> 01:37:23.145
and they make their way to the end which is proposed to them. And this is the reason why such

01:37:23.145 --> 01:37:32.225
acts are named kator thosais, or right acts, which word signifies that they proceed by the right road.

01:37:33.725 --> 01:37:41.825
None of these things ought to be called a man's, which do not belong to a man, as man. They are not

01:37:41.825 --> 01:37:48.685
required of a man, nor does man's nature promise them, nor are they the means of man's nature

01:37:48.685 --> 01:37:56.625
attaining its end. Neither then does the end of man lie in these things, nor yet that which aids

01:37:56.625 --> 01:38:02.205
to the accomplishment of this end, and that which aids toward this end is that which is good.

01:38:03.505 --> 01:38:10.505
Besides, if any of these things did belong to man, it would not be right for a man to despise them

01:38:10.505 --> 01:38:17.385
and to set himself against them, nor would a man be worthy of praise who showed that he did not

01:38:17.385 --> 01:38:24.745
want these things, nor would he who stinted himself in any of them be good, if indeed these things

01:38:24.745 --> 01:38:32.005
were good. But now the more of these things a man deprives himself of, or of other things like them,

01:38:32.005 --> 01:38:37.905
or even when he is deprived of any of them, the more patiently he endures the loss,

01:38:38.285 --> 01:38:41.325
just in the same degree he is a better man.

01:38:42.925 --> 01:38:51.145
Such as are thy habitual thoughts, such also will be the character of thy mind. For the soul is died

01:38:51.145 --> 01:38:58.905
by the thoughts. Die it then with a continuous series of such thoughts as these. For instance,

01:38:58.905 --> 01:39:05.365
that where a man can live, there he can also live well. But he must live in a palace.

01:39:06.125 --> 01:39:13.045
Well then, he can also live well in a palace. And again, consider that for whatever purpose

01:39:13.045 --> 01:39:20.005
each thing has been constituted. For this it has been constituted, and toward this it is carried,

01:39:20.745 --> 01:39:28.705
and its end is in that toward which it is carried. And where the end is, there also is the advantage

01:39:28.705 --> 01:39:34.965
and the good of each thing. Now the good for the reasonable animal is society,

01:39:35.785 --> 01:39:43.065
for that we are made for society has been shown above. Is it not plain that the inferior exist

01:39:43.065 --> 01:39:49.165
for the sake of the superior? But the things which have life are superior to those which have not

01:39:49.165 --> 01:39:57.125
life, and of those which have life the superior are those which have reason. To seek what is

01:39:57.125 --> 01:40:03.605
impossible is madness, and it is impossible that the bad should not do something of this kind.

01:40:04.625 --> 01:40:12.125
Nothing happens to any man which he is not formed by nature to bear. The same things happen to

01:40:12.125 --> 01:40:17.985
another, and either because he does not see that they have happened, or because he would show a

01:40:17.985 --> 01:40:25.565
great spirit, he is firm and remains unharmed. It is a shame then that ignorance and conceit

01:40:25.565 --> 01:40:33.865
should be stronger than wisdom. Things themselves touch not the soul, not in the least degree,

01:40:34.365 --> 01:40:41.685
nor have they admission to the soul, nor can they turn or move the soul. But the soul turns and

01:40:41.685 --> 01:40:49.425
moves itself alone, and whatever judgments it may think proper to make, such it makes for itself the

01:40:49.425 --> 01:40:57.285
things which present themselves to it. In one respect, man is the nearest thing to me, so far

01:40:57.285 --> 01:41:04.885
as I must do good to men and endure them. But so far as some men make themselves obstacles to my

01:41:04.885 --> 01:41:12.285
proper acts, man becomes to me one of the things which are indifferent, no less than the sun or wind

01:41:12.285 --> 01:41:19.845
or a wild beast. Now it is true that these may impede my action, but they are no impediments

01:41:19.845 --> 01:41:26.365
to my effects and disposition, which have the power of acting conditionally and changing.

01:41:27.005 --> 01:41:34.205
For the mind converts and changes every hindrance to its activity into an aid, and so that which

01:41:34.205 --> 01:41:41.265
is a hindrance is made a furtherance to an act, and that which is an obstacle on the road helps

01:41:41.265 --> 01:41:50.265
us on this road. Reverence that which is best in the universe, and this is that which makes use

01:41:50.265 --> 01:41:58.745
of all things and directs all things. And in like manner also, reverence that which is best in thyself,

01:41:59.185 --> 01:42:06.785
and this is of the same kind as that. For in thyself also, that which makes use of everything else

01:42:06.785 --> 01:42:16.285
is this, and thy life is directed by this. That which does no harm to the state, does no harm to

01:42:16.285 --> 01:42:23.765
the citizen. In the case of every appearance of harm, apply this rule. If the state is not harmed

01:42:23.765 --> 01:42:31.865
by this, neither am I harmed. But if the state is harmed, thou must not be angry with him who does

01:42:31.865 --> 01:42:41.145
harm to the state. Show him where his error is. Often think of the rapidity with which things pass

01:42:41.145 --> 01:42:48.005
by and disappear, both the things which are and the things which are produced. For substance is

01:42:48.005 --> 01:42:55.425
like a river in a continual flow, and the activities of things are in constant change, and the causes

01:42:55.425 --> 01:43:03.105
work in infinite varieties, and there is hardly anything which stands still. And consider this

01:43:03.105 --> 01:43:09.025
which is near to thee, this boundless abyss of the past and of the future, in which all things

01:43:09.025 --> 01:43:15.585
disappear. How then is he not a fool who is puffed up with such things, or plagued about them,

01:43:15.905 --> 01:43:22.525
or makes himself miserable? For they vex him only for a time, and a short time.

01:43:23.765 --> 01:43:31.065
Think of the universal substance, of which thou hast a very small portion, and of universal time,

01:43:31.645 --> 01:43:38.565
of which a short and indivisible interval has been assigned to thee, and of that which is fixed by

01:43:38.565 --> 01:43:47.445
destiny, and how small the part of it thou art. Does another do me wrong? Let him look to it.

01:43:47.445 --> 01:43:54.785
He has his own disposition, his own activity. I now have what the universal nature wills

01:43:54.785 --> 01:44:03.525
me to have, and I do what my nature now wills me to do. Let the part of thy soul which leads

01:44:03.525 --> 01:44:09.705
and governs be undisturbed by the movements in the flesh, whether of pleasure or of pain,

01:44:10.085 --> 01:44:16.425
and let it not unite with them, but let it circumscribe itself and limit those effects

01:44:16.425 --> 01:44:23.185
to their parts. But when these effects rise up to the mind by virtue of that other sympathy

01:44:23.185 --> 01:44:31.145
that naturally exists in a body which is all one, then thou must not strive to resist the sensation,

01:44:31.545 --> 01:44:38.705
for it is natural. But let not the ruling part of itself add to the sensation the opinion that it

01:44:38.705 --> 01:44:47.965
is either good or bad. Live with the gods. And he does live with the gods who constantly shows

01:44:47.965 --> 01:44:54.565
to them that his own soul is satisfied with that which is assigned to him, and that it does all

01:44:54.565 --> 01:45:01.485
that the demon wishes, which Zeus have given to every man for his guardian and guide, a portion

01:45:01.485 --> 01:45:10.505
of himself. And this is every man's understanding and reason. Art thou angry with him whose armpits

01:45:10.505 --> 01:45:19.325
stink? Art thou angry with him whose mouth smells foul? What good will this anger do thee? He has

01:45:19.325 --> 01:45:26.685
such a mouth. He has such armpits. It is necessary that such an emanation must come from such things.

01:45:27.305 --> 01:45:34.545
But the man has reason, it will be said, and he is able, if he takes pains, to discover wherein

01:45:34.545 --> 01:45:42.585
he offends. I wish thee well of thy discovery. Well then, and thou hast reason, by thy rational

01:45:42.585 --> 01:45:50.425
faculty, stir up his rational faculty, show him his error, admonish him. For if he listens,

01:45:50.425 --> 01:45:54.365
thou wilt cure him, and there is no need of anger.

01:45:56.705 --> 01:46:03.045
As thou intendest to live, when thou art gone out, so it is in thy power to live here.

01:46:03.605 --> 01:46:10.765
But if men do not permit thee, then get away out of life, yet so as if thou wert suffering no harm.

01:46:11.725 --> 01:46:18.005
The house is smoky, and I quit it. Why dost thou think that this is any trouble?

01:46:18.725 --> 01:46:26.505
But so long as nothing of the kind drives me out, I remain, am free, and no man shall hinder me from

01:46:26.505 --> 01:46:33.065
doing what I choose, and I choose to do what is according to the nature of the rational and social

01:46:33.065 --> 01:46:41.685
animal. The intelligence of the universe is social. Accordingly, it has made the inferior things for

01:46:41.685 --> 01:46:48.845
sake of the superior, and it has fitted the superior to one another. Thou seest how it has

01:46:48.845 --> 01:46:55.245
subordinated, coordinated, and assigned to everything its proper portion, and has brought

01:46:55.245 --> 01:47:03.325
together into concord with one another the things which are the best. How hast thou behaved hitherto

01:47:03.325 --> 01:47:10.925
to the gods, thy parents, brethren, children, teachers, to those who looked after thy infancy,

01:47:10.925 --> 01:47:19.865
to thy friends, kinsfolk, to thy slaves? Consider if thou hast hitherto behaved to all in such a way

01:47:19.865 --> 01:47:28.725
that this may be said of thee. Never has wronged a man in deed or word. And call to recollection

01:47:28.725 --> 01:47:35.245
both how many things thou hast passed through, and how many things thou hast been able to endure,

01:47:35.885 --> 01:47:42.845
and that the history of thy life is now complete, and thy service is ended, and how many beautiful

01:47:42.845 --> 01:47:49.965
things thou hast seen, and how many pleasures and pains thou hast despised, and how many things

01:47:49.965 --> 01:47:57.825
called honorable thou hast spurned, and to how many ill-minded folks thou hast shown a kind disposition.

01:47:59.025 --> 01:48:07.205
Why do unskilled and ignorant souls disturb him who has skill and knowledge? What soul then has

01:48:07.205 --> 01:48:14.245
skill and knowledge? That which knows beginning and end, and knows the reason which pervades all

01:48:14.245 --> 01:48:23.045
substance, and through all time by fixed periods administers the universe. Soon, very soon, thou

01:48:23.045 --> 01:48:31.625
wilt be ashes or a skeleton, and either a name or not even a name. But name is sound and echo,

01:48:32.045 --> 01:48:37.925
and the things which are much valued in life are empty and rotten and trifling, and like little

01:48:37.925 --> 01:48:44.445
dogs biting one another, and little children quarreling, laughing, and then straightway weeping.

01:48:45.265 --> 01:48:52.865
But fidelity and modesty and justice and truth are fled up to Olympus from the widespread earth.

01:48:53.045 --> 01:49:00.525
What then is there which still detains thee here, if the objects of sense are easily changed and

01:49:00.525 --> 01:49:06.705
never stand still, and the organs of perception are dull and easily receive false impressions,

01:49:07.065 --> 01:49:14.285
and the poor soul itself is an exhalation from blood? But to have good repute amid such a world

01:49:14.285 --> 01:49:20.325
as this is an empty thing. Why then dost thou not wait in tranquillity for thy end,

01:49:20.325 --> 01:49:26.525
whether it is extinction or removal to another state? And until that time comes,

01:49:27.065 --> 01:49:33.905
what is sufficient? Why, what else then to venerate the gods and bless them,

01:49:34.345 --> 01:49:41.945
and to do good to men, and to practice tolerance and self-restraint? But as to everything which

01:49:41.945 --> 01:49:48.945
is beyond the limits of the poor flesh and breath, to remember that this is neither thine nor in thy

01:49:48.945 --> 01:49:58.165
power. Thou canst pass thy life in an equable flow of happiness, if thou canst go by the right way,

01:49:58.505 --> 01:50:05.785
and think and act in the right way. These two things are common both to the soul of God,

01:50:06.265 --> 01:50:13.385
and to the soul of man, and to the soul of every rational being, not to be hindered by another,

01:50:14.315 --> 01:50:20.285
and to hold good to consist in the disposition to justice and the practice of it,

01:50:20.865 --> 01:50:24.825
and in this to let thy desire find its termination.

01:50:26.385 --> 01:50:33.545
If this is neither my own badness nor an effect of my own badness, and the commonwealth is not

01:50:33.545 --> 01:50:40.005
injured, why am I troubled about it? And what is the harm to the commonwealth?

01:50:41.185 --> 01:50:47.925
Do not be carried along inconsiderately by the appearance of things, but give help to all

01:50:47.925 --> 01:50:54.645
according to thy ability and their fitness, and if they should have sustained loss in matters which

01:50:54.645 --> 01:51:03.545
are indifferent, do not imagine this to be a damage, for it is a bad habit. But as the old man,

01:51:03.545 --> 01:51:10.325
when he went away, asked back his foster child's top, remembering that it was a top,

01:51:11.145 --> 01:51:19.145
so do thou in this case also. When thou art calling out on the rostra, hast thou forgotten,

01:51:19.385 --> 01:51:26.565
man, what these things are? Yes, but they are objects of great concern to these people.

01:51:26.565 --> 01:51:33.665
Wilt thou too then be made a fool for these things? I was once a fortunate man,

01:51:34.205 --> 01:51:41.545
but I lost it, I know not how. But fortunate means that a man has assigned to himself

01:51:41.545 --> 01:51:50.445
a good fortune, and a good fortune is good disposition of the soul, good emotions, good actions.

01:52:21.018 --> 01:52:25.458
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus.

01:52:30.018 --> 01:52:34.218
The substance of the universe is obedient and compliant, and the reason which governs

01:52:34.218 --> 01:52:39.098
it has in itself no cause for doing evil, for it has no malice, nor does it do evil

01:52:39.098 --> 01:52:41.958
to anything, nor is anything harmed by it.

01:52:42.218 --> 01:52:45.358
But all things are made and perfected according to this reason.

01:52:48.018 --> 01:52:52.318
Let it make no difference to thee whether thou art cold or warm, if thou art doing

01:52:52.318 --> 01:52:58.978
thy duty, and whether thou art drowsy or satisfied with sleep, and whether ill-spoken or praised,

01:52:59.718 --> 01:53:05.358
and whether dying or doing something else, for it is one of the acts of this life, this act by

01:53:05.358 --> 01:53:11.158
which we die, it is sufficient then in this act also to do well what we have in hand.

01:53:13.558 --> 01:53:18.698
Look within, let neither the peculiar quality of anything nor its value escape thee.

01:53:20.858 --> 01:53:24.738
All existing things soon change, and they will either be reduced to vapor,

01:53:25.198 --> 01:53:28.538
if indeed all substance is one, or they will be dispersed.

01:53:30.358 --> 01:53:36.118
The reason which governs knows what its own disposition is, and what it does, and on what

01:53:36.118 --> 01:53:37.278
material it works.

01:53:40.038 --> 01:53:44.518
The best way of avenging thyself is not to become like the wrongdoer.

01:53:46.518 --> 01:53:50.658
Take pleasure in one thing and rest in it, in passing from one social act to another

01:53:50.658 --> 01:53:52.698
social act, thinking of God.

01:53:54.538 --> 01:53:59.798
The ruling principle is that which rouses and turns itself, and while it makes itself

01:53:59.798 --> 01:54:04.738
such as it is, and such as it wills to be, it also makes everything which happens to

01:54:04.738 --> 01:54:07.618
appear itself to be such as it wills.

01:54:09.698 --> 01:54:13.698
In conformity to the nature of the universe, every single thing is accomplished.

01:54:14.678 --> 01:54:18.938
For certainly it is not in conformity to any other nature that each thing is accomplished,

01:54:18.938 --> 01:54:25.238
either a nature which externally comprehends this, or a nature which is comprehended within

01:54:25.238 --> 01:54:29.318
this nature, or a nature external and independent of this.

01:54:32.718 --> 01:54:38.958
The universe is either a confusion and a mutual involution of things, and a dispersion, or

01:54:38.958 --> 01:54:41.398
it is unity and order and providence.

01:54:41.838 --> 01:54:46.938
If, then, it is the former, why do I desire to tarry in a fortuitous combination of things

01:54:46.938 --> 01:54:52.238
in such a disorder, and why do I care about anything else than how I shall at last become

01:54:52.238 --> 01:54:57.678
earth, and why am I disturbed for the dispersion of my elements will happen whatever I do?

01:54:58.318 --> 01:55:05.358
But if the other supposition is true, I venerate, and I am firm, and I trust in him who governs.

01:55:06.598 --> 01:55:11.698
When thou hast been compelled by circumstances to be disturbed in a manner, quickly return

01:55:11.698 --> 01:55:16.758
to thyself, and do not continue out of tune longer than the compulsion lasts, for that

01:55:16.758 --> 01:55:21.098
thou wilt have more mastery over the harmony by continually recurring to it.

01:55:23.878 --> 01:55:28.258
If thou hadst a stepmother and a mother at the same time, thou wouldest be dutiful to

01:55:28.258 --> 01:55:32.038
thy stepmother, but thou wouldest constantly return to thy mother.

01:55:32.638 --> 01:55:36.538
Let the court and philosophy now be to thee stepmother and mother.

01:55:37.098 --> 01:55:42.718
Return to philosophy frequently, and repose in her, through whom what thou meetest with

01:55:42.718 --> 01:55:46.958
in the court appears to thee tolerable, and thou appearest tolerable in the court.

01:55:50.338 --> 01:55:56.338
When we have meat before us, and such eatables, we receive the impression that this is the

01:55:56.338 --> 01:56:01.938
dead body of a fish, and this is the dead body of a bird, or of a pig, and again that

01:56:01.938 --> 01:56:07.458
this Phalernian is only a little grape juice, and this purple robe some sheep's wool dyed

01:56:07.458 --> 01:56:08.878
with the blood of a shellfish.

01:56:09.618 --> 01:56:13.738
Such then are these impressions, and they reach the things themselves and penetrate

01:56:13.738 --> 01:56:16.818
them, and so we see what kind of things they are.

01:56:17.598 --> 01:56:22.298
Just in the same way, ought we to act all through life, and where there are things which

01:56:22.298 --> 01:56:26.478
appear most worthy of our approbation, we ought to lay them bare, and look at their

01:56:26.478 --> 01:56:30.218
worthlessness, and strip them of all the words by which they are exalted.

01:56:31.098 --> 01:56:36.778
For outward show is a wonderful perverter of the reason, and when thou art most sure

01:56:36.778 --> 01:56:41.498
that thou art employed about things worth thy pains, it is then that it cheats thee

01:56:41.498 --> 01:56:41.918
most.

01:56:42.918 --> 01:56:46.518
Consider, then, what Crates says of Xenocrates himself.

01:56:49.358 --> 01:56:53.678
Most of the things which the multitude admire are referred to objects of the most general

01:56:53.678 --> 01:57:00.178
kind, those which are held together by cohesion or natural organization, such as stones, wood,

01:57:00.518 --> 01:57:05.638
fig trees, vines, olives, but those which are admired by men, who are a little more

01:57:05.638 --> 01:57:10.458
reasonable, are referred to the things which are held together by a living principle, as

01:57:10.458 --> 01:57:12.338
flocks, herds.

01:57:12.618 --> 01:57:17.698
Those which are admired by men, who are still more instructed, are the things which are

01:57:17.698 --> 01:57:24.478
held together by a rational soul, not, however, a universal soul, for rational, so far as

01:57:24.478 --> 01:57:30.198
it is a soul skilled in some art, or expert in some other way, or simply rational so far

01:57:30.198 --> 01:57:32.238
as it possesses a number of slaves.

01:57:32.238 --> 01:57:39.038
But he who values a rational soul, a soul universal and fitted for political life, regards

01:57:39.038 --> 01:57:45.358
nothing else except this, and above all things he keeps his soul in a condition and in an

01:57:45.358 --> 01:57:51.318
actively conformable to reason and social life, and he cooperates to this end with those

01:57:51.318 --> 01:57:53.378
who are of the same kind as himself.

01:57:55.198 --> 01:58:00.578
Some things are hurrying into existence, others are hurrying out of it, and of that which

01:58:00.578 --> 01:58:04.358
is coming into existence, part is already extinguished.

01:58:04.518 --> 01:58:09.498
Motions and changes are continually renewing the world, such as the uninterrupted course

01:58:09.498 --> 01:58:12.358
of time is always renewing the infinite duration of ages.

01:58:13.198 --> 01:58:18.878
In this flowing stream then, on which there is no abiding, what is there of the things

01:58:18.878 --> 01:58:21.998
which hurry by on which a man would set a high price?

01:58:22.438 --> 01:58:26.798
It would be just as if a man should fall in love with one of the sparrows which fly by,

01:58:27.198 --> 01:58:29.218
but it is already passed out of sight.

01:58:30.098 --> 01:58:35.678
Something of this kind is the very life of every man, like the exhalation of the blood

01:58:35.678 --> 01:58:37.298
and the respiration of the air.

01:58:38.198 --> 01:58:43.758
Such as it is to once have drawn in the air and to have given it back, which we do every

01:58:43.758 --> 01:58:49.618
moment, just the same is it with the whole respiratory power which thou didst receive

01:58:49.618 --> 01:58:54.878
at thy birth yesterday and the day before, to give it back to the elemental from which

01:58:54.878 --> 01:58:56.378
thou didst first draw it.

01:58:58.378 --> 01:59:04.098
Neither is transpiration, as in plants, a thing to be valued, nor respiration, as in

01:59:04.098 --> 01:59:09.118
domesticated animals and wild beasts, nor the receiving of impressions by the appearances

01:59:09.118 --> 01:59:15.118
of things, nor being moved by desires, as puppets by strings, nor assembling in herds,

01:59:15.338 --> 01:59:21.098
nor being nourished by food, for this is just like the act of separating and parting with

01:59:21.098 --> 01:59:22.238
the useless part of the food.

01:59:23.058 --> 01:59:25.138
What, then, is worth being valued?

01:59:25.478 --> 01:59:27.318
To be received with clapping of hands?

01:59:27.938 --> 01:59:32.738
No, neither must we value the clapping of tongues, for the praise which comes from the

01:59:32.738 --> 01:59:34.358
many is the clapping of tongues.

01:59:36.118 --> 01:59:40.338
Suppose, then, that thou hast given up this worthless thing called fame.

01:59:40.498 --> 01:59:42.718
What remains that is worth valuing?

01:59:43.618 --> 01:59:48.598
This, in my opinion, to move thyself and to restrain thyself in conformity to thy proper

01:59:48.598 --> 01:59:54.738
constitution, to which end both all employments and arts lead, for every art aims at this,

01:59:55.018 --> 01:59:59.478
that the thing which has been made should be adapted to the work for which it has been

01:59:59.478 --> 02:00:04.658
made, and both the vine-planner who looks after the vine and the horse-breaker and he

02:00:04.658 --> 02:00:06.678
who trains the dog seeks this end.

02:00:07.578 --> 02:00:13.318
But the education and the teaching of youth aim at something, and this, then, is the value

02:00:13.318 --> 02:00:14.698
of the education and the teaching.

02:00:15.978 --> 02:00:19.298
And if this is well, thou wilt not seek anything else.

02:00:19.918 --> 02:00:22.478
Wilt thou not cease to value many other things, too?

02:00:22.798 --> 02:00:27.698
Then thou wilt neither be free nor sufficient for thy own happiness, nor without passion.

02:00:28.798 --> 02:00:33.158
For of necessity thou must be envious, jealous, and suspicious of those who can take away

02:00:33.158 --> 02:00:38.118
those things and plot against those who have that which is valued by thee.

02:00:38.118 --> 02:00:45.058
Of necessity a man must be altogether in a state of perturbation who wants any of these

02:00:45.058 --> 02:00:48.698
things, and besides he must often find fault with the gods.

02:00:49.778 --> 02:00:54.658
But to reverence and honor thy own mind will make thee content with thyself, and in harmony

02:00:54.658 --> 02:01:00.058
with society, in agreement with the gods, that is, praising all that they give and have

02:01:00.058 --> 02:01:00.438
ordered.

02:01:02.958 --> 02:01:07.398
Above, below, all around are the movements of the elements.

02:01:08.138 --> 02:01:10.398
But the motion of virtue is in none of these.

02:01:10.958 --> 02:01:15.978
It is something more divine, and advancing by a way hardly observed, it goes happily

02:01:15.978 --> 02:01:16.798
on its road.

02:01:19.098 --> 02:01:20.418
How strangely men act!

02:01:20.858 --> 02:01:24.718
They will not praise those who are living at the same time and living with themselves.

02:01:25.538 --> 02:01:30.498
But to be themselves praised by posterity, by those whom they have never seen or will

02:01:30.498 --> 02:01:33.038
ever see, this they set much value on.

02:01:33.718 --> 02:01:37.918
But this is very much the same as if thou shouldest be grieved because those who have

02:01:37.918 --> 02:01:40.378
lived before thee did not praise thee.

02:01:42.838 --> 02:01:47.398
If a thing is difficult to be accomplished by thyself, do not think that it is impossible

02:01:47.398 --> 02:01:48.038
for man.

02:01:48.978 --> 02:01:53.978
But if anything is possible for man, and conformable to his nature, think that this can be attained

02:01:53.978 --> 02:01:55.278
by thyself, too.

02:01:57.598 --> 02:02:02.398
In the gymnastic exercises, suppose that a man has torn thee with his nails, and by

02:02:02.398 --> 02:02:04.458
dashing against thy head has inflicted a wound.

02:02:05.218 --> 02:02:11.038
Well, we neither show any signs of vexation, nor are we offended, nor do we suspect him

02:02:11.038 --> 02:02:12.578
afterward as a treacherous fellow.

02:02:13.318 --> 02:02:18.358
And yet we are on our guard against him, not, however, as an enemy, nor with suspicion,

02:02:18.938 --> 02:02:20.658
but we quietly get out of his way.

02:02:21.598 --> 02:02:25.358
Something like this let their behavior be in all other parts of life.

02:02:25.718 --> 02:02:31.298
Let us overlook many things in those who are like antagonists in the gymnasium, for it

02:02:31.298 --> 02:02:36.098
is in our power, as I said, to get out of the way and to have no suspicion or hatred.

02:02:39.038 --> 02:02:44.438
If a man is able to convince me and show me that he do not think or act right, I will

02:02:44.438 --> 02:02:49.118
gladly change, for I seek the truth by which no man was ever injured.

02:02:49.118 --> 02:02:53.078
But he is injured who abides in his error and ignorance.

02:02:55.398 --> 02:02:59.978
I do my duty, other things trouble me not, for they are either things without life or

02:02:59.978 --> 02:03:03.778
things without reason, or things that have rambled and know not the way.

02:03:05.338 --> 02:03:10.218
As to the animals which have no reason, and generally all things and objects, do thou,

02:03:10.478 --> 02:03:14.938
since thou hast reason and they have none, make use of them with a generous and liberal

02:03:14.938 --> 02:03:21.118
spirit, but towards human beings, as they have reason, behave in a social spirit, and

02:03:21.118 --> 02:03:26.158
on all occasions call on the gods, and do not perplex thyself about the length of time

02:03:26.158 --> 02:03:30.558
in which thou shalt do this, for even three hours so spent are sufficient.

02:03:33.338 --> 02:03:38.638
Alexander the Macedonian and his groom by death were brought to the same state, for

02:03:38.638 --> 02:03:43.278
either they were received among the same seminal principles of the universe, or they were alike

02:03:43.278 --> 02:03:44.998
dispersed among the atoms.

02:03:47.318 --> 02:03:51.718
Consider how many things in the same indivisible time take place in each of us, things which

02:03:51.718 --> 02:03:56.878
concern the body and things which concern the soul, and so that we will not wonder if

02:03:56.878 --> 02:04:01.918
many more things, or rather all things which come into existence in that which is the one

02:04:01.918 --> 02:04:06.318
and all which we call Cosmos, exist in it at the same time.

02:04:07.938 --> 02:04:14.238
If any man should propose to thee the question, how the name Antoninus is written, wouldest

02:04:14.238 --> 02:04:18.498
thou with the straining of the voice utter each letter? What then if they grow angry,

02:04:18.838 --> 02:04:23.798
wilt thou grow angry too? Wilt thou not go on with composure and number every letter?

02:04:25.058 --> 02:04:31.738
Just so then is this life also remember that every duty is made up of certain parts. These

02:04:31.738 --> 02:04:36.118
things it is thy duty to observe, and without being disturbed or showing anger towards

02:04:36.118 --> 02:04:41.358
those who are angry with thee, to go on thy way and finish that which is set before thee.

02:04:43.578 --> 02:04:48.238
How cruel it is not to allow men to strive after the things which appear to them to be

02:04:48.238 --> 02:04:53.598
suitable to thy nature and profitable. Yet in a manner thou dost not allow them to do

02:04:53.598 --> 02:04:58.658
this, when thou art vexed because they do wrong. For they are certainly moved towards

02:04:58.658 --> 02:05:02.518
the things which they suppose them to be suitable to their nature and profitable to

02:05:02.518 --> 02:05:08.198
them. But it is not so. Teach them then, and show them without being angry.

02:05:10.658 --> 02:05:16.078
Death is the cessation of the impression through the senses, and of the pulling of the strings

02:05:16.078 --> 02:05:21.298
which move the appetites, and of the discursive movements of the thoughts, and of the service

02:05:21.298 --> 02:05:28.418
to the flesh. It is a shame for the soul to be the first to give way in this life, when

02:05:28.418 --> 02:05:29.838
thy body does not give way.

02:05:32.498 --> 02:05:38.398
Take care that thou art not made into a Caesar, that thou art not died with this die, for

02:05:38.398 --> 02:05:44.598
such things happen. Keep thyself then simple, good, pure, serious, free from affectation,

02:05:45.378 --> 02:05:50.758
a friend of justice, a worshiper of the gods, kind, affectionate, strenuous in all proper

02:05:50.758 --> 02:05:58.258
acts. Strive to continue to be such as philosophy wished to make thee. Reverence the gods and

02:05:58.258 --> 02:06:05.658
help men. Short is life. There is only one fruit in this tureen life, a pious disposition

02:06:05.658 --> 02:06:12.478
and social acts. Do everything as a disciple of Antoninus. Remember his constancy in every

02:06:12.478 --> 02:06:18.838
act which was conformable to reason, and his evenness in all things, and his piety, and

02:06:18.838 --> 02:06:24.438
the serenity of his continence, and his sweetness, and his disregard of empty fame, and his efforts

02:06:24.438 --> 02:06:30.078
to understand things, and how he would never let anything pass without having first, most

02:06:30.078 --> 02:06:35.158
carefully examined it and clearly understood it, and how he bore with those who blamed

02:06:35.158 --> 02:06:40.238
him unjustly without blaming them in return, and how he did nothing in a hurry, and how

02:06:40.238 --> 02:06:46.238
he listened not to calumnies, and how exact an examiner of manners and actions he was,

02:06:46.638 --> 02:06:53.898
and not given to reproach people, nor timid, nor suspicious, nor asophist, and with how

02:06:53.898 --> 02:07:00.178
little he was satisfied, such as lodging, bed, dress, food, servants, and how laborious

02:07:00.178 --> 02:07:06.018
and patient, and how he was able, on account of his sparing diet, to hold out to the evening

02:07:06.018 --> 02:07:12.278
without even requiring to relieve himself by any evacuations except at the usual hour,

02:07:12.838 --> 02:07:17.138
and with his firmness and uniformity in his friendships, and how he tolerated freedom

02:07:17.138 --> 02:07:22.678
of speech in those who opposed his opinions, and the pleasure that he had when any man

02:07:22.678 --> 02:07:27.238
showed him anything better, and how religious he was without superstition.

02:07:27.878 --> 02:07:32.698
Imitate all this that thou mayest have as good a conscience when thy last hour comes,

02:07:33.058 --> 02:07:33.938
as he had.

02:07:37.218 --> 02:07:42.198
Return to thy sober senses, and call thyself back, when thou hast roused thyself from

02:07:42.198 --> 02:07:48.058
sleep, and hast perceived that they were only dreams which troubled thee, now in thy waking

02:07:48.058 --> 02:07:53.078
hour's look at these, the things about thee, as thou didst look at those, the dreams.

02:07:54.678 --> 02:07:56.678
I consist of a little body and soul.

02:07:57.138 --> 02:08:01.618
Now to this little body all things are indifferent, for it is not able to perceive differences,

02:08:02.438 --> 02:08:06.838
but to the understanding those things only are indifferent, which are not the works of

02:08:06.838 --> 02:08:07.658
its own activity.

02:08:08.538 --> 02:08:13.038
But whatever things are the works of its own activity, all these things are in its power,

02:08:13.698 --> 02:08:17.858
and of these however only those which are done with reference to the present, for as

02:08:17.858 --> 02:08:22.678
to the future and the past activities of the mind, even these are for the present indifferent.

02:08:25.778 --> 02:08:31.098
Neither the labor, which the hand does, nor that of the foot is contrary to nature, so

02:08:31.098 --> 02:08:35.358
long as the foot does the foot's work and the hand the hand's.

02:08:35.678 --> 02:08:40.838
So then neither to a man, as a man is his labor contrary to nature, as long as he does

02:08:40.838 --> 02:08:46.178
the things of a man, but if the labor is not contrary to his nature, neither is it an evil

02:08:46.178 --> 02:08:46.798
to him.

02:08:48.798 --> 02:08:52.818
How many pleasures have been enjoyed by robbers, patricides, tyrants?

02:08:55.778 --> 02:09:00.638
Dost thou not see how the handicraftsmen accommodate themselves up to a certain point to those

02:09:00.638 --> 02:09:02.078
which are not skilled in their craft?

02:09:02.658 --> 02:09:06.538
Nevertheless, they cling to the reason, the principles of their art, and do not endure

02:09:06.538 --> 02:09:07.618
to depart from it.

02:09:08.738 --> 02:09:12.798
Is it not strange if the architect and the physician shall have more respect to the reason,

02:09:12.798 --> 02:09:17.338
the principles of their own arts, than man to his own reason, which is common to him

02:09:17.338 --> 02:09:17.998
and the gods?

02:09:20.378 --> 02:09:23.778
Asia, Europe, are corners of the universe.

02:09:24.418 --> 02:09:26.418
All the sea a drop in the universe.

02:09:26.998 --> 02:09:29.278
Athos, a little clod in the universe.

02:09:29.998 --> 02:09:32.358
All the present time is a point in eternity.

02:09:33.518 --> 02:09:36.138
All things are little, changeable, perishable.

02:09:36.838 --> 02:09:42.738
All things come from thence, from that universal ruling power, either directly proceeding or

02:09:42.738 --> 02:09:43.618
by way of sequence.

02:09:44.158 --> 02:09:48.638
And, accordingly, the lion's gaping jaws, and that which is poisonous, and every harmful

02:09:48.638 --> 02:09:53.358
thing, as a thorn, as mud, are afterproducts of the grand and beautiful.

02:09:54.378 --> 02:09:59.078
Do not imagine, then, that they are of another kind from that which thou dost venerate, but

02:09:59.078 --> 02:10:01.398
form a just opinion of the source of all.

02:10:03.758 --> 02:10:08.418
He who has seen present things has seen all, both everything which has taken place from

02:10:08.418 --> 02:10:14.298
all eternity, and everything which will be for time without end, for all things are of

02:10:14.298 --> 02:10:16.638
one kin and of one form.

02:10:19.738 --> 02:10:23.598
Frequently consider the connection of all things in the universe in their relation to

02:10:23.598 --> 02:10:24.078
one another.

02:10:24.938 --> 02:10:28.958
For, in a manner, all things are implicated with one another, and all, in this way, are

02:10:28.958 --> 02:10:29.998
friendly to one another.

02:10:30.418 --> 02:10:35.958
For one thing comes in order after another, and this is by virtue of the active movement

02:10:35.958 --> 02:10:39.438
and mutual composition and the unity of the substance.

02:10:41.418 --> 02:10:46.058
Adapt thyself to the things with which thy lot has been cast, and the men among whom

02:10:46.058 --> 02:10:47.878
thou hast received thy portion.

02:10:48.458 --> 02:10:50.318
Love them, but do it truly.

02:10:52.658 --> 02:10:58.598
Every instrument, too, vessel, if it does that for which it has been made, is well,

02:10:58.958 --> 02:11:01.438
and yet he who made it is not there.

02:11:01.438 --> 02:11:06.418
But in all things which are held together by nature, there is within, and there abides

02:11:06.418 --> 02:11:08.858
in them, the power which made them.

02:11:10.058 --> 02:11:14.658
Wherefore, the more it is fit to reverence this power, and to think that, if thou dost

02:11:14.658 --> 02:11:19.418
live and act according to its will, everything in thee is in conformity to intelligence.

02:11:20.358 --> 02:11:25.138
And thus also in the universe the things which belong to it are in conformity to intelligence.

02:11:27.158 --> 02:11:31.618
Whatever of the things which are not within thy power thou shalt suppose to be good for

02:11:31.618 --> 02:11:32.658
thee, or evil.

02:11:33.298 --> 02:11:38.818
It must of necessity be that, if such a bad thing befall thee, or the loss of such a good

02:11:38.818 --> 02:11:44.558
thing, thou wilt blame the gods, and hate men, too, those who are the cause of the misfortune,

02:11:44.658 --> 02:11:48.418
or the loss, or those who are suspected of being likely to be the cause.

02:11:49.018 --> 02:11:55.118
And indeed we do much injustice, because we make a difference between those things, because

02:11:55.118 --> 02:11:56.958
we do not regard these things as indifferent.

02:11:58.618 --> 02:12:03.758
But if we judge only those things which are in our power to be good or bad, there remains

02:12:03.758 --> 02:12:08.618
no reason either for finding fault with God, or standing in a hostile attitude to man.

02:12:11.018 --> 02:12:16.298
We are all working together to one end, some with knowledge and design, and others without

02:12:16.298 --> 02:12:22.298
knowing what they do, as men also when they are asleep, of whom it is Heraclius, I think,

02:12:22.298 --> 02:12:26.958
who says that there are laborers and cooperators in the things which take place in the universe.

02:12:27.998 --> 02:12:33.178
But men cooperate after different fashions, and even those cooperate abundantly, who find

02:12:33.178 --> 02:12:37.198
fault with what happens, and those who try to oppose it and to hinder it.

02:12:37.658 --> 02:12:40.338
For the universe has need even of such men as these.

02:12:41.078 --> 02:12:45.978
It remains then for thee to understand among what kind of workman thou placest thyself.

02:12:46.418 --> 02:12:51.958
For he who rules all things will certainly make a right use of thee, and he will receive

02:12:51.958 --> 02:12:57.618
thee among some part of the cooperators, and of those whose labors conduce to one end.

02:12:58.258 --> 02:13:03.018
But be not thou such a part as the mean and ridiculous verse in the play which Prisippus

02:13:03.018 --> 02:13:03.858
speaks of.

02:13:05.998 --> 02:13:08.858
Does the sun undertake to do the work of the rain?

02:13:09.598 --> 02:13:12.678
Or ice Galapias, the work of the fruit-bearer?

02:13:12.998 --> 02:13:17.718
And how is it with respect to each of the stars, are they not different, and yet they

02:13:17.718 --> 02:13:19.478
work together to the same end?

02:13:22.298 --> 02:13:27.258
If the gods have determined about me, and about the things which must happen to me,

02:13:27.498 --> 02:13:28.678
they have determined well.

02:13:29.218 --> 02:13:32.738
For it is not easy even to imagine a deity without forethought.

02:13:33.458 --> 02:13:37.298
And as to doing me harm, why should they have any desire towards that?

02:13:37.678 --> 02:13:41.878
For what advantage would result to them from this, or to the whole, which is the special

02:13:41.878 --> 02:13:43.078
object of their providence?

02:13:43.718 --> 02:13:47.818
But if they have not determined about me individually, they have certainly determined

02:13:47.818 --> 02:13:52.978
about the whole at least, and the things which happen by way of sequence in this general

02:13:52.978 --> 02:13:56.478
arrangement I ought to accept with pleasure, and to be content with them.

02:13:57.138 --> 02:14:01.918
But if they determine about nothing, which it is wicked to believe, or if we do believe

02:14:01.918 --> 02:14:07.758
it, let us neither sacrifice, nor pray, nor swear by them, nor do anything else, which

02:14:07.758 --> 02:14:10.378
we do as if the gods were present and lived with us.

02:14:10.958 --> 02:14:16.298
But if, however, the gods determine about none of the things which concern us, I am

02:14:16.298 --> 02:14:21.498
able to determine about myself, and I can acquire about that which is useful, and that

02:14:21.498 --> 02:14:25.678
is useful to every man which is conformable to his own constitution and nature.

02:14:26.558 --> 02:14:33.038
But my nature is rational, and social, and my city and country, as far as I am Antoninus,

02:14:33.238 --> 02:14:33.798
is Rome.

02:14:34.518 --> 02:14:36.938
But so far as I am a man, it is the world.

02:14:37.598 --> 02:14:42.198
The things then which are useful to these cities are alone useful to me.

02:14:44.958 --> 02:14:48.798
Whatever happens to every man, this is for the interest of the universal.

02:14:49.418 --> 02:14:50.518
This might be sufficient.

02:14:51.218 --> 02:14:56.338
But further thou wilt observe this also as a general truth, if thou dost observe, that

02:14:56.338 --> 02:15:00.098
whatever is profitable to any man is profitable also to other men.

02:15:01.038 --> 02:15:06.918
But let the word profitable be taken here in the common sense as said of things of the

02:15:06.918 --> 02:15:07.518
more bad.

02:15:10.138 --> 02:15:14.898
As it happens to thee in the amphitheater and such places, that the continual sight

02:15:14.898 --> 02:15:20.718
of the same things, and the uniformity make the spectacle wearisome, so it is in the whole

02:15:20.718 --> 02:15:21.318
of life.

02:15:21.898 --> 02:15:25.678
For all things above, below, are the same, and from the same.

02:15:26.398 --> 02:15:27.418
How long then?

02:15:31.058 --> 02:15:35.918
Think continually that all kinds of men, and all kinds of pursuits, and of all nations

02:15:35.918 --> 02:15:41.978
are dead, so that thy thoughts come down even to Philistion, and Phoebus, and Oregonian.

02:15:42.978 --> 02:15:45.538
Now turn thy thoughts to the other kinds of men.

02:15:46.138 --> 02:15:51.218
To that place, then, we must remove, where there are so many great orators, so many noble

02:15:51.218 --> 02:15:57.398
philosophers, Heraclitus, Pythagoras, Socrates, so many heroes of former days, so many

02:15:57.398 --> 02:16:00.558
generals after them, and tyrants.

02:16:00.998 --> 02:16:07.798
Besides these, Eudoxus, Hipparchus, Archimedes, and other men of acute natural talents, great

02:16:07.798 --> 02:16:13.878
minds, lovers of labor, versatile, confident, mockers even of the perishable and ephemeral

02:16:13.878 --> 02:16:17.418
life of man, as Menippus and such as are like him.

02:16:18.098 --> 02:16:22.258
As to all these, consider that they have long been in the dust.

02:16:23.078 --> 02:16:25.218
What harm, then, is this to them?

02:16:25.218 --> 02:16:28.498
And what to those whose names are altogether unknown?

02:16:29.478 --> 02:16:35.238
One thing here is worth a great deal, to pass thy life in truth and justice, with a benevolent

02:16:35.238 --> 02:16:38.278
disposition even to liars and unjust men.

02:16:40.998 --> 02:16:46.858
Thou art not dissatisfied, I suppose, because thou weighest only so many leader, and not

02:16:46.858 --> 02:16:47.438
three hundred.

02:16:48.298 --> 02:16:52.458
Be not dissatisfied, then, that thou must live only so many years, and not more.

02:16:52.458 --> 02:16:58.738
For as thou art satisfied with the amount of substance which has been assigned to thee,

02:16:59.258 --> 02:17:01.338
so be content with the time.

02:17:05.018 --> 02:17:09.798
Let us try to persuade them, but act even against their will when the principles of

02:17:09.798 --> 02:17:11.258
justice lead that way.

02:17:11.758 --> 02:17:17.258
If, however, any man using force stands in thy way, betake thyself to contentment and

02:17:17.258 --> 02:17:22.098
tranquility, and at the same time employ the hindrance toward the exercise of some other

02:17:22.098 --> 02:17:27.958
virtue, and remember that thy attempt was with a reservation, that thou didst not desire

02:17:27.958 --> 02:17:29.338
to do impossibilities.

02:17:30.218 --> 02:17:31.818
What, then, didst thou desire?

02:17:32.878 --> 02:17:38.198
Some such effort is this, but thou attainest thy object if the things to which thou wast

02:17:38.198 --> 02:17:39.398
move are accomplished.

02:17:42.358 --> 02:17:48.138
He who loves fame considers another man's activity to be his own good, and he who loves

02:17:48.138 --> 02:17:54.198
pleasure his own sensations, but he who has understanding considers his own acts to be

02:17:54.198 --> 02:17:55.118
his own good.

02:17:57.418 --> 02:18:02.178
It is in our power to have no opinion about a thing, and not to be disturbed in our soul,

02:18:02.478 --> 02:18:05.658
for things themselves have no natural power to form our judgments.

02:18:08.958 --> 02:18:14.138
Accustom thyself to attend carefully to what is said by another, and as much as it is possible

02:18:14.138 --> 02:18:15.958
be in the speaker's mind.

02:18:17.938 --> 02:18:21.898
That which is not good for the swarm, neither is it good for the bee.

02:18:24.778 --> 02:18:30.058
If sailors abused the helmsman, or the sick the doctor, would they listen to anybody else?

02:18:30.478 --> 02:18:35.818
And how could the helmsman secure the safety of those in the ship, or the doctor, health of

02:18:35.818 --> 02:18:36.918
those whom he attends?

02:18:39.878 --> 02:18:44.778
How many together with whom I came into the world are already gone out of it?

02:18:47.238 --> 02:18:53.018
To the jaundiced honey tastes bitter, and to those bitten by mad dogs water causes fear,

02:18:53.558 --> 02:18:56.118
and to little children the ball is a fine thing.

02:18:56.958 --> 02:18:58.118
Why then am I angry?

02:18:58.638 --> 02:19:03.598
Dost thou think that a false opinion has less power than the bile in the jaundiced, or the

02:19:03.598 --> 02:19:05.838
poison in him who is bitten by a mad dog?

02:19:08.838 --> 02:19:12.338
No man will hinder thee from living according to the reason of thy nature.

02:19:12.338 --> 02:19:17.158
Nothing will happen to the country, to the reason of the universal nature.

02:19:21.098 --> 02:19:26.278
What kind of people are those whom men wish to please, and for what objects, and by what

02:19:26.278 --> 02:19:27.198
kinds of acts?

02:19:27.918 --> 02:19:33.158
How soon time will cover all things, and how many it has covered already.

02:19:47.278 --> 02:19:48.678
Thank you.

02:20:14.588 --> 02:20:15.848
What is badness?

02:20:15.848 --> 02:20:26.948
It is that which thou hast often seen, and on the occasion of everything which happens, keep this in mind, that it is that which thou hast often seen.

02:20:28.028 --> 02:20:40.048
Everywhere up and down thou wilt find the same things, with which the old histories are filled, those of the Middle Ages and those of our own day, with which cities and houses are filled now.

02:20:40.048 --> 02:20:45.428
There is nothing new. All things are both familiar and short-lived.

02:20:46.708 --> 02:20:55.648
2. How can our principles become dead, unless the impressions, thoughts, which correspond to them are extinguished?

02:20:56.308 --> 02:21:05.328
But it is in thy power continuously to fan these thoughts into a flame. I can have that opinion about anything which I ought to have.

02:21:05.328 --> 02:21:14.108
If I can, why am I disturbed? The things which are external to my mind have no relation at all to my mind.

02:21:14.948 --> 02:21:28.928
Let this be the state of thy effects, and thou standest erect. To recover thy life is in thy power. Look at things again as thou didst used to look at them, for in this consists the recovery of thy life.

02:21:29.688 --> 02:21:44.928
3. The idle business of show. Plays on the stage, flocks of sheep, herds, exercises with spears, a bone to cast to little dogs, a bit of bread into fish ponds,

02:21:45.968 --> 02:21:55.128
labourings of ants and burden-carrying, runnings about of frightened little mice, puppets pulled by strings, all alike.

02:21:56.148 --> 02:22:09.188
It is thy duty, then, in the midst of such things to show good humour and not a proud air, to understand, however, that every man is worth just so much as the things are worth about which he busies himself.

02:22:10.588 --> 02:22:28.008
4. In discourse thou must attend to what is said, and in every movement thou must observe what is doing, and in the one thou should see immediately to what end it refers, but in the other watch carefully what is the thing signified.

02:22:29.648 --> 02:22:50.448
5. Is my understanding sufficient for this or not? If it is sufficient, I use it for the work as an instrument given by the universal nature, but if it is not sufficient, then either I retire from the work and give way to him who is able to do it better, unless there be some reason why I ought not to do so,

02:22:50.448 --> 02:23:12.648
or I do it as well as I can, taking to help me the man who, with the aid of my ruling principle, can do what is now fit and useful for the general good, for whatsoever, either by myself or with another, I can do, ought to be directed to this only, to that which is useful and well suited to society.

02:23:14.048 --> 02:23:25.448
6. How many after being celebrated by fame have been given up to oblivion, and how many who have celebrated the fame of others have long been dead?

02:23:26.928 --> 02:23:44.868
7. Be not ashamed to be helped, for it is thy business to do thy duty like a soldier in the assault on a town. How then, if being lame thou canst not mount up on the battlements alone, but with the help of another it is possible?

02:23:46.328 --> 02:23:59.828
8. Let not future things disturb thee, for thou wilt come to them, if it shall be necessary, having with thee the same reason which now thou usest for present things.

02:24:01.168 --> 02:24:16.868
9. All things are implicated with one another, and the bond is holy, and there is hardly anything unconnected with any other thing, for things have been coordinated, and they combine to form the same universe, order.

02:24:16.868 --> 02:24:39.488
10. For there is one universe made up of all things, and one God who pervades all things, and one substance, and one law, one common reason in all intelligent animals, and one truth, if indeed there is also one perfection for all animals which are of the same stock and participate in the same reason.

02:24:40.488 --> 02:24:56.148
10. Everything material soon disappears in the substance of the whole, and everything formal, causal, is very soon taken back into the universal reason, and the memory of everything is very soon overwhelmed in time.

02:24:57.628 --> 02:25:04.328
11. To the rational animal the same act is according to nature and according to reason.

02:25:05.528 --> 02:25:09.328
12. Be thou erect, or be made erect.

02:25:10.668 --> 02:25:33.508
13. Just as it is with the members in those bodies which are united in one, so it is with rational beings which exist separate, for they have been constituted for one cooperation, and the perception of this will be more apparent to thee if thou often sayest to thyself that I am a member of the system of rational beings.

02:25:33.508 --> 02:25:52.108
14. But if thou sayest that thou art a part, thou dost not yet love men from thy heart. Magnificence does not yet delight thee for its own sake. Thou still doest it barely as a thing of propriety, and not yet as doing good to thyself.

02:25:53.868 --> 02:26:14.748
14. Let there fall externally what will on the parts which can feel the effects of this fall, for those parts which have felt will complain, if they choose. But I, unless I think that what has happened is an evil, am not injured, and it is in my power not to think so.

02:26:16.228 --> 02:26:32.488
15. Whatever any one does or says, I must be good. Just as if the gold, or the emerald, or the purple were always saying this, whatever any one does or says, I must be emerald and keep my color.

02:26:33.648 --> 02:26:50.268
16. The ruling faculty does not disturb itself, I mean does not frighten itself or cause itself pain. But if any one else can frighten or pain it, let him do so, for the faculty itself will not by its own opinion turn into such ways.

02:26:50.268 --> 02:27:12.388
17. Let the body itself take care, if it can, that it suffer nothing, and let it speak, if it suffers. But the soul itself, that which is subject to fear, to pain, which has completely the power of forming an opinion about these things, will suffer nothing, for it will never deviate into such a judgment.

02:27:12.388 --> 02:27:26.348
The leading principle in itself wants nothing, unless it makes a want for itself, and therefore it is both free from perturbation and unimpeded, if it does not disturb and impede itself.

02:27:28.028 --> 02:27:54.308
17. Eudaimonia, happiness, is a good demon or a good thing. What then art thou doing here, O imagination? Go away, I entreat thee by the gods, as thou didst come, for I want thee not. But thou art come according to thy old fashion. I am not angry with thee, only go away.

02:27:56.168 --> 02:28:17.508
18. Is any man afraid of change? Why, what can take place without change? What then is more pleasing or more suitable to the universal nature? And canst thou take a bath unless the wood undergoes a change? And canst thou be nourished unless the food undergoes a change?

02:28:17.508 --> 02:28:31.148
And can anything else that is useful be accomplished without change? Dost thou not see then that for thyself also to change is just the same, and equally necessary for the universal nature?

02:28:32.048 --> 02:28:59.448
19. Through the universal substance, as through a furious torrent, all bodies are carried, being by their nature united with and cooperating with the whole, as the parts of our body with one another. How many a Chrysippus, how many a Socrates, how many an Epictetus has time already swallowed up? And let the same thought occur to thee with reference to every man and thing.

02:29:01.028 --> 02:29:14.768
20. One thing only troubles me, lest I should do something which the constitution of man does not allow, or in the way which it does not allow, or what it does not allow now.

02:29:16.308 --> 02:29:24.108
21. Near is thy forgetfulness of all things, and near the forgetfulness of thee by all.

02:29:25.628 --> 02:29:51.108
22. It is peculiar to man to love even those who do wrong. And this happens, if when they do wrong it occurs to thee that they are kinsmen, and that they do wrong through ignorance and unintentionally, and that soon both of you will die, and above all, that the wrongdoer has done thee no harm, for he has not made thy ruling faculty worse than it was before.

02:29:52.528 --> 02:30:09.288
23. The universal nature out of the universal substance, as if it were wax, now molds a horse. And when it has broken this up, it uses the material for a tree, then for a man, then for something else.

02:30:09.948 --> 02:30:20.948
24. And each of these things subsists for a very short time. But it is no hardship for the vessel to be broken up, just as there was none in its being fastened together.

02:30:21.808 --> 02:30:38.008
24. A scowling look is altogether unnatural. When it is often assumed, the result is that all comeliness dies away, and at last is so completely extinguished that it cannot be again lighted up at all.

02:30:38.768 --> 02:30:50.308
25. Try to conclude from this very fact that it is contrary to reason. For if even the perception of doing wrong shall depart, what reason is there for living any longer?

02:30:52.268 --> 02:31:07.248
25. Nature which governs the whole will soon change all things which thou seest, and thou of their substance will make other things, and again other things from the substance of them, in order that the world may ever be new.

02:31:09.268 --> 02:31:26.568
26. When a man has done thee any wrong, immediately consider with what opinion about good or evil he has done wrong. For when thou hast seen this, thou wilt pity him, and wilt neither wonder nor be angry.

02:31:27.248 --> 02:31:46.808
27. For either thou thyself thinkest the same thing to be good that he does, or another thing of the same kind, it is thy duty then to pardon him. But if thou dost not think such things to be good or evil, thou wilt more readily be well disposed to him who is in error.

02:31:48.848 --> 02:32:05.108
27. Think not so much of what thou hast not, as of what thou hast. But of the things which thou hast select the best, and then reflect how eagerly they would have been sought, if thou hast them not.

02:32:19.628 --> 02:32:33.968
28. Retire into thyself. The rational principle which rules has this nature, that it is content with itself when it does what is just, and so secures tranquility.

02:32:35.708 --> 02:33:03.348
29. Wipe out the imagination. Stop the pulling of the strings. Confine thyself to the present. Understand well what happens either to thee or to another. Divide and distribute every object into the causal, formal, and the material. Think of thy last hour. Let the wrong which is done by a man stay there where the wrong was done.

02:33:05.048 --> 02:33:15.528
30. Direct thy attention to what is said. Let thy understanding enter into the things that are doing, and the things which do them.

02:33:16.908 --> 02:33:36.768
31. Adorn thyself with simplicity and modesty, and with indifference toward the things which lie between virtue and vice. Love mankind. Follow God. The poet says that law rules all, and it is enough to remember that law rules all.

02:33:38.008 --> 02:33:50.968
32. About death. Whether it is a dispersion or a resolution into atoms or annihilation, it is either extinction or change.

02:33:52.648 --> 02:34:17.608
33. About pain. The pain which is intolerable carries us off, but that which lasts a long time is tolerable, and the mind maintains its own tranquility by retiring into itself, and the ruling faculty is not made worse. But the parts which are harmed by pain, let them, if they can, give their opinion about it.

02:34:17.608 --> 02:34:42.648
34. About fame. Look at the minds of those who seek fame. Observe what they are, and what kind of things they avoid, and what kind of things they pursue. And consider that as the heaps of sand piled on one another hide the former sands, so in life the events which go before are soon covered by those which come after.

02:34:44.288 --> 02:35:07.708
35. From Plato. The man who has an elevated mind and takes a view of all time and of all substance, dost thou suppose it possible for him to think that human life is anything great? It is not possible, he said. Such a man then will think that death also is no evil. Certainly not.

02:35:07.708 --> 02:35:14.028
36. From Antisthenes. It is royal to do good and to be abused.

02:35:15.608 --> 02:35:30.068
37. It is a base thing for the countenance to be obedient and to regulate and compose itself as the mind commands, and for the mind not to be regulated and composed by itself.

02:35:31.748 --> 02:35:39.548
38. It is not right to vex ourselves at things, for they care not about it.

02:35:40.608 --> 02:35:45.568
39. To the immortal gods and us give joy.

02:35:47.508 --> 02:35:55.028
40. Life must be reaped like the ripe ears of corn. One man is born, another dies.

02:35:56.828 --> 02:36:05.388
41. If gods care not for me and for my children, there is a reason for it.

02:36:06.528 --> 02:36:11.768
42. For the good is with me and the just.

02:36:13.708 --> 02:36:20.148
43. No joining others in their wailing, no violent emotion.

02:36:21.008 --> 02:36:48.508
44. From Plato. But I would make this man a sufficient answer, which is this. Thou sayest not well, if thou thinkest that a man who is good for anything at all ought to compute the hazard of life or death, and should not rather look to this only in all that he does, whether he is doing what is just or unjust, and the works of a good or a bad man.

02:36:50.568 --> 02:37:16.368
45. For thus it is, men of Athens, in truth, wherever a man has placed himself thinking it the best place for him, or has been placed by a commander, there in my opinion he ought to stay and to abide the hazard, taking nothing into the reckoning, either death or anything else, before the baseness of deserting his post.

02:37:18.048 --> 02:37:41.208
46. But, my good friend, reflect whether that which is noble and good is not something different from saving and being saved. For as to a man living such or such a time, at least one who is really a man, consider if this is not a thing to be dismissed from the thoughts, and there must be no love of life.

02:37:41.208 --> 02:37:56.428
But as to these matters, a man must entrust them to the Deity, and believe what the women say, that no man can escape his destiny, the next inquiry being how he may best live the time that he has to live.

02:37:58.388 --> 02:38:14.468
47. Look round at the courses of the stars, as if thou wert going along with them, and constantly consider the changes of the elements into one another, for such thoughts purge away the filth of the terrine life.

02:38:16.348 --> 02:38:44.448
48. This is a fine saying of Plato, that he who is discoursing about men should look also at earthly things as if he viewed them from some higher place, should look at them in their assemblies, armies, agricultural labors, marriages, treaties, births, deaths, noise of the courts of justice, desert places, various nations of barbarism.

02:38:53.068 --> 02:39:14.448
49. Consider the past, such great changes of political supremacies. Thou mayest foresee also the things which will be, for they will certainly be of like form, and it is not possible that they should deviate from the order of the things which take place now.

02:39:15.988 --> 02:39:25.968
Accordingly, to have contemplated human life forty years is the same as to have contemplated it for ten thousand years. For what more wilt thou see?

02:39:27.348 --> 02:39:47.708
50. That which has grown from the earth to the earth, but that which has sprung from heavenly seed, back to the heavenly realms returns. This is either a dissolution of the mutual involution of the atoms, or a similar dispersion of the in-sanctioned elements.

02:39:47.708 --> 02:40:02.588
51. With food and drinks and cunning magic arts, turning the channel's course to escape from death, the breeze which heaven has sent, we must endure and toil without complaining.

02:40:04.428 --> 02:40:20.708
52. Another may be more expert in casting his opponent, but he is not more social, nor more modest, nor better disciplined to meet all that happens, nor more considerate with respect to the faults of his neighbors.

02:40:22.088 --> 02:40:41.628
53. Where any work can be done conformably to the reason which is common to gods and men, there we have nothing to fear. For where we are able to get profits by means of the activity which is successful and proceeds according to our constitution, there no harm is to be suspected.

02:40:43.428 --> 02:41:02.928
54. Everywhere and at all times it is in thy power piously to acquiesce in thy present condition, and to behave justly to those who are about thee, and to exert thy skill upon thy present thoughts, that nothing shall steal into them without being well examined.

02:41:04.328 --> 02:41:21.228
55. Do not look around thee to discover other men's ruling principles, but look straight to this, to what nature leads thee, both the universal nature through the things which happen to thee, and thy own nature through the acts which must be done by thee.

02:41:21.228 --> 02:41:39.368
56. But every being ought to do that which is according to its constitution, and all other things have been constituted for the sake of rational beings, just as among irrational things the inferior for the sake of the superior, but the rational for the sake of one another.

02:41:40.268 --> 02:42:03.348
57. The prime principle then in man's constitution is the social, and the second is not to yield to the persuasions of the body, for it is the peculiar office of the rational and intelligent motion to circumscribe itself, and never to be overpowered either by the motion of the senses or of the appetites, for both are animal.

02:42:03.348 --> 02:42:29.808
58. But the intelligent motion claims superiority, and does not permit itself to be overpowered by the others, and with good reason, for it is formed by nature to use all of them. The third thing in the rational constitution is freedom from error and from deception. Let then the ruling principle holding fast to these things go straight on, and it has what is its own.

02:42:33.428 --> 02:42:45.428
56. Consider thyself to be dead, and to have completed thy life up to the present time, and live according to nature the remainder which is allowed to thee.

02:42:47.188 --> 02:42:56.608
57. Love that only which happens to thee, and is spun with the thread of thy destiny, for what is more suitable.

02:42:57.568 --> 02:43:13.588
58. In everything which happens, keep before thy eyes those to whom the same things happened, and how they were vexed, and treated them as strange things, and found fault with them. And now where are they? Nowhere.

02:43:13.588 --> 02:43:40.268
59. Why then dost thou too choose to act in the same way? And why dost thou not leave these agitations which are foreign to nature, and those who cause them, and those who are moved by them? And why art thou not altogether intent upon the right way of making use of the things which happen to thee? For then thou wilt use them well, and they will be a material for thee to work on.

02:43:40.968 --> 02:43:48.308
Only attend to thyself, and resolve to be a good man in every act which thou doest, and remember.

02:43:50.468 --> 02:43:59.468
59. Look within. Within is the fountain of good, and it will ever bubble up, if thou wilt ever dig.

02:44:01.648 --> 02:44:23.628
60. The body ought to be compact, and to show no irregularity either in motion or attitude. For what the mind shows in the face, by maintaining in it the expression of intelligence and propriety, that ought to be required also in the whole body. But all these things should be observed without affectation.

02:44:25.488 --> 02:44:38.428
61. The art of life is more like the wrestler's art than the dancer's. In respect of this, that it should stand ready and firm to meet onsets which are sudden and unexpected.

02:44:40.308 --> 02:45:01.428
62. Constantly observe who those are whose approbation thou wishest to have, and what ruling principles they possess. For then thou wilt neither blame those who offend involuntarily, nor wilt thou want their approbation, if thou lookest to the sources of their opinions and appetites.

02:45:02.508 --> 02:45:26.168
63. Every soul, the philosopher says, is involuntarily deprived of truth. Consequently, in the same way, it is deprived of justice, and temperance, and benevolence, and everything of the kind. It is most necessary to bear this constantly in mind, for thus thou wilt be more gentle towards all.

02:45:27.668 --> 02:45:44.828
64. In every pain let this thought be present, that there is no dishonor in it, nor does it make the governing intelligence worse, for it does not damage the intelligence either so far as the intelligence is rational, or so far as it is social.

02:45:45.628 --> 02:46:02.048
65. Indeed, in the case of most pains, let this remark of Epicurus aid thee, that pain is neither intolerable nor everlasting, if thou bearest in mind that it has limits, and if thou addest nothing to it in imagination.

02:46:02.928 --> 02:46:27.908
And remember this, too, that we do not perceive that many things which are disagreeable to us are the same as pain, such as excessive drowsiness, and the being scorched by heat, and the having no appetite. When then thou art discontented about any of these things, say to thyself that thou art yielding to pain.

02:46:30.228 --> 02:46:36.648
65. Take care not to feel towards the inhuman as they feel towards men.

02:46:37.428 --> 02:47:05.168
66. How do we know if Tellogus was not superior in character to Socrates? For it is not enough that Socrates dies a more noble death, and disputed more skillfully with the sophists, and passed the night in the cold with more endurance, and that when he was bid to arrest Leon of Salamis, he considered it more noble to refuse, and that he walked in a swaggering way in the streets.

02:47:06.008 --> 02:47:10.188
Though as to this fact one may have great doubts if it was true.

02:47:10.188 --> 02:47:39.548
But we ought to inquire what kind of a soul it was that Socrates possessed, and if he was able to be content with being just towards men and pious towards the gods, neither idly vexed on account of men's villainy, nor yet making himself a slave to any man's ignorance, nor receiving as strange anything that fell to his share out of the universal, nor enduring it as intolerable.

02:47:39.548 --> 02:47:46.608
Nor allowing his understanding to sympathize with the effects of the miserable flesh.

02:47:47.588 --> 02:48:04.368
67. Nature has not so mingled the intelligence with the composition of the body, as not to have allowed thee the power of circumscribing thyself, and of bringing under subjection to thyself all that is thy own.

02:48:04.368 --> 02:48:10.548
For it is very possible to be a divine man, and to be recognized as such by no one.

02:48:11.508 --> 02:48:19.568
Always bear this in mind, and another thing too, that very little indeed is necessary for living a happy life.

02:48:20.208 --> 02:48:33.608
And because thou hast despaired of becoming a dialectician, and skilled in the knowledge of nature, do not for this reason renounce the hope of being both free and modest, and social and obedient to God.

02:48:34.388 --> 02:48:52.368
68. It is in thy power to live free from all compulsion and the greatest tranquillity of mind, even if all the world cry out against thee as much as they choose, and even if wild beasts tear in pieces the members of this needed matter which has grown around thee.

02:48:52.368 --> 02:49:10.368
For what hinders the mind in the midst of all this from maintaining itself in tranquillity, and in a just judgment of all surrounding things, and in a ready use of the objects which are presented to it, so that the judgment may say to the thing which falls under its observation,

02:49:11.228 --> 02:49:25.428
This thou art in substance. Though in men's opinion thou mayest appear to be of a different kind, and the youth shall say to that which falls under the hand, thou art the thing that I was seeking.

02:49:25.428 --> 02:49:39.228
For to me that which represents itself is always a material for virtue, both rational and political, and, in a word, for the exercise of art, which belongs to man or God.

02:49:40.188 --> 02:49:51.268
For everything which happens has a relationship either to God or man, and is neither new nor difficult to handle, but usual and apt matter to work on.

02:49:52.668 --> 02:50:05.508
69. The perfection of moral character consists in this, in passing every day as the last, and in being neither violently excited nor torpid nor playing the hypocrite.

02:50:07.528 --> 02:50:24.408
70. The gods who are immortal are not vexed because during so long a time they must tolerate continually men such as they are, and so many of them bad, and besides this they also take care of them in all ways.

02:50:24.408 --> 02:50:34.688
But thou, who art destined to end so soon, art thou wearied of enduring the bad, and this too when thou art one of them?

02:50:36.108 --> 02:50:48.788
71. It is a ridiculous thing for a man not to fly from his own badness, which is indeed possible, but to fly from other men's badness, which is impossible.

02:50:50.208 --> 02:51:01.888
72. Whatever the rational and political faculty finds to be neither intelligent nor social, it properly judges to be inferior to itself.

02:51:03.588 --> 02:51:21.048
73. When thou hast done a good act and another hast received it, why dost thou still look for a third thing besides these, as fools do, either to have the reputation of having done a good act or to obtain a return?

02:51:23.588 --> 02:51:36.228
74. No man is tired of receiving what is useful, but it is useful to act according to nature. Do not then be tired of receiving what is useful by doing it to others.

02:51:37.208 --> 02:52:04.048
75. The nature of the All moved to make the universe, but now either everything that takes place comes by way of consequence or continuity, or even the chief things towards which the ruling power of the universe directs its own movement are governed by no rational principle. If this is remembered, it will make thee more tranquil in many things.

02:52:05.408 --> 02:52:11.988
Note 1. The end of this section is unintelligible.

02:53:05.448 --> 02:53:11.848
This reflection also tends to the removal of the desire of empty fame, that it is no longer in

02:53:11.848 --> 02:53:17.468
thy power to have lived the whole of thy life, or at least thy life from thy youth upwards,

02:53:17.748 --> 02:53:24.668
like a philosopher. But both to many others and to thyself, it is plain that thou art far from

02:53:24.668 --> 02:53:32.228
philosophy. Thou hast fallen into disorder then, so that it is no longer easy for thee to get the

02:53:32.228 --> 02:53:39.968
reputation of a philosopher, and thy plan of life also opposes it. If then thou hast truly seen

02:53:39.968 --> 02:53:47.288
where the matter lies, throw away the thought. How thou shalt seem to others, and be content

02:53:47.288 --> 02:53:54.588
if thou shalt live the rest of thy life in such wise as thy nature wills. Observe then what it

02:53:54.588 --> 02:54:01.788
wills, and let nothing else distract thee. But thou hast had experience of many wanderings without

02:54:01.788 --> 02:54:11.108
having found happiness anywhere, not in syllogisms, nor in wealth, nor in reputation, nor in enjoyment,

02:54:11.628 --> 02:54:21.308
nor anywhere. Where is it then? In doing what man's nature requires. How then shall a man do this?

02:54:21.868 --> 02:54:27.988
If he has principles, from which come his effects and his acts. What principles?

02:54:29.048 --> 02:54:34.288
Those which relate to good and bad. The belief that there is nothing good for man,

02:54:34.608 --> 02:54:40.808
which does not make him just, temperate, manly, free, and that there is nothing bad,

02:54:41.228 --> 02:54:44.608
which does not do the contrary to what has been mentioned.

02:54:46.388 --> 02:54:55.528
On the occasion of every act, ask thyself, how is this with respect to me? Shall I repent of it?

02:54:56.028 --> 02:55:03.668
A little time, and I am dead, and all is gone. What more do I seek, if what I am doing now

02:55:03.668 --> 02:55:10.748
is the work of an intelligent living being, and a social being, and one who is under the same law with God?

02:55:14.028 --> 02:55:21.468
Alexander, and Caius, and Pompeius. What are they in comparison with Diogenes, and Heraclitus,

02:55:21.708 --> 02:55:30.248
and Socrates? For they were acquainted with things, and their causes, forms, and their matter,

02:55:30.428 --> 02:55:37.048
and the ruling principles of these men were the same, or conformable to their pursuits.

02:55:37.768 --> 02:55:41.968
But as to the others, how many things had they to care for,

02:55:42.728 --> 02:55:45.568
and to how many things were they slaves?

02:55:49.828 --> 02:55:56.028
Consider that men will do the same things nevertheless, even though thou shouldst burst.

02:55:59.768 --> 02:56:07.868
This is the chief thing. Be not perturbed, for all things are according to the nature of the universal,

02:56:08.708 --> 02:56:15.328
and in a little time thou wilt be nobody and nowhere, like Hadrianus and Augustus.

02:56:16.308 --> 02:56:21.968
In the next place, having fixed thy eye steadily on thy business, look at it,

02:56:21.968 --> 02:56:26.008
and at the same time remembering that it is thy duty to do the same thing,

02:56:26.008 --> 02:56:32.668
to be a good man, and what man's nature demands. Do that without turning aside,

02:56:33.448 --> 02:56:39.748
and speak as it seems to thee most just, only let it be with a good disposition,

02:56:40.508 --> 02:56:43.968
and with modesty, and without hypocrisy.

02:56:47.888 --> 02:56:54.848
The nature of the universal has this work to do, to remove to that place the things which

02:56:54.848 --> 02:57:01.188
are in this, to change them, to take them away hence, and to carry them there.

02:57:01.868 --> 02:57:06.228
All things are change, yet we need not fear anything new.

02:57:07.088 --> 02:57:13.668
All things are familiar to us, but the distribution of them still remains the same.

02:57:16.828 --> 02:57:21.708
Every nature is contented with itself when it goes on its way well,

02:57:22.268 --> 02:57:28.788
and a rational nature goes on its way well, when in its thoughts it ascends to nothing false

02:57:28.788 --> 02:57:36.088
or uncertain, and when it directs its movements to social acts only, and when it confines its

02:57:36.088 --> 02:57:42.708
desires and aversions to the things which are in its power, and when it is satisfied with everything

02:57:42.708 --> 02:57:49.988
that is assigned to it by the common nature. For of this common nature every particular nature

02:57:49.988 --> 02:57:57.488
is a part, as the nature of the leaf is a part of the nature of the plant, except that in the plant

02:57:57.488 --> 02:58:04.468
the nature of the leaf is part of a nature which has not perception or reason, and is subject to

02:58:04.468 --> 02:58:11.388
be impeded. But the nature of man is part of a nature which is not subject to impediments,

02:58:11.748 --> 02:58:17.308
and is intelligent and just, since it gives to everything in equal portions,

02:58:17.308 --> 02:58:26.928
and according to its worth, times, substance, cause, form, activity, and incident. But examine

02:58:26.928 --> 02:58:33.888
not to discover that any one thing compared with any other single thing is equal in all respects,

02:58:34.368 --> 02:58:41.108
but by taking all the parts together of one thing and comparing them with all the parts together

02:58:41.108 --> 02:58:42.308
of another.

02:58:45.888 --> 02:58:53.868
Thou hast not leisure or ability to read, but thou hast leisure or ability to check arrogance.

02:58:54.788 --> 02:59:01.668
Thou hast leisure to be superior to pleasure and pain. Thou hast leisure to be superior to love

02:59:01.668 --> 02:59:09.188
of fame, and not to be vexed at stupid and ungrateful people, nay even to care for them.

02:59:13.568 --> 02:59:19.988
Let no man any longer hear thee finding fault with the court life or with thy own.

02:59:25.128 --> 02:59:31.668
Repentance is a kind of self-reproof for having neglected something useful, but that which is

02:59:31.668 --> 02:59:39.228
good must be something useful, and the perfect good man should look after it. But no such man

02:59:39.228 --> 02:59:45.968
would ever repent of having refused any sensual pleasure. Pleasure, then, is neither good nor

02:59:45.968 --> 02:59:59.128
useful. This thing, what is it in itself, in its own constitution? What is its substance and material,

03:00:00.188 --> 03:00:08.448
and what its causal nature or form, and what is it doing in the world, and how long does it

03:00:08.448 --> 03:00:18.948
persist? When thou risest from sleep with reluctance, remember that it is according to

03:00:18.948 --> 03:00:25.228
thy constitution, and according to human nature, to perform social acts. But sleeping is common

03:00:25.228 --> 03:00:33.608
also to irrational animals. But that which is according to each individual's nature is also more

03:00:33.608 --> 03:00:39.928
peculiarly its own, and more suitable to its nature, and indeed also more agreeable.

03:00:44.408 --> 03:00:50.708
Constantly, and, if it be possible, on the occasion of every impression on the soul,

03:00:51.448 --> 03:00:56.488
apply to it the principles of physics, of ethics, of dialectics.

03:00:59.488 --> 03:01:04.148
Whatever man thou meetest with, immediately say to thyself,

03:01:04.848 --> 03:01:11.608
What opinions has this man about good and bad? For it, with respect to pleasure and pain,

03:01:11.768 --> 03:01:18.028
and the causes of each, and with respect to famine and ignominy, death and life,

03:01:18.348 --> 03:01:24.148
he has such and such opinions. It will seem nothing wonderful or strange to me,

03:01:24.148 --> 03:01:30.948
if he does such and such things. And I shall bear in mind that he is compelled to do so.

03:01:34.748 --> 03:01:42.128
Remember that as it is a shame to be surprised if the fig tree produces figs, so it is to be

03:01:42.128 --> 03:01:48.908
surprised if the world produces such and such things of which it is productive. And for the

03:01:49.968 --> 03:01:58.148
helmsman, it is a shame to be surprised if a man has a fever, or if the wind, if unfavorable.

03:02:01.868 --> 03:02:06.688
Remember that to change thy opinion and to follow him who corrects thy error

03:02:06.688 --> 03:02:13.668
is as consistent with freedom as it is to persist in thy error. For it is thy own,

03:02:13.668 --> 03:02:18.368
the activity which is exerted according to thy own movement and judgment,

03:02:19.028 --> 03:02:22.928
and indeed according to thy own understanding, too.

03:02:26.148 --> 03:02:33.588
If a thing is in thy own power, why dost thou do it? But if it is in the power of another,

03:02:34.108 --> 03:02:43.368
whom dost thou blame? The atoms, chance, or the gods? Both are foolish. Thou must blame nobody.

03:02:43.668 --> 03:02:51.528
For if thou canst correct what is the cause, but if thou canst not do this, correct at least the

03:02:51.528 --> 03:02:59.188
thing itself. But if thou canst not do even this, of what use it to thee to find fault?

03:02:59.968 --> 03:03:02.668
For nothing should be done without a purpose.

03:03:06.248 --> 03:03:15.008
That which has died falls not out of the universe. If it stays here, it also changes here and is

03:03:15.008 --> 03:03:21.608
dissolved into its proper parts, which are elements of the universe and of thyself. And these, too,

03:03:21.768 --> 03:03:24.048
change, and they murmur not.

03:03:27.668 --> 03:03:36.168
Everything exists for some end, a horse, a vine. Why dost thou wonder? Even the sun will say,

03:03:36.648 --> 03:03:44.068
I am for some purpose, and the rest of the gods will say the same. For what purpose then art thou,

03:03:44.408 --> 03:03:49.568
to enjoy pleasure? See if common sense allows this.

03:03:53.028 --> 03:03:59.948
Nature has had regard in everything no less to the end than to the beginning, and the continuance,

03:04:00.208 --> 03:04:06.128
just like the man who throws up a ball. What good is it, then, for the ball to be thrown up,

03:04:06.428 --> 03:04:13.048
or harm for it to come down, or even to have fallen? And what good is it to the bubble while

03:04:13.048 --> 03:04:19.548
it holds together, or what harm when it is burst? The same may be said of a light also,

03:04:19.548 --> 03:04:29.168
though. Turn it, the body, inside out, and see what kind of thing it is, and when it has grown

03:04:29.168 --> 03:04:37.828
old, what kind of thing it becomes, and when it is diseased. Short-lived are both the praiser and

03:04:37.828 --> 03:04:46.088
the praised, and the rememberer and the remembered. And all this in a nook of this part of the world,

03:04:46.088 --> 03:04:55.028
and not even here do all agree, no, not any one with himself, and the whole earth, too, is a point.

03:04:59.688 --> 03:05:06.008
Attend to the matter which is before thee, whether it is an opinion, or an act, or a word.

03:05:06.888 --> 03:05:14.548
Thou suffer'st this justly, for thou choose'st rather to become good tomorrow than to be good

03:05:14.548 --> 03:05:23.508
today. Am I doing anything? I do it with reference to the good of mankind.

03:05:24.728 --> 03:05:30.148
Does anything happen to me? I receive it and refer it to the gods,

03:05:30.628 --> 03:05:35.368
and the source of all things, from which all that happens is derived.

03:05:38.648 --> 03:05:46.308
Such as bathing appears to thee, oil, sweat, dirt, filthy water, all things disgusting,

03:05:47.408 --> 03:05:58.728
so is every part of life and everything. Lucilla saw Varus die, and then Lucilla died.

03:05:59.528 --> 03:06:10.548
Secunda saw Maximus die, and then Secunda died. Epitecanos saw Deotemus die, and then Epitecanos

03:06:10.548 --> 03:06:18.628
died. Antoninus saw Faustina die, and then Antoninus died. Such is everything.

03:06:19.868 --> 03:06:28.048
Chaelor saw Hadrianus die, and then Chaelor died. And those sharp-witted men, either seers or men

03:06:28.048 --> 03:06:35.868
inflated with pride, where are they? For instance, the sharp-witted men Charax and Demetrius,

03:06:36.028 --> 03:06:44.708
the Platonists, and Eudaimon, and anyone else like them, all ephemeral, dead long ago.

03:06:45.768 --> 03:06:52.428
Some indeed have not been remembered even for a short time, and others have become the heroes

03:06:52.428 --> 03:07:00.388
of fables, and again others have disappeared even from fables. Remember this, then, that this

03:07:00.388 --> 03:07:08.348
little compound thyself must either be dissolved or thy poor breath must be extinguished or be

03:07:08.348 --> 03:07:18.748
removed and placed elsewhere. It is satisfaction to a man to do the proper works of a man.

03:07:18.748 --> 03:07:26.148
Now it is a proper work of a man to be benevolent to his own kind, to despise the movements of the

03:07:26.148 --> 03:07:33.328
senses, to form a just judgment of plausible appearances, and to take a survey of the nature

03:07:33.328 --> 03:07:48.728
of the universe and of the things which happen in it. There are three relations between thee and

03:07:48.728 --> 03:07:55.768
the other, to the divine cause from which all things come to all, and the third to those who

03:07:55.768 --> 03:08:05.948
live with thee. Pain is either an evil to the body, then let the body say what it thinks of it,

03:08:06.428 --> 03:08:14.428
or to the soul. But it is in the power of the soul to maintain its own serenity and tranquility,

03:08:14.428 --> 03:08:21.148
and not to think that pain is an evil. For every judgment and movement and desire

03:08:21.148 --> 03:08:33.028
and aversion is within, and no evil ascends so high. Wipe out thy imaginations by often saying

03:08:33.028 --> 03:08:41.128
to thyself, now it is in my power to let no badness be in this soul, nor desire, nor any

03:08:41.128 --> 03:08:48.708
perturbation at all. But looking at all things, I see what is their nature, and I use each according

03:08:48.708 --> 03:09:00.908
to its value. Remember this power which thou hast from nature. Speak both in the Senate and to every

03:09:00.908 --> 03:09:09.168
man, whoever he may be, appropriately, not with any affectation. Use plain discourse.

03:09:13.248 --> 03:09:23.768
Augustus court, wife, daughter, descendants, ancestors, sister, Agrippa, kinsmen, intimates,

03:09:24.248 --> 03:09:32.948
friends, Arius, Machinus, physicians, and sacrificing priests. The whole court is dead.

03:09:33.708 --> 03:09:39.668
Then turn to the rest, not considering the death of a single man, but of a whole race,

03:09:39.668 --> 03:09:46.848
as of the Pompeii, and that which is inscribed on the tombs, the last of his race.

03:09:47.368 --> 03:09:52.768
Then consider what trouble those before them have had that they might leave a successor,

03:09:53.388 --> 03:10:02.568
and then that of necessity someone must be the last. Again, here consider the death of a whole race.

03:10:06.748 --> 03:10:14.368
It is thy duty to order thy life well in every single act, and if every act does its duty as far

03:10:14.368 --> 03:10:22.628
as is possible, be content, and no one is able to hinder thee, so that each act shall not do its duty.

03:10:23.768 --> 03:10:29.728
But something external will stand in the way. Nothing will stand in the way of thy acting

03:10:29.728 --> 03:10:36.668
justly and soberly and considerably, but perhaps some other active power will be hindered.

03:10:37.308 --> 03:10:43.788
Well, but by acquiescing in the hindrance and by being content to transfer thy efforts to that

03:10:43.788 --> 03:10:50.468
which is allowed, another opportunity of action is immediately put before thee in place of that

03:10:50.468 --> 03:10:56.688
which was hindered, and one will adapt itself to this ordering of which we are speaking.

03:11:01.448 --> 03:11:07.008
Receive wealth or prosperity without arrogance, and be ready to let it go.

03:11:10.448 --> 03:11:18.788
If thou didst ever see a hand cut off, or a foot, or a head lying anywhere apart from the rest of the

03:11:18.788 --> 03:11:26.028
body, which does a man make himself as far as he can who is not content with what happens,

03:11:26.028 --> 03:11:31.088
and separates himself from others, or does anything unsocial,

03:11:32.528 --> 03:11:39.468
suppose that thou hast detached thyself from the natural unity, for thou wast made by nature

03:11:39.468 --> 03:11:46.388
apart, but now thou hast cut thyself off. Yet here there is this beautiful provision,

03:11:47.248 --> 03:11:53.668
that it is in thy power again to unite thyself. God has allowed this to no other part,

03:11:53.668 --> 03:12:00.948
after it has been separated and cut asunder to come together again. But consider the kindness

03:12:00.948 --> 03:12:08.188
by which he has distinguished man, for he has put it in his power not to be separated at all from

03:12:08.188 --> 03:12:15.468
the universal, and when he has been separated, he has allowed him to return and to be united,

03:12:15.968 --> 03:12:18.648
and to resume his place as apart.

03:12:21.688 --> 03:12:28.448
As the nature of the universal has given to every rational being all the other powers that it has,

03:12:29.028 --> 03:12:36.588
so we have received from it this power also. For as the universal nature converts and fixes

03:12:36.588 --> 03:12:43.528
in its predestined place everything which stands in the way and opposes it, and makes such things

03:12:43.528 --> 03:12:50.628
apart of itself, so also the rational animal is able to make every hindrance its own material,

03:12:51.108 --> 03:12:55.428
and to use it for such purposes as it may have designed.

03:12:59.748 --> 03:13:07.128
Do not disturb thyself by thinking of the whole of thy life. Let not thy thoughts at once embrace

03:13:07.128 --> 03:13:13.088
all the various troubles which thou mayest expect to befall thee, but on every occasion

03:13:13.088 --> 03:13:20.628
ask thyself, what is there in this which is intolerable and past bearing? For thou wilt

03:13:20.628 --> 03:13:27.408
be ashamed to confess. In the next place remember that neither the future nor the past pains thee,

03:13:27.568 --> 03:13:34.908
but only the present. But this is reduced to a very little, if thou only circumscribest it

03:13:34.908 --> 03:13:40.158
and chidest thy mind if it is unable to hold out against even this.

03:13:44.588 --> 03:13:53.468
Does Panthea or Pergamos now sit by the tomb of Verus? Does Chaureus or Deometas sit by the

03:13:53.468 --> 03:14:00.978
tomb of Hadrianus? That would be ridiculous. Well suppose they did sit there, would the dead be

03:14:00.978 --> 03:14:07.858
conscious of it? And if the dead were conscious, would they be pleased? And if they were pleased,

03:14:08.238 --> 03:14:15.338
would that make them immortal? Was it not in the order of destiny that these persons should first

03:14:15.338 --> 03:14:22.778
become old women and old men and then die? What then would those do after these were dead?

03:14:23.298 --> 03:14:26.598
All this is foul smell and blood in a bag.

03:14:30.098 --> 03:14:38.238
If thou can see sharp, look and judge wisely, says the philosopher. In the constitution of the

03:14:38.238 --> 03:14:45.158
rational animal, I see no virtue which is opposed to justice, but I see a virtue which is opposed

03:14:45.158 --> 03:14:56.378
to love of pleasure, and that is temperance. If thou takest away thy opinion about that which

03:14:56.378 --> 03:15:05.058
to give thee pain, thou thyself standest in perfect security. Who is this self, the reason?

03:15:05.838 --> 03:15:12.298
But I am not reason, be it so. Let then the reason itself not trouble itself,

03:15:13.078 --> 03:15:19.058
but if any other part of thee suffers, let it have its own opinion about itself.

03:15:22.358 --> 03:15:29.638
Hindrance to the perceptions of sense is an evil to the animal nature. Hindrance to the movement's

03:15:29.638 --> 03:15:37.618
desires is equally an evil to the animal nature, and something else also is equally an impediment

03:15:37.618 --> 03:15:45.478
and evil to the constitution of plants. So then that which is a hindrance to the intelligence

03:15:45.478 --> 03:15:50.758
is an evil to the intelligent nature. Apply all these things to thyself.

03:15:51.838 --> 03:15:57.118
Does pain or sensuous pleasure affect thee? The senses will look to that.

03:15:57.818 --> 03:16:04.378
Has any obstacle opposed thee in thy efforts toward an object? If indeed thou was making

03:16:04.378 --> 03:16:13.458
this effort absolutely, unconditionally, or without any reservation, certainly this obstacle is an

03:16:13.458 --> 03:16:19.478
irrational animal. But if thou takest into consideration the usual course of things,

03:16:19.758 --> 03:16:26.538
thou hast not yet been injured or even impeded. The things, however, which are proper to the

03:16:26.538 --> 03:16:34.738
understanding, no other man is used to impede, for neither fire nor iron nor tyrant nor purse

03:16:34.738 --> 03:16:42.098
touches it in any way. When it has been made a sphere, it continues a sphere.

03:16:47.258 --> 03:16:55.338
It is not fit that I should give myself pain, for I have never intentionally given pain even to another.

03:16:59.138 --> 03:17:05.258
Different things delight different people, but it is my delight to keep the ruling faculty sound

03:17:05.258 --> 03:17:12.458
without turning either from any man or from any of the things which happen to man, but looking at

03:17:12.458 --> 03:17:18.018
receiving all with welcome eyes and using everything according to its nature.

03:17:22.398 --> 03:17:29.178
See that thou secure this present time to thyself. For those who rather pursue posthumous fame,

03:17:29.498 --> 03:17:36.798
do not consider that the men of after time will be exactly such as these whom they cannot bear now,

03:17:36.798 --> 03:17:43.978
and both are mortal. And what is it in any way to thee if these men of after time utter this

03:17:43.978 --> 03:17:48.058
or that sound, or have this or that opinion about thee?

03:17:51.898 --> 03:17:57.478
Take me and cast me where thou wilt, for there I shall keep my divine part tranquil,

03:17:57.858 --> 03:18:03.198
that is, content if it can feel and act comfortably to its proper constitution.

03:18:04.258 --> 03:18:11.478
Is this change of place sufficient reason why man, my soul, should be unhappy and worse than it was,

03:18:11.758 --> 03:18:18.918
depressed, expanded, shrinking, or frightened? And what wilt thou find which is sufficient reason for this?

03:18:22.698 --> 03:18:33.078
Nothing can happen to any man which is not human accident, nor to an ox which is not according to

03:18:33.078 --> 03:18:40.158
nature of a vine, nor to a stone which is not proper to a stone. If then there happens to each

03:18:40.158 --> 03:18:47.018
thing both what is usual and natural, why shouldst thou complain? For the common nature brings nothing

03:18:47.018 --> 03:18:57.578
which may not be borne by thee. If thou art pained by any external thing, it is not this that

03:18:58.158 --> 03:19:04.878
but by thy own judgment about it, and it is in thy power to wipe out this judgment now.

03:19:05.498 --> 03:19:11.158
But if anything in thy own disposition gives thee pain, who hinders thee from correcting thy opinion?

03:19:11.318 --> 03:19:17.438
And even if thou art pained because thou art not doing some particular thing which seems to thee

03:19:17.438 --> 03:19:24.898
to be right, why dost thou not rather act than complain? But some insuperable obstacle is in

03:19:24.898 --> 03:19:32.918
thy way. Do not be grieved then, for the cause of its not being done depends not on thee. But it is

03:19:32.918 --> 03:19:40.358
not worthwhile to live. If this cannot be done, take thy departure then from life contentedly,

03:19:40.418 --> 03:19:47.258
just as he dies who is in full activity, and well pleased to with the things which are obstacles.

03:19:50.638 --> 03:19:57.498
Remember that the ruling faculty is invincible. When self-collected, it is satisfied with itself.

03:19:57.858 --> 03:20:04.018
If it does nothing which it does not choose to do, even if it resists from mere obstinacy,

03:20:04.798 --> 03:20:10.878
what then will it meet when it forms a judgment about anything aided by reason and deliberately?

03:20:12.058 --> 03:20:17.238
Therefore, the mind which is freedom from passions is a citadel. For man is free from

03:20:17.238 --> 03:20:23.438
nothing more secure to which he can fly for refuge and for the future to be inexpungible.

03:20:24.438 --> 03:20:30.898
He then who has not seen this is an ignorant man, but he who has seen it and does not fly

03:20:30.898 --> 03:20:41.158
to this refuge is unhappy. Say nothing more to thyself than what the first appearances report.

03:20:41.958 --> 03:20:46.558
Suppose that it has been reported to thee that a certain person speaks ill of thee.

03:20:47.238 --> 03:20:52.038
This has been reported, but that thou hast been injured this has not been reported.

03:20:52.758 --> 03:20:58.758
I see that my child is sick, I do see, but that he is in danger I do not see.

03:20:59.858 --> 03:21:05.598
Thus then always abide by the permanent appearances, and add nothing thyself from within,

03:21:05.598 --> 03:21:11.758
and when nothing happens to thee, or rather add something like a man who knows everything

03:21:11.758 --> 03:21:19.678
that happens in the world. A cucumber is bitter, throw it away.

03:21:20.698 --> 03:21:27.158
There are briars in the road, turn aside from them. This is enough. Do not add,

03:21:27.598 --> 03:21:35.378
and why were such things made in the world? For thou wilt be ridiculed by a man who is

03:21:35.378 --> 03:21:40.458
ridiculed by a carpenter and a shoemaker, if thou didst find fault, because thou seest in

03:21:40.458 --> 03:21:46.558
their workshops savings and cuttings from which they make. And yet they have places into which

03:21:46.558 --> 03:21:51.998
they can throw these shavings and cuttings, and the universal nature has no external space.

03:21:52.538 --> 03:21:57.898
But the wondrous part of her art is that though she has circumscribed herself,

03:21:58.098 --> 03:22:02.958
everything within her which appears to decay and to grow old and to be useless,

03:22:02.958 --> 03:22:10.338
she changes into herself, and again makes new things from these very same, so that she requires

03:22:10.338 --> 03:22:16.618
neither substance from without, nor wants a place into which she may cast that which delays.

03:22:17.298 --> 03:22:22.438
She is content then with her own space, and her own matter, and her own heart.

03:22:26.958 --> 03:22:32.078
Neither in thy actions be sluggish, nor in thy conversation without method,

03:22:32.618 --> 03:22:37.718
nor wandering in thy thoughts, nor let there be in thy soul inward contention

03:22:37.718 --> 03:22:43.478
or external effusion, nor in life be so busy as to leave no pleasure.

03:22:46.138 --> 03:22:53.758
Suppose that men kill thee, cut thee in pieces, curse thee. What then can these things do to

03:22:53.758 --> 03:23:01.878
prevent thy mind from remaining pure, wise, sober, just? For instance, if a man should stand by a

03:23:01.878 --> 03:23:08.258
limpid pure spring and curse it, the spring never ceases setting up potable water. And if he should

03:23:08.258 --> 03:23:15.338
cast clay into it or filth, it will speedily disperse them and wash them out, and will not be

03:23:15.338 --> 03:23:21.938
at all polluted. How then shall thou possess a perpetual fountain and not a mere wall,

03:23:22.438 --> 03:23:28.838
by forming thyself hourly to freedom, conjoined with contentment, simplicity, and modesty?

03:23:32.618 --> 03:23:40.778
He who does not know what the world is, does not know where he is. And he who does not know for what

03:23:40.778 --> 03:23:48.958
purpose the world exists, does not know who he is, nor what the world is. But he who has failed in

03:23:48.958 --> 03:23:55.898
any of these things could not even say for what purpose he exists himself. What then does thou

03:23:55.898 --> 03:24:02.478
think of him who avoids or seeks the praise of those who applaud, of men who know not either

03:24:02.478 --> 03:24:10.838
where they are or who they are? Does thou wish to be praised by a man who curses himself Christ

03:24:10.838 --> 03:24:19.038
every hour? Wouldst thou wish to please a man who does not please himself? Does a man please himself

03:24:19.038 --> 03:24:28.518
who repents of nearly everything that he does? No longer let thy breathing only act in concert

03:24:28.518 --> 03:24:34.458
with the air which surrounds thee, but let thy intelligence also now be in harmony with the

03:24:34.458 --> 03:24:41.058
intelligence which embraces all things. For the intelligent power is no less diffused in all parts

03:24:41.058 --> 03:24:47.438
and pervades all things from him who is willing to draw it to him than the aerial power for him who

03:24:47.438 --> 03:24:57.758
is able to respire it. Generally wickedness does no harm at all to the universe and particularly

03:24:57.758 --> 03:25:04.538
the wickedness of one man does no harm or another. It is only harmful to him who has it in his power

03:25:04.538 --> 03:25:14.998
to be released from it as soon as he shall choose. To my own free will, the free will of my neighbor

03:25:14.998 --> 03:25:21.478
is just as indifferent as his poor health and flesh. For though we are made especially for the

03:25:21.478 --> 03:25:28.358
sake of one another, still the ruling power of each of us has its own office, for otherwise my

03:25:28.358 --> 03:25:34.358
neighbor's wickedness would be my harm, which God has not willed in order that my unhappiness

03:25:34.358 --> 03:25:43.238
might not depend on another. The sun appears to be poured down

03:25:43.798 --> 03:25:51.058
and in all directions indeed it is diffused, yet it is not diffused, for this diffusion is extension.

03:25:52.058 --> 03:25:59.498
Accordingly its rays are called extensions, Greek, because they are extended, Greek. But one may judge

03:25:59.498 --> 03:26:05.478
what kind of a thing a ray is if he looks at the night's light passing through a narrow opening

03:26:05.478 --> 03:26:12.758
into a darkened room, for it is extended in a right line and as it were is divided

03:26:12.758 --> 03:26:17.858
when it meets with any solid body which stands in the way and intercepts the air beyond.

03:26:18.838 --> 03:26:24.978
But there the light remains fixed and does not glide or fall. Such then ought to be the outpouring

03:26:24.978 --> 03:26:31.318
and defection of the understanding, and it should in no way be an effusion but an extension,

03:26:31.778 --> 03:26:38.298
and it should make no violent or impetuous collision with the obstacles which are in its

03:26:38.298 --> 03:26:45.518
way, nor yet fall down, but be fixed and enlightened that which receives it, for a body will deprive

03:26:45.518 --> 03:26:55.138
itself of the illumination if it does not admit it. He who fears death either fears the loss of sensation

03:26:55.138 --> 03:27:02.938
or a different kind of sensation, but if thou shalt have no sensation neither wilt thou feel

03:27:02.938 --> 03:27:10.298
any harm, and if thou shalt acquire another kind of sensation thou wilt be a kind of living being

03:27:10.298 --> 03:27:21.198
and who will not cease. Men exist for the sake of one another. Teach them then or bear with them.

03:27:25.098 --> 03:27:31.918
In one way an arrow moves, in another way the mind. The mind indeed both when it exercises

03:27:31.918 --> 03:27:40.178
caution and when it is employed about iniquity moves straight onward, not the less, into its object.

03:27:42.778 --> 03:27:49.818
Enter into every man's ruling faculty and also let every other man enter into thine.

03:28:18.645 --> 03:28:21.545
Of Meditations of Marcus Aurelius.

03:28:43.745 --> 03:28:49.165
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus.

03:28:57.205 --> 03:29:06.125
He who acts unjustly, acts impiously. For since the universal nature has made rational animals,

03:29:06.125 --> 03:29:09.925
for the sake of one another, to help one another according to their deserts,

03:29:09.925 --> 03:29:17.125
but in no way to injure one another, he who transgresses her will is clearly guilty of

03:29:17.125 --> 03:29:25.985
impiety towards the highest divinity. And he too who lies is guilty of impiety to the same divinity.

03:29:26.485 --> 03:29:33.945
For the universal nature is the nature of things that are, and things that are have a relation to

03:29:33.945 --> 03:29:42.865
things that come into existence. And further this universal nature is named truth, and is the prime

03:29:42.865 --> 03:29:51.585
cause of all things that are true. He then who lies intentionally is guilty of impiety in as much

03:29:51.585 --> 03:30:02.125
as he acts unjustly by deceiving. And he who also lies unintentionally in as much as he is at variance

03:30:02.125 --> 03:30:08.365
with the universal nature, and in as much as he disturbs the order by fighting against the nature

03:30:08.365 --> 03:30:14.685
of the world, for he fights against it who is moved of himself to that which is contrary to truth,

03:30:15.205 --> 03:30:20.325
for he had received powers from nature through the neglect of which he is not able now to

03:30:20.325 --> 03:30:27.825
distinguish falsehood from truth. And indeed he who pursues pleasure as good, and avoids pain as

03:30:27.825 --> 03:30:35.205
evil, is guilty of impiety. For of necessity such a man must often find fault with the universal

03:30:35.205 --> 03:30:41.165
nature, alleging that it assigns things to the bad and the good contrary to their desserts,

03:30:41.665 --> 03:30:47.105
because frequently the bad are in the enjoyment of pleasure, and possess the things which procure

03:30:47.105 --> 03:30:54.385
pleasure, but the good have pain for their share, and the things which cause pain. And further he who

03:30:54.385 --> 03:30:59.765
is afraid of pain will sometimes also be afraid of some things which will happen in the world,

03:31:00.105 --> 03:31:07.165
and even this is impiety. And he who pursues pleasure will not abstain from injustice,

03:31:07.685 --> 03:31:14.605
and this is plainly impiety. Now with respect to the things toward which the universal nature is

03:31:14.605 --> 03:31:21.085
equally affected, for it would not have made both unless it was equally affected towards both.

03:31:21.605 --> 03:31:27.305
Towards these they who wish to follow nature should be of the same mind with it, and equally

03:31:27.305 --> 03:31:35.685
affected. With respect to pain then and pleasure, or death and life, or honor and dishonor, which

03:31:35.685 --> 03:31:42.445
the universal nature employs equally, whoever is not equally affected is manifestly acting

03:31:42.445 --> 03:31:49.845
impiously. And I say that the universal nature employs them equally, instead of saying that they

03:31:51.065 --> 03:31:57.865
happen alike to those who are produced in continuous series, and to those who come after

03:31:57.865 --> 03:32:04.525
them by virtue of a certain original movement of providence, according to which it moved from a

03:32:04.525 --> 03:32:10.785
certain being to this ordering of things, having conceived certain principles of the things which

03:32:10.785 --> 03:32:17.565
were to be, and having determined powers productive of beings, and of changes, and of such like

03:32:18.165 --> 03:32:28.345
It would be a man's happiest lot to depart from mankind without having had any taste of lying

03:32:28.345 --> 03:32:35.005
and hypocrisy and luxury and pride. However, to breathe out one's life when a man has had

03:32:35.005 --> 03:32:42.165
enough of these things is the next best voyage, as the saying is. Hast thou determined to abide

03:32:42.165 --> 03:32:50.285
with vice, and hast not experience yet induced thee to fly from this pestilence? For the destruction

03:32:50.285 --> 03:32:56.165
of the understanding is a pestilence, much more indeed than any such corruption and change of

03:32:56.165 --> 03:33:02.785
this atmosphere which surrounds us. For this corruption is a pestilence of animals so far as

03:33:02.785 --> 03:33:08.185
they are animals, but the other is a pestilence of men so far as they are men.

03:33:11.905 --> 03:33:19.185
Do not despise death, but be well content with it, since this too is one of those things which

03:33:19.185 --> 03:33:26.505
nature wills. For such as it is to be young and to grow old, and to increase and to reach

03:33:26.505 --> 03:33:33.945
maturity, and to have teeth and beard and gray hairs, and to beget and be pregnant, and to bring

03:33:33.945 --> 03:33:41.345
forth, and all the other natural operations which the seasons of thy life bring, such also is

03:33:41.345 --> 03:33:48.145
dissolution. This then is consistent with the character of a reflecting man, to be neither

03:33:48.145 --> 03:33:55.125
careless nor impatient nor contemptuous with respect to death, but to wait for it as one of

03:33:55.125 --> 03:34:01.665
the operations of nature. As thou now waitest for the time when the child shall come out of

03:34:01.665 --> 03:34:08.825
thy wife's womb, so be ready for the time when thy soul shall fall out of this envelope. But

03:34:08.825 --> 03:34:15.485
if thou requirest also a vulgar kind of comfort which shall reach thy heart, thou wilt be made

03:34:15.485 --> 03:34:22.825
best reconciled to death by observing the objects from which thou art going to be removed, and the

03:34:22.825 --> 03:34:30.605
with whom thy soul will no longer be mingled. For it is no way right to be offended with men,

03:34:31.045 --> 03:34:37.205
but it is thy duty to care for them and to bear with them gently, and yet to remember that thy

03:34:37.205 --> 03:34:44.585
departure will be not from men who have the same principles as thyself. For this is the only thing,

03:34:44.925 --> 03:34:52.645
if there be any, which could draw us the contrary way and attach us to life, to be permitted to live

03:34:52.645 --> 03:34:59.905
with those who have the same principles as ourselves. But now thou seest how great is the

03:34:59.905 --> 03:35:05.685
trouble arising from the discordance of those who live together, so that thou mayst say,

03:35:06.145 --> 03:35:16.665
Come quick, O death, lest perchance I too should forget myself. He who does wrong,

03:35:17.305 --> 03:35:26.365
against himself. He who acts unjustly, acts unjustly to himself, because he makes himself bad.

03:35:29.365 --> 03:35:37.105
He often acts unjustly who does not do a certain thing, not only he who does a certain thing.

03:35:40.425 --> 03:35:47.985
Thy present opinion founded on understanding, and thy present conduct directed to social good,

03:35:48.505 --> 03:35:54.865
and thy present disposition of contentment with everything which happens, that is enough.

03:35:58.305 --> 03:36:08.525
Wipe out imagination. Check desire. Extinguish appetite. Keep the ruling faculty in its own power.

03:36:12.865 --> 03:36:19.465
Among the animals which have not reason, one life is distributed. But among reasonable animals,

03:36:19.465 --> 03:36:25.725
one intelligent soul is distributed. Just as there is one earth of all things which are of

03:36:25.725 --> 03:36:32.845
an earthly nature, and we see by one light and breathe one air, all of us that have the

03:36:32.845 --> 03:36:44.785
faculty of vision, and all that have life. All things which participate in anything which is

03:36:44.785 --> 03:36:51.865
common to them all, move towards that which is of the same kind with themselves. Everything which

03:36:51.865 --> 03:36:58.125
is earthly turns toward the earth. Everything which is liquid flows together. And everything

03:36:58.125 --> 03:37:04.725
which is of an aerial kind does the same, so that they require something to keep them asunder,

03:37:05.185 --> 03:37:12.965
and the application of force. Fire indeed moves upwards on account of the elemental fire, but it

03:37:12.965 --> 03:37:19.185
is so ready to be kindled together with all the fire which is here, that even every substance

03:37:19.185 --> 03:37:25.945
which is somewhat dry is easily ignited, because there is less mingled with it of that which is a

03:37:25.945 --> 03:37:32.945
hindrance to ignition. Accordingly, then everything also which participates in the common intelligent

03:37:32.945 --> 03:37:40.225
nature moves in like manner towards that which is of the same kind with itself, or moves even more.

03:37:40.225 --> 03:37:48.165
For so much as it is superior in comparison with all other things, in the same degree also it is

03:37:48.165 --> 03:37:55.125
more ready to mingle with and to be fused with that which is akin to it. Accordingly, among animals

03:37:55.125 --> 03:38:02.465
devoid of reason, we find swarms of bees and herds of cattle, and the nurture of young birds, and in

03:38:02.465 --> 03:38:09.065
a manner loves. For even in animals there are souls, and that power which brings them together

03:38:09.065 --> 03:38:15.565
is seen to exert itself in the superior degree, and in such a way as never has been observed in

03:38:15.565 --> 03:38:22.385
plants, or in stones, nor in trees. But in rational animals there are political communities, and

03:38:22.385 --> 03:38:30.425
friendships, and families, and meetings of people, and in wars, treaties, and armistices. But in the

03:38:30.425 --> 03:38:36.745
things which are still superior, even though they are separated from one another, unity in a manner

03:38:36.745 --> 03:38:44.925
exists as in the stars. Thus the ascent to the higher degree is able to produce a sympathy even

03:38:44.925 --> 03:38:52.485
in things which are separated. See then what now takes place. For only intelligent animals have now

03:38:52.485 --> 03:38:58.505
forgotten this mutual desire and inclination, and in them alone the property of flowing together

03:38:58.505 --> 03:39:06.605
is not seen. But still, though men strive to avoid this union, they are caught and held by it, for

03:39:06.605 --> 03:39:14.725
their nature is too strong for them, and thou wilt see what I say, if thou only observest. Sooner

03:39:14.725 --> 03:39:21.565
then will one find anything earthy which comes in contact with no earthy thing than a man altogether

03:39:21.565 --> 03:39:33.745
separated from other men. Both man and God and the universe produce fruit. At the proper seasons,

03:39:33.745 --> 03:39:41.105
each produces it. But if usage has especially fixed these terms to the vine and like things,

03:39:41.405 --> 03:39:48.845
this is nothing. Reason produces fruit both for all and for itself, and there are produced from

03:39:48.845 --> 03:40:00.265
it other things of the same kind as reason itself. If thou art able, correct by teaching those who do

03:40:00.265 --> 03:40:06.505
wrong. But if thou canst not, remember that indulgence is given to thee for this purpose,

03:40:07.005 --> 03:40:13.745
and the gods too are indulgent to such persons. And for some purposes they even help them to get

03:40:13.745 --> 03:40:23.365
health, wealth, reputation, so kind they are. And it is in thy power also. Or say, who hinders thee?

03:40:27.425 --> 03:40:35.045
Labor not as one who is wretched, nor yet as one who would be pitied or admired, but direct thy

03:40:35.045 --> 03:40:42.665
will to one thing only, to put thyself in motion and to check thyself, as the social reason requires.

03:40:46.645 --> 03:40:53.345
Today I have got out of all trouble, or rather I have cast out all trouble, for it was not outside,

03:40:53.345 --> 03:41:04.965
but within, and in my opinions. All things are the same, familiar in experience and ephemeral

03:41:04.965 --> 03:41:12.765
in time, and worthless in the matter. Everything now is just as it was in the time of those whom

03:41:12.765 --> 03:41:23.405
we have buried. Things stand outside of us, themselves by themselves, neither knowing

03:41:23.405 --> 03:41:30.725
aught of themselves, nor expressing any judgment. What is it then which does judge about them,

03:41:31.345 --> 03:41:42.745
the ruling faculty? Not in passivity, but in activity lie the evil and the good of the

03:41:42.745 --> 03:41:49.965
rational social animal, just as his virtue and his vice lie not in passivity, but in activity.

03:41:55.145 --> 03:42:02.045
For the stone which has been thrown up, it is no evil to come down, nor indeed any good to have

03:42:02.045 --> 03:42:12.585
been carried up. Penetrate inwards into men's leading principles, and thou wilt see what judges

03:42:12.585 --> 03:42:22.665
thou art afraid of, and what kind of judges they are of themselves. All things are changing,

03:42:23.145 --> 03:42:29.765
and thou thyself art in continuous mutation, and in a manner in continuous destruction,

03:42:30.245 --> 03:42:40.205
and the whole universe too. It is thy duty to leave another man's wrongful act there where

03:42:40.205 --> 03:42:52.345
it is. Termination of activity, cessation from movement and opinion, and in a sense their death

03:42:52.345 --> 03:42:59.385
is no evil. Turn thy thoughts now to the consideration of thy life, thy life as a child,

03:42:59.565 --> 03:43:08.665
as a youth, thy manhood, thy old age. For in these also every change was a death. Is anything

03:43:08.665 --> 03:43:16.965
to fear? Turn thy thoughts now to thy life under thy grandfather, then to thy life under thy mother,

03:43:17.425 --> 03:43:23.765
then to thy life under thy father, as thou findest many other differences and changes and

03:43:23.765 --> 03:43:31.765
terminations. Ask thyself, is this anything to fear? In like manner then neither are the

03:43:31.765 --> 03:43:37.195
termination and cessation and change of thy whole life a thing to be afraid of.

03:43:41.545 --> 03:43:47.425
Hasten to examine thy own ruling faculty, and that of the universe, and that of thy neighbor,

03:43:48.345 --> 03:43:55.305
thy own, that thou mayest make it just, and that of the universe, that thou mayest remember of what

03:43:55.305 --> 03:44:01.865
thou art apart, and that of thy neighbor, that thou mayest know whether he has acted ignorantly

03:44:01.865 --> 03:44:08.925
or with knowledge, and that thou mayest also consider that his ruling faculty is akin to thine.

03:44:13.265 --> 03:44:21.785
As thou art thyself a component part of a social system, so let every act of thine be a component

03:44:21.785 --> 03:44:29.365
part of social life. Whatever act of thine then has no reference, either immediately or remotely,

03:44:29.505 --> 03:44:37.625
to a social end, this tears asunder thy life, and does not allow it to be one, and is of the nature

03:44:37.625 --> 03:44:45.065
of a mutiny, just as when in a popular assembly a man acting by himself stands apart from the

03:44:49.025 --> 03:44:55.425
Quarrels of little children and their sports, and poor spirits caring about dead bodies,

03:44:55.985 --> 03:45:02.845
such is everything, and so what is exhibited in the representation of the mansions of the dead

03:45:02.845 --> 03:45:14.805
strikes our eyes more clearly. Examine into the quality of the form of an object and detach it

03:45:14.805 --> 03:45:23.165
from its material part, and then contemplate it, then determine the time, the longest which

03:45:23.165 --> 03:45:34.985
a thing of this peculiar form is naturally made to endure. Thou hast endured infinite troubles

03:45:34.985 --> 03:45:41.685
through not being contented with thy ruling faculty, when it does the things which it is

03:45:41.685 --> 03:45:53.465
instituted by nature to do, but enough of this. When another blames thee or hates thee, or when

03:45:53.465 --> 03:46:02.185
men say about thee anything injurious, approach their poor souls, penetrate within, and see what

03:46:02.185 --> 03:46:09.125
kind of men they are. Thou wilt discover that there is no reason to take any trouble that these

03:46:09.125 --> 03:46:16.045
men may have this or that opinion about thee. However, thou must be well disposed towards them,

03:46:16.445 --> 03:46:24.685
for by nature they are friends, and the gods too aid them in all ways, by dreams,

03:46:24.845 --> 03:46:29.865
by signs, toward the attainment of those things on which they set a value.

03:46:35.245 --> 03:46:42.725
The periodic movements of the universe are the same up and down from age to age, and either

03:46:42.725 --> 03:46:49.045
the universal intelligence puts itself in motion for every separate effect, and if this is so,

03:46:49.245 --> 03:46:55.885
be thou content with that which is the result of its activity, or it puts itself in motion once,

03:46:55.885 --> 03:47:02.445
and everything else comes by way of sequence in a manner where indivisible elements are the

03:47:02.445 --> 03:47:09.605
origin of all things. In a word, if there is a God, all is well, and if chance rules,

03:47:10.325 --> 03:47:19.005
do not thou also be governed by it. Soon will the earth cover us all, then the earth too will

03:47:19.005 --> 03:47:25.865
change, and the things also which result from change will continue to change forever, and these

03:47:25.865 --> 03:47:31.925
again forever. For if a man reflects on the changes and transformations which follow one another,

03:47:32.245 --> 03:47:38.125
like wave after wave, and their rapidity, he will despise everything which is perishable.

03:47:42.765 --> 03:47:50.725
The universal cause is like a winter torrent. It carries everything along with it. But how

03:47:50.725 --> 03:47:56.905
worthless are all these poor people who are engaged in matters political and, as they suppose,

03:47:57.045 --> 03:48:05.145
are playing the philosopher. All are drivelers. Well, then, man, do what nature now requires.

03:48:05.625 --> 03:48:12.365
Set thyself in motion. If it is in thy power, and do not look about thee to see if anyone will

03:48:12.365 --> 03:48:19.065
observe it, nor yet expect Plato's Republic, but be content if the smallest thing goes on well,

03:48:19.065 --> 03:48:26.345
and consider such an event to be no small matter. For who can change men's opinions? And without a

03:48:26.345 --> 03:48:32.405
change of opinions, what else is there than the slavery of men who groan while they pretend to

03:48:32.405 --> 03:48:40.105
obey? Come now and tell me of Alexander and Philippus and Demetrius and Phalarum. They

03:48:40.105 --> 03:48:45.505
themselves shall judge whether they discovered what the common nature required, and train

03:48:45.505 --> 03:48:52.805
themselves accordingly. But if they acted like tragedy heroes, no one has condemned me to imitate

03:48:52.805 --> 03:49:00.885
them. Simple and modest is the work of philosophy. Draw me not aside to insolence and pride.

03:49:05.205 --> 03:49:11.225
Look down from above on the countless herds of men and their countless solemnities, and the

03:49:11.225 --> 03:49:18.445
varied voyagings into storms and calms, and the differences among those who are born, who live

03:49:18.445 --> 03:49:25.245
together and die. And consider, too, the life lived by others in olden time, and the life of

03:49:25.245 --> 03:49:32.925
those who will live after thee, and the life now lived among barbarous nations, and how many know

03:49:32.925 --> 03:49:40.285
not even thy name, and how many will soon forget it, and how they who perhaps now are praising thee

03:49:40.285 --> 03:49:47.345
will very soon blame thee, and that neither a posthumous name is of any value, nor reputation,

03:49:47.925 --> 03:49:58.945
nor anything else. Let there be freedom from perturbations with respect to the things which

03:49:58.945 --> 03:50:05.405
come from the external cause. And let there be justice in the things done by virtue of the

03:50:05.405 --> 03:50:13.345
cause. That is, let there be movement and action terminating in this, in social acts, for this is

03:50:13.345 --> 03:50:26.085
according to thy nature. Thou canst remove out of the way many useless things among those which

03:50:26.085 --> 03:50:32.145
disturb thee, for they lie entirely in thy opinion. And thou wilt then gain for thyself

03:50:32.145 --> 03:50:38.405
ample space by comprehending the whole universe in thy mind, and by contemplating the eternity

03:50:38.405 --> 03:50:45.465
of time, and observing the rapid change of every several thing, how short is the time from birth

03:50:45.465 --> 03:50:53.365
to dissolution, and the illimitable time before birth, as well as the equally boundless time after

03:50:53.365 --> 03:51:03.525
dissolution. All that thou seest will quickly perish, and those who have been spectators of

03:51:03.525 --> 03:51:12.545
its dissolution will very soon perish too, and he who dies at the extremest old age will be brought

03:51:12.545 --> 03:51:21.685
into the same condition with him who died prematurely. What are these men's leading

03:51:21.995 --> 03:51:28.465
principles, and about what kind of things are they busy, and for what kind of reasons do they

03:51:28.465 --> 03:51:35.525
love and honor? Imagine that thou seest their poor souls laid bare when they think that they

03:51:35.525 --> 03:51:46.665
do harm by their blame or good by their praise. What an idea! Loss is nothing else than change,

03:51:46.665 --> 03:51:53.805
but the universal nature delights in change, and in obedience to her all things are now done well,

03:51:54.125 --> 03:52:01.725
and from eternity have been done in like form, and will be done to such time without end. What

03:52:01.725 --> 03:52:08.165
then dost thou say, that all things have been, and all things always will be bad, and that no

03:52:08.165 --> 03:52:14.605
power has ever been found in so many gods to rectify these things, but the world has been

03:52:14.605 --> 03:52:24.945
condemned to be bound in never ceasing evil? The rottenness of the matter which is the foundation

03:52:24.945 --> 03:52:34.165
of everything, water, dust, bones, filth, or again marble rocks, the callosities of the earth,

03:52:34.705 --> 03:52:42.485
and gold and silver and sediments and garments, only bits of hair and purple dye, blood and

03:52:42.485 --> 03:52:49.885
everything else is of the same kind, and that which is of the nature of breath is also another

03:52:49.885 --> 03:53:00.105
thing of the same kind, changing from this to that. Enough of this wretched life and murmurings

03:53:00.105 --> 03:53:08.535
and apish tricks. Why art thou disturbed? What is there new in this? What unsettles thee? Is it the

03:53:08.535 --> 03:53:17.135
form of the thing? Look at it. Or is it the matter? Look at it. But besides these, there is nothing.

03:53:17.935 --> 03:53:25.475
Toward the gods, then, now become at last more simple and better. It is the same whether we

03:53:25.475 --> 03:53:35.295
examine these things for a hundred years or three. If any man has done wrong, the harm is his own.

03:53:35.295 --> 03:53:47.075
But perhaps he has not done wrong. Either all things proceed from one intelligent source and

03:53:47.075 --> 03:53:54.055
come together as in one body, and the part ought not to find fault with what is done for the benefit

03:53:54.055 --> 03:54:01.415
of the whole, or there are only atoms and nothing else than mixture and dispersion. Why then art

03:54:01.415 --> 03:54:08.575
thou disturbed? Say to the ruling faculty, Art thou dead? Art thou corrupted? Art thou playing

03:54:08.575 --> 03:54:20.115
the hypocrite? Art thou become a beast? Dost thou herd and feed with the rest? Either the gods have

03:54:20.115 --> 03:54:28.575
no power or they have power. If then they have no power, why dost thou pray to them? But if they

03:54:28.575 --> 03:54:34.115
have power, why dost thou not pray for them to give thee the faculty of not fearing any of the

03:54:34.115 --> 03:54:40.895
things which thou fearst, or of not desiring any of the things which thou desirest, or not being

03:54:40.895 --> 03:54:47.395
pained at anything, rather than pray that any of these things should not happen or happen? For

03:54:47.395 --> 03:54:54.595
certainly if they can cooperate with men, they can cooperate for these purposes. But perhaps thou

03:54:54.595 --> 03:55:01.935
wilt say the gods have placed them in thy power. Well then, is it not better to use what is in thy

03:55:01.935 --> 03:55:08.915
power like a free man than to desire in a slavish and abject way what is not in thy power? And who

03:55:08.915 --> 03:55:15.915
has told thee that the gods do not aid us even in the things which are in our power? Begin then to

03:55:15.915 --> 03:55:23.175
pray for such things, and thou wilt see. One man prays thus, How shall I be able to lie with that

03:55:23.175 --> 03:55:31.595
woman? Do thou prays thus, How shall I not desire to lie with her? Another prays thus, How shall I

03:55:31.595 --> 03:55:39.695
be released from this? Another prays, How shall I not desire to be released? Another thus, How shall

03:55:39.695 --> 03:55:48.495
I not lose my little son? Thou thus, How shall I not be afraid to lose him? In turn, turn thy

03:55:48.495 --> 03:56:01.855
way and see what comes. Epicurus says, In my sickness my conversation was not about my bodily

03:56:01.855 --> 03:56:09.375
sufferings, nor, says he, did I talk on such subjects to those who visited me. But I continued

03:56:09.375 --> 03:56:15.535
to discourse on the nature of things as before, keeping to this main point how the mind while

03:56:15.535 --> 03:56:23.115
participating in such movements as go on in the poor flesh shall be free from perturbations and

03:56:23.115 --> 03:56:30.655
maintain its proper good. Nor did I, he says, give the physicians an opportunity of putting on

03:56:30.655 --> 03:56:37.095
solemn looks, as if they were doing something great, but my life went on well and happily. Do

03:56:37.095 --> 03:56:43.795
then the same that he did, both in sickness, if thou art sick, and in any other circumstances. For

03:56:43.795 --> 03:56:50.715
never to desert philosophy in any events that may befall us, nor to hold trifling talk either

03:56:50.715 --> 03:56:56.475
with an ignorant man, or with one unacquainted with nature, is a principle of all schools of

03:56:56.475 --> 03:57:05.055
philosophy. But to be intent only on that which thou art now doing, and on the instrument by which

03:57:05.055 --> 03:57:17.675
thou dost it. When thou art offended with any man's shameless conduct, immediately ask thyself,

03:57:18.915 --> 03:57:26.555
is it possible then that shameless men should not be in the world? It is not possible. Do then

03:57:28.035 --> 03:57:35.935
require what is impossible. For this man also is one of those shameless men who must of necessity

03:57:35.935 --> 03:57:42.515
be in the world. Let the same considerations be present to thy mind in the case of the knave,

03:57:42.675 --> 03:57:49.155
and the faithless man, and of every man who does wrong in any way. For at the same time that thou

03:57:49.155 --> 03:57:55.015
dost remind thyself that it is impossible that such kind of men should not exist, thou wilt become

03:57:55.015 --> 03:58:01.835
more kindly disposed toward every one individually. It is useful to perceive this, too, immediately

03:58:01.835 --> 03:58:09.595
when the occasion arises, that virtue nature has given to man to oppose to every wrongful act. For

03:58:09.595 --> 03:58:17.095
she has given to man, as an antidote against the stupid man, mildness, and against another kind of

03:58:17.095 --> 03:58:23.955
man, some other power. And in all cases it is possible for thee to correct thy teaching, the

03:58:23.955 --> 03:58:31.395
man who is gone astray. For every man who errs misses his object and is gone astray. Besides,

03:58:31.635 --> 03:58:37.695
wherein hast thou been injured? For thou wilt find that no one among those against whom thou

03:58:37.695 --> 03:58:45.155
art irritated has done anything by which thy mind could be made worse. But that which is evil to thee

03:58:45.155 --> 03:58:52.255
and harmful has its foundation only in the mind. And what harm is done, or what is there strange,

03:58:52.255 --> 03:58:59.155
if the man who has not been instructed does the acts of an uninstructed man? Consider whether

03:58:59.155 --> 03:59:05.215
thou shouldest not rather blame thyself, because thou didst not expect such a man to err in such

03:59:05.215 --> 03:59:12.075
a way. For thou hast means given thee by thy reason to suppose that it was likely that he would

03:59:12.075 --> 03:59:18.675
commit this error. And yet thou hast forgotten and art amazed that he has erred. But most of all,

03:59:18.675 --> 03:59:26.535
when thou blamest him as a father or ungrateful, turn thyself. For the fault is manifestly thy own.

03:59:27.195 --> 03:59:32.995
Whether thou didst trust that a man who had such a disposition would keep his promise,

03:59:33.395 --> 03:59:39.695
or when conferring thy kindness thou didst not confer it absolutely, nor yet in such a way as

03:59:39.695 --> 03:59:47.215
to have received from thy very act all a profit. For what more dost thou want when thou hast done

03:59:47.215 --> 03:59:54.455
man a service? Art thou not content that thou hast done something comfortable to thy nature,

03:59:54.815 --> 04:00:00.855
and dost thou seek to be paid for it? Just as if the eye demanded a recompense for seeing,

04:00:01.275 --> 04:00:07.695
or the feet for walking. For as these members are formed for a particular purpose, and by

04:00:07.695 --> 04:00:15.355
working according to their several constitutions, obtain what is their own. So also, as man is

04:00:15.355 --> 04:00:21.155
formed by nature to acts of benevolence, when he has done anything benevolent, or in any other way

04:00:21.155 --> 04:00:28.295
conducive to the common interest, he has acted conformably to his constitution, and he gets what

04:00:28.295 --> 04:00:44.375
is his own.

04:01:00.007 --> 04:01:06.687
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus

04:01:19.087 --> 04:01:20.207
Section 10.

04:01:23.887 --> 04:01:27.827
Wilt thou then, my soul, never be good and simple, and one and naked,

04:01:28.327 --> 04:01:30.547
more manifest than the body which surrounds thee?

04:01:31.687 --> 04:01:34.467
Wilt thou never enjoy an affectionate and contented disposition?

04:01:35.367 --> 04:01:38.387
Wilt thou never be full and without a want of any kind,

04:01:38.447 --> 04:01:42.507
longing for nothing more, nor desiring anything, either animate or inanimate,

04:01:42.787 --> 04:01:44.187
for the enjoyment of pleasures?

04:01:44.827 --> 04:01:48.887
Nor yet desiring time wherein thou shalt have longer enjoyment, or place,

04:01:49.287 --> 04:01:52.747
or pleasant climate, or society of men with whom thou mayest live in harmony?

04:01:53.727 --> 04:01:56.427
But wilt thou be satisfied with thy present condition,

04:01:56.907 --> 04:01:58.827
and pleased with all that is about thee?

04:01:58.987 --> 04:02:02.307
And wilt thou convince thyself that thou hast everything,

04:02:02.307 --> 04:02:05.627
and that it comes from the gods, that everything is well for thee,

04:02:05.727 --> 04:02:07.687
and will be well whatever shall please them,

04:02:08.147 --> 04:02:11.487
and whatever they shall give for the conservation of perfect living being,

04:02:11.807 --> 04:02:16.287
the good, and just, and beautiful, which generates and holds together all things,

04:02:16.787 --> 04:02:19.287
and contains and embraces all things which are dissolved

04:02:19.287 --> 04:02:21.227
for the production of other like things?

04:02:22.487 --> 04:02:26.487
Wilt thou never be such that thou shalt so dwell in community with gods and men,

04:02:26.607 --> 04:02:30.387
as neither to find fault with them at all, nor to be condemned by them?

04:02:31.487 --> 04:02:39.347
2. Observe what thy nature requires, so far as thou art governed by nature only.

04:02:39.627 --> 04:02:41.467
Then do it, and accept it.

04:02:41.787 --> 04:02:45.887
If thy nature, so far as thou art a living being, shall not be made worse by it.

04:02:46.887 --> 04:02:49.927
And next thou must observe what thy nature requires,

04:02:50.147 --> 04:02:51.667
so far as thou art a living being.

04:02:52.587 --> 04:02:55.727
And all this thou mayest allow thyself, if thy nature,

04:02:55.947 --> 04:02:59.687
so far as thou art a rational animal, shall not be made worse by it.

04:03:00.387 --> 04:03:04.007
But the rational animal is consequently also a political animal.

04:03:05.147 --> 04:03:08.727
Use these rules then, and trouble thyself about nothing else.

04:03:11.647 --> 04:03:17.007
3. Everything which happens, either happens in such wise

04:03:17.007 --> 04:03:22.387
as thou art formed by nature to bear it, or as thou art not formed by nature to bear it.

04:03:23.287 --> 04:03:26.967
If then it happens to thee in such a way as thou art formed by nature to bear it,

04:03:26.967 --> 04:03:30.927
do not complain, but bear it as thou art formed by nature to bear it.

04:03:31.847 --> 04:03:35.667
But if it happens in such wise as thou art not formed by nature to bear it,

04:03:35.867 --> 04:03:39.627
do not complain, for it will perish after it has consumed thee.

04:03:40.367 --> 04:03:43.807
Remember, however, that thou art formed by nature to bear everything,

04:03:44.247 --> 04:03:46.867
with respect to which it depends on thy own opinion to make it

04:03:46.867 --> 04:03:52.167
endurable and tolerable, by thinking that it is either thy interest or thy duty to do this.

04:03:53.027 --> 04:03:58.427
4. If a man is mistaken, instruct him kindly and show him his error.

04:03:59.027 --> 04:04:03.367
But if thou art not able, blame thyself, or blame not even thyself.

04:04:06.887 --> 04:04:12.627
5. Whatever may happen to thee, it was prepared for thee from all eternity,

04:04:13.127 --> 04:04:17.487
and the implication of causes was from eternity spinning the thread of thy being,

04:04:17.647 --> 04:04:19.627
and of that which is incident to it.

04:04:21.387 --> 04:04:29.127
6. Whether the universe is a concourse of atoms, or nature as a system, let this first be established,

04:04:29.507 --> 04:04:32.467
that I am part of the whole which is governed by nature, next,

04:04:32.827 --> 04:04:37.327
I am in a manner intimately related to the parts which are of the same kind with myself.

04:04:38.527 --> 04:04:41.047
For remembering this, inasmuch as I am a part,

04:04:41.427 --> 04:04:45.227
I shall be discontented with none of the things which are assigned to me out of the whole.

04:04:45.867 --> 04:04:50.287
For nothing is injurious to the part if it is for the advantage of the whole.

04:04:51.307 --> 04:04:53.947
For the whole contains nothing which is not for its advantage,

04:04:54.567 --> 04:04:58.647
and all natures indeed have this common principle, but the nature of the universe

04:04:58.647 --> 04:05:03.507
has this principle besides that it cannot be compelled even by any external cause

04:05:03.507 --> 04:05:05.627
to generate anything harmful to itself.

04:05:07.187 --> 04:05:11.447
By remembering, then, that I am part of such a whole, I shall be content with everything that

04:05:11.447 --> 04:05:15.987
happens, and inasmuch as I am in a manner intimately related to the parts which are

04:05:15.987 --> 04:05:21.607
of the same kind with myself, I shall do nothing unsocial, but I shall rather direct myself to the

04:05:21.607 --> 04:05:26.707
things which are of the same kind with myself, and I shall turn all my efforts to the common interest,

04:05:27.067 --> 04:05:28.687
and divert them from the contrary.

04:05:30.107 --> 04:05:33.587
Now, if these things are done so, life must flow on happily,

04:05:33.767 --> 04:05:36.787
just as thou mayest observe that the life of a citizen is happy,

04:05:37.167 --> 04:05:40.967
who continues a course of action which is advantageous to his fellow citizens,

04:05:40.967 --> 04:05:44.167
and is content with whatever the state may assign to him.

04:05:48.427 --> 04:05:55.067
7. The parts of the whole, everything I mean, which is naturally comprehended in the universe,

04:05:55.587 --> 04:06:01.627
must of necessity perish. But let this be understood in this sense, that they must undergo

04:06:01.627 --> 04:06:08.227
change. But if this is naturally both an evil and a necessity for the parts, the whole would not

04:06:08.227 --> 04:06:12.947
continue to exist in a good condition, the parts being subject to change and constituted so as to

04:06:12.947 --> 04:06:18.987
perish in various ways. For whether did Nature herself design to do evil to the things which

04:06:18.987 --> 04:06:24.187
are parts of herself, and to make them subject to evil and of necessity fall into evil,

04:06:24.547 --> 04:06:30.907
or have such results happened without her knowing it? Both these suppositions indeed are incredible,

04:06:31.467 --> 04:06:36.627
but if a man should ever drop the term Nature as an efficient power, and should speak of these

04:06:36.627 --> 04:06:42.007
as natural, even then it would be ridiculous to affirm at the same time that the parts of the

04:06:42.007 --> 04:06:46.887
whole are in their nature subject to change, and at the same time to be surprised or vexed as if

04:06:46.887 --> 04:06:51.867
something were happening contrary to Nature, particularly as the dissolution of things into

04:06:51.867 --> 04:06:57.787
those things of which each thing is composed. For there is either a dispersion of the elements out

04:06:57.787 --> 04:07:03.127
of which everything has been compounded, or a change from the solid to the earthy, and from the

04:07:03.127 --> 04:07:08.227
aerial, so that these parts are taken back into the universal reason, whether this at certain

04:07:08.227 --> 04:07:15.367
periods is consumed by fire or renewed by eternal changes. And do not imagine that the solid and the

04:07:15.367 --> 04:07:21.087
airy part belong to thee from time of generation. For all this received its accretion only yesterday,

04:07:21.627 --> 04:07:27.507
and the day before, as one may say, from the food and the air which is inspired. This then,

04:07:27.587 --> 04:07:31.547
which have received the accretion, changes not that which thy mother brought forth.

04:07:32.187 --> 04:07:36.627
But suppose that this, which thy mother brought forth, implicates thee very much with the other

04:07:36.627 --> 04:07:42.047
part, which has the peculiar quality of change. This is nothing, in fact, in the way of objection

04:07:42.047 --> 04:07:51.987
to what is said. 8. When thou hast assumed thy names, good, modest, true, rational, a man of

04:07:51.987 --> 04:07:57.687
equanimity and magnanimous, take care thou dost not change these names. And if thou should lose

04:07:57.687 --> 04:08:03.627
them, quickly return to them. And remember that the term rational was intended to signify a

04:08:03.627 --> 04:08:09.327
discriminating attention to every several thing and freedom from negligence, and that equanimity

04:08:09.327 --> 04:08:13.327
is the voluntary acceptance of the things which are assigned to thee by the common nature,

04:08:13.967 --> 04:08:18.347
and that magnanimity is the elevation of the intelligent part above the pleasurable or

04:08:18.347 --> 04:08:24.027
painful sensations of the flesh, and above that poor thing called fame, and death, and all such

04:08:24.027 --> 04:08:30.707
things. 9. If then thou maintainest thyself in the possession of these names, without desiring

04:08:30.707 --> 04:08:36.107
to be called by these names by others, thou wilt be another person and wilt enter on to another

04:08:36.107 --> 04:08:43.107
life. For to continue to be such as thou hast hitherto been, and to be torn in pieces and defiled

04:08:43.107 --> 04:08:49.727
in such a life, is the character of a very stupid man, and one over-fond of his life. And like those

04:08:49.727 --> 04:08:53.807
half-devoured fighters with wild beasts, who though covered with wounds and gore, are still

04:08:53.807 --> 04:08:58.407
entreat to be kept to the following day, though they will be exposed in the same state to the

04:08:58.407 --> 04:09:05.007
same claws and bites. Therefore, fix thyself in the possession of these few names, and if

04:09:05.007 --> 04:09:10.227
thou art able to abide in them, abide as if thou wast removed to certain islands of the happy.

04:09:11.807 --> 04:09:16.267
But if thou shalt perceive that thou fallest out of them and dost not maintain thy hold,

04:09:16.267 --> 04:09:22.247
go courageously into some nook where thou shalt maintain them, or even depart at once from life,

04:09:22.527 --> 04:09:28.147
not in passion, but with simplicity and freedom and modesty, after doing this one laudable thing

04:09:28.147 --> 04:09:34.687
at least in thy life, to have gone out of it thus. In order, however, to the remembrance

04:09:34.687 --> 04:09:39.827
of these names, it will greatly help thee if thou rememberest the gods, and that they wish

04:09:39.827 --> 04:09:45.167
not to be flattered, but wish all reasonable beings to be made like themselves. And if

04:09:45.167 --> 04:09:50.207
thou rememberest, that which does the work of a fig tree is a fig tree, and that which does the

04:09:50.207 --> 04:09:56.607
work of a dog is a dog, and that which does the work of a bee is a bee, and that which does the

04:09:56.607 --> 04:10:05.587
work of man is a man. 9. Meme, war, astonishment, torpor,

04:10:05.647 --> 04:10:11.727
slavery, will daily wipe out those holy principles of thine. How many things without studying nature

04:10:11.727 --> 04:10:18.407
dost thou imagine, and how many dost thou neglect? But it is thy duty so to look on,

04:10:18.487 --> 04:10:23.527
and so to do everything, that at the same time the power of dealing with circumstances is perfect,

04:10:23.867 --> 04:10:28.727
and the contemplative faculty is exercised, and the confidence which comes from the knowledge of

04:10:28.727 --> 04:10:36.827
each several thing is maintained without showing it, by yet not concealed. For when wilt thou enjoy

04:10:36.827 --> 04:10:42.787
simplicity, when gravity, and when the knowledge of every several thing, both what is in substance,

04:10:43.067 --> 04:10:47.487
and what place it has in the universe, and how long it is formed to exist, and of what things

04:10:47.487 --> 04:10:53.327
it is compounded, and to whom it can belong, and who are able both to give it and take it away?

04:10:56.767 --> 04:11:03.947
10. A spider is proud when it has caught a fly, and another when he has caught a poor hair,

04:11:04.507 --> 04:11:10.167
and another when he has taken the little fish in the net, and another when he has taken wild boars,

04:11:10.727 --> 04:11:15.207
and another when he has taken bears, and another when he has taken sarmatians.

04:11:16.347 --> 04:11:19.327
Are not these robbers, if thou examinest their opinions?

04:11:21.667 --> 04:11:27.707
11. Acquire the contemplative way of seeing how all things change into one another,

04:11:28.107 --> 04:11:32.907
and constantly attend to it, and exercise thyself about this part of philosophy.

04:11:33.947 --> 04:11:39.547
For nothing is so much adapted produce magnanimity. Such a man is put off the body,

04:11:40.087 --> 04:11:46.087
and he sees that he must, no one knows how soon, go away from among men and leave everything here.

04:11:46.487 --> 04:11:51.707
He gives himself up entirely to just doing in all his actions, and in everything else that happens,

04:11:51.847 --> 04:11:58.347
he resigns himself to the universal nature. But as to what any man shall say or think about him,

04:11:58.387 --> 04:12:03.727
or do against him, he never even thinks of it, being himself contented with these two things.

04:12:03.947 --> 04:12:09.807
With acting justly in what he now does, and being satisfied with what is now assigned to him.

04:12:10.807 --> 04:12:15.447
And he lays aside all distracting and busy pursuits, and desires nothing else

04:12:15.447 --> 04:12:19.987
than to accomplish the straight course through the law, and by accomplishing the straight course,

04:12:20.147 --> 04:12:23.927
to follow God. 12.

04:12:25.907 --> 04:12:30.827
What need is there of suspicious fear, since it is thy power to inquire what ought to be done?

04:12:31.347 --> 04:12:36.027
And if thou seest clear, go by this way content, without turning back.

04:12:36.547 --> 04:12:40.407
But if thou dost not see clear, stop and take the best advisers.

04:12:41.687 --> 04:12:46.567
But if any other things oppose thee, go on according to thy powers with due consideration,

04:12:46.747 --> 04:12:51.407
keeping to that which appears to be just. For it is best to reach this object,

04:12:51.467 --> 04:12:57.307
and if thou dost fail, let thy failure be in attempting this. He who follows reason in all

04:12:57.307 --> 04:13:02.587
things is both tranquil and active at the same time, and also cheerful and collected.

04:13:06.307 --> 04:13:06.807
13.

04:13:09.147 --> 04:13:13.667
Inquire of thyself, as soon as thou wakest from sleep, whether it will make any difference to thee,

04:13:13.807 --> 04:13:20.287
if another does what is just and right. It will make no difference. Thou hast not forgotten,

04:13:20.327 --> 04:13:24.667
I suppose, that those who assume arrogant errors in bestowing their praise or blame on others,

04:13:24.667 --> 04:13:29.867
are such as they are at bed and at board. And thou hast not forgotten what they do,

04:13:30.207 --> 04:13:33.867
and what they avoid, and what they pursue, and how they steal, and how they rob,

04:13:34.147 --> 04:13:39.327
not with hands and feet, but with their most valuable part, by means of which there is produced

04:13:39.327 --> 04:13:45.087
when a man chooses fidelity, modesty, truth, law, a good demon, and happiness.

04:13:46.787 --> 04:13:47.267
14.

04:13:48.987 --> 04:13:54.687
To her who gives and takes back all, to nature, the man who is instructed in modest says,

04:13:55.107 --> 04:13:59.967
Give what thy wilt, take back what thou wilt. And he says this not proudly,

04:14:00.267 --> 04:14:02.267
but obediently, and well pleased with her.

04:14:04.987 --> 04:14:05.507
15.

04:14:07.307 --> 04:14:13.127
Short is the little which remains to thee of life. Live as on a mountain. For it makes no

04:14:13.127 --> 04:14:17.707
difference whether a man lives there or here, if he lives everywhere in the world as an estate.

04:14:18.987 --> 04:14:22.687
Let men see, let them know a real man who lives according to nature.

04:14:23.527 --> 04:14:28.827
If they cannot endure him, let them kill him. For that is better than to live like this.

04:14:31.767 --> 04:14:32.247
16.

04:14:33.887 --> 04:14:38.887
No longer talk at all about the kind of man that a good man ought to be, but be such.

04:14:40.947 --> 04:14:41.427
17.

04:14:43.027 --> 04:14:47.527
Constantly contemplate the whole of time and the whole of substance, and consider that all

04:14:47.527 --> 04:14:53.427
individual things as to substance are as a grain of a fig, and as to time the turning of a gimlet.

04:14:58.087 --> 04:15:02.867
Look at everything that exists, and observe that it is already in dissolution and in change,

04:15:03.487 --> 04:15:09.107
and as it were putrefaction or dispersion, or that everything is so constituted by nature as to die.

04:15:10.927 --> 04:15:11.407
19.

04:15:13.347 --> 04:15:17.387
Consider what men are when they are eating, sleeping, generating, easing themselves,

04:15:17.467 --> 04:15:21.867
and so forth. Then what kind of men they are when they are imperious and arrogant,

04:15:22.147 --> 04:15:28.567
or angry and scolding from their elevated place. Put a short time ago to how many they were slaves

04:15:28.567 --> 04:15:33.507
and for what things. And after a little time, consider in what a condition they will be.

04:15:35.807 --> 04:15:36.287
20.

04:15:37.967 --> 04:15:42.067
That is for the good of each thing which the universal nature brings to each,

04:15:42.507 --> 04:15:45.467
and it is for its good at the time when nature brings it.

04:15:47.727 --> 04:15:48.247
21.

04:15:49.687 --> 04:15:57.167
The earth loves a shower, and the solemn aether loves, and the universe loves to make whatever

04:15:57.167 --> 04:16:04.187
it is about to be. I say then to the universe that I love as thou lovest, and is not this too said

04:16:04.187 --> 04:16:07.267
this or that loves as want to be produced.

04:16:09.267 --> 04:16:09.827
22.

04:16:12.247 --> 04:16:16.187
Either thou livest here, and hast already accustomed thyself to it,

04:16:16.367 --> 04:16:22.847
or thou art going away, and this was on thy own will, or thou art dying, and hast discharged thy

04:16:22.847 --> 04:16:27.667
duty. But besides these things there is nothing. Be of good cheer then.

04:16:30.247 --> 04:16:30.807
23.

04:16:32.587 --> 04:16:37.187
Let this always be plain to thee, that this piece of land is like any other,

04:16:37.367 --> 04:16:40.587
and that all things here are the same with things on top of a mountain,

04:16:40.787 --> 04:16:46.767
or on the seashore, or wherever thou choosest to be. For thou wilt find just what Plato says,

04:16:47.247 --> 04:16:50.707
dwelling within the walls of a city as in a shepherd's fold on a mountain.

04:16:53.447 --> 04:16:53.887
24.

04:16:55.167 --> 04:17:00.407
What is my ruling faculty now to me? And of what nature am I now making it?

04:17:00.407 --> 04:17:06.347
And for what purpose am I now using it? Is it void of understanding? Is it loosed and rent

04:17:06.347 --> 04:17:11.307
asunder from social life? Is it melted into and mixed with the poor flesh so as to move together

04:17:11.307 --> 04:17:15.287
with it? 25.

04:17:16.747 --> 04:17:22.387
He who flies from his master is a runaway, but the law is master, and he who breaks the law

04:17:22.387 --> 04:17:28.847
is a runaway. And he also who is grieved or angry or afraid is dissatisfied because something has

04:17:28.847 --> 04:17:33.607
been or is or shall be of the things which are appointed by him who rules all things,

04:17:33.927 --> 04:17:40.987
and he is law and assigns to every man what is fit. He then who fears or is grieved or is angry

04:17:40.987 --> 04:17:44.947
is a runaway. 26.

04:17:47.467 --> 04:17:53.187
A man deposits seed in a womb and goes away, and then another cause takes it and labors on it and

04:17:53.187 --> 04:18:00.827
makes a child. What a thing from such a material! Again, the child passes food down the throat,

04:18:01.287 --> 04:18:05.847
and then another cause takes it and makes it perception and motion. And in fine life and

04:18:05.847 --> 04:18:11.267
strength and other things, how many and how strange! Observe, then, the things which are

04:18:11.267 --> 04:18:16.007
produced in such a hidden way, and see the power just as we see the power which carries

04:18:16.007 --> 04:18:20.907
things downwards and upwards, not with the eyes, but still no less plainly.

04:18:23.907 --> 04:18:24.427
27.

04:18:26.147 --> 04:18:30.647
Constantly consider how all things such as they now are and time past also were,

04:18:30.907 --> 04:18:35.707
and consider that they will be the same again. And place before thy eyes entire dramas and

04:18:35.707 --> 04:18:40.507
stages of the same form, whatever thou hast learned from thy experience or from older history.

04:18:41.087 --> 04:18:47.007
For example, the whole court of Hadrianus, and the whole court of Antoninus, and the whole court of

04:18:47.007 --> 04:18:53.427
Olympus, Alexander, Croesus, for all those were dramas such as we see now only with different actors.

04:18:55.127 --> 04:19:00.387
28. Imagine every man who is grieved at anything or discontented to be like a pig

04:19:00.387 --> 04:19:07.147
which is sacrificed in kicks and screams. Like this pig also is he who on his bed in silence

04:19:07.147 --> 04:19:11.807
laments the bonds in which we are held, and consider that only to the rational animal is

04:19:11.807 --> 04:19:17.807
given to follow voluntarily what happens, but simply to follow as a necessity imposed on all.

04:19:20.167 --> 04:19:20.727
29.

04:19:22.307 --> 04:19:27.047
Severally on the occasion of everything that thou dost, pause and ask thyself if death is

04:19:27.047 --> 04:19:35.187
a dreadful thing because it deprives thee of this. 30. When thou art offended at any man's fault,

04:19:35.727 --> 04:19:39.707
forwith turn to thyself and reflect in what like manner thou dost err thyself,

04:19:39.707 --> 04:19:44.507
for example in thinking that money is a good thing, or pleasure, or a bit of reputation,

04:19:44.647 --> 04:19:49.947
and the like. For by attending to this thou wilt quickly forget thy anger, if this consideration

04:19:49.947 --> 04:19:56.147
also is added, that the man is compelled for what else could he do. Or, if thou art able,

04:19:56.407 --> 04:20:04.687
take away from him the compulsion. 31. When thou hast seen Sartron the Socratic,

04:20:04.687 --> 04:20:11.327
think of Eutyches or Hymen. And when thou hast seen Euphrates, think of Eutychion or Silvanus.

04:20:12.387 --> 04:20:17.987
And when thou hast seen Alcefron, think of Troipaphorus. And when thou hast seen Xenophon,

04:20:18.247 --> 04:20:24.027
think of Credo of Severus. And when thou hast looked on thyself, think of any other Caesar,

04:20:24.787 --> 04:20:29.547
and in the case of every one do in like manner. 32.

04:20:29.547 --> 04:20:34.067
Then let this thought be in thy mind. Where then are those men?

04:20:34.707 --> 04:20:41.307
Nowhere, or nobody knows where. For thus continuously thou wilt look at human things

04:20:41.307 --> 04:20:46.467
as smoke and nothing at all, especially if thou reflectest at the same time that what

04:20:46.467 --> 04:20:52.987
has once changed will never exist again in the infinite duration of time. But thou,

04:20:53.447 --> 04:20:59.047
in what a brief space of time is thy existence, and why art thou not content to pass through

04:20:59.047 --> 04:21:04.887
this short time in an orderly way? What matter and opportunity for thy activity art thou avoiding?

04:21:05.527 --> 04:21:08.987
For what else are all these things except exercises for the reason,

04:21:09.267 --> 04:21:14.187
when it is viewed carefully, and by examination into their nature the things which happen in life?

04:21:16.327 --> 04:21:21.607
Persevere then until thou shalt have made these things thy own, as the stomach which is strengthened

04:21:21.607 --> 04:21:27.027
makes all things its own, as the blazing fire makes flame and brightness out of everything that is

04:21:27.027 --> 04:21:35.027
thrown into it. 32.

04:21:36.867 --> 04:21:41.827
Let it not be in any man's power to say truly of thee that thou art not simple, or that thou art

04:21:41.827 --> 04:21:47.427
not good. But let him be a liar whoever shall think anything of this kind about thee, and this

04:21:47.427 --> 04:21:53.567
is altogether in thy power. For who is he that shall hinder thee from being good and simple?

04:21:54.207 --> 04:21:58.947
Do thou only determine to live no longer, and lest thou shalt be such?

04:22:00.087 --> 04:22:03.667
For neither does reason allow thee to live, if thou art not such.

04:22:06.347 --> 04:22:14.107
33. What is that which as to this material our life can be done or said in a way most

04:22:14.107 --> 04:22:20.007
conformable to reason? For whatever this may be, it is in thy power to do it or say it,

04:22:20.007 --> 04:22:25.887
and do not make excuses that thou art hindered. Thou wilt not cease to lament till thy mind is

04:22:25.887 --> 04:22:31.207
in such a condition that, what luxury is to those who enjoy pleasure, such shall be to thee

04:22:31.207 --> 04:22:35.927
in the matter which is subjected and presented to thee, the doing of things which are conformable

04:22:35.927 --> 04:22:41.667
to man's constitution. For a man ought to consider as an enjoyment everything which is in his power

04:22:41.667 --> 04:22:53.827
to do according to his own nature, and it is in his power everywhere. Now it is not given to a

04:22:53.827 --> 04:23:00.227
cylinder to move everywhere by its own motion, nor yet water, nor to fire, nor to anything else

04:23:00.227 --> 04:23:05.327
which is governed by nature of an irrational soul, for the things which check them and stand in the

04:23:05.327 --> 04:23:11.027
way are many. But intelligence and reason are able to go through everything that opposes them,

04:23:11.027 --> 04:23:17.287
and in such manner as they are formed by nature and as they choose. Place before thy eyes this

04:23:17.287 --> 04:23:22.807
facility with which the reason will be carried through all things, as fire upwards, as a stone

04:23:22.807 --> 04:23:30.707
downwards, as a cylinder down an inclined surface, and seek nothing further. For all other obstacles

04:23:30.707 --> 04:23:36.547
either affect the body only which is a dead thing, or except through opinion and the yielding of the

04:23:36.547 --> 04:23:43.347
they do not crush nor do any harm of any kind, for if they did, he who felt it would immediately

04:23:43.347 --> 04:23:50.647
become bad. Now in the case of all things which have a certain constitution, whatever harm may

04:23:50.647 --> 04:23:58.047
happen to any of them, that which is so affected becomes consequently worse. But in the like case,

04:23:58.147 --> 04:24:03.707
a man becomes both better if one may say so, and more worthy of praise by making a right use of

04:24:03.707 --> 04:24:11.147
accidents. And finally, remember that nothing harms him who is really a citizen, which does not

04:24:11.147 --> 04:24:17.067
harm the state, nor yet does anything harm the state which does not harm law, and of these things

04:24:17.067 --> 04:24:24.247
which are called misfortunes, not one harms law. What then does not harm law does not harm either

04:24:24.247 --> 04:24:25.267
citizen.

04:24:30.007 --> 04:24:35.067
To him who is penetrated by true principles, even the briefest precept is sufficient,

04:24:35.607 --> 04:24:41.447
and any common precept, to remind him that he should be free from grief and fair. For example,

04:24:43.707 --> 04:24:48.767
leaves, some the wind scatters on the ground, so is the race of men.

04:24:50.727 --> 04:24:56.147
Leaves also are thy children, and leaves too are they who cry out as if they were worthy of credit

04:24:56.147 --> 04:25:02.187
and bestow their praise, or on the contrary curse, or secretly blame and sneer, and leaves in like

04:25:02.187 --> 04:25:08.307
manner are those who shall receive and transmit a man's fame to aftertimes. For all such things as

04:25:08.307 --> 04:25:16.567
these, quote, are produced in the season of spring, end quote, as the poet says. But the wind casts

04:25:16.567 --> 04:25:22.707
them down, then the forest produces other leaves in their places. But a brief existence is common

04:25:22.707 --> 04:25:29.027
to all things, and yet thou avoidest and pursuest all things as if they would be eternal. A little

04:25:29.027 --> 04:25:34.967
time and thou shalt close thy eyes, and him who has attended thee to thy grave another soon will lament.

04:25:39.727 --> 04:25:40.167
35.

04:25:42.907 --> 04:25:48.327
The healthy eye ought to see all visible things, and not to say, I wish for green things. For this

04:25:48.327 --> 04:25:53.867
is the condition of a diseased eye. And the healthy hearing and smelling ought to be ready to perceive

04:25:53.867 --> 04:25:58.927
all that can be heard and smelled. And the healthy stomach ought to be with respect to all food,

04:25:58.967 --> 04:26:02.347
just as the meal with respect to all things which it is formed to grind.

04:26:03.547 --> 04:26:08.307
And accordingly, the healthy understanding ought to be prepared for everything which happens.

04:26:08.867 --> 04:26:13.707
But that which says, let my dear children live, and let all men praise whatever I may do,

04:26:14.507 --> 04:26:19.167
is an eye which seeks for green things, or teeth which seek for soft things.

04:26:23.247 --> 04:26:23.767
36.

04:26:26.687 --> 04:26:30.347
There is no man so fortunate that there shall not be by him when he is dying,

04:26:30.347 --> 04:26:32.787
some who were pleased with what is going to happen.

04:26:34.527 --> 04:26:39.907
Suppose that he was a good and wise man. Will there not be at last someone to say to himself,

04:26:40.727 --> 04:26:44.207
Let us at last breathe freely, being relieved from this schoolmaster?

04:26:45.427 --> 04:26:50.847
It is true that he was harsh to none of us, but I perceive that he tacitly condemns us.

04:26:51.827 --> 04:26:58.487
This is what is said of a good man. But in our own case, how many other things are there for which

04:26:58.487 --> 04:27:03.367
are many who wish to get rid of us? Thou wilt consider this then when thou art dying,

04:27:03.767 --> 04:27:06.887
and thou wilt depart more contentedly by reflecting thus.

04:27:08.327 --> 04:27:13.487
I am going away from such a life, in which even my associates, in behalf of whom I have

04:27:13.487 --> 04:27:19.527
striven so much, prayed and cared, themselves wished me to depart, hoping perchance to get

04:27:19.527 --> 04:27:25.587
some little advantage by it. Why, then, should a man cling to a longer stay here?

04:27:27.287 --> 04:27:31.447
Do not, however, for this reason go away less kindly disposed to them,

04:27:31.947 --> 04:27:35.227
but preserving thy own character, and friendly and benevolent and mild,

04:27:35.507 --> 04:27:40.667
and on the other hand not, as if thou wast torn away, but as a man who dies a quiet death.

04:27:42.427 --> 04:27:48.227
The poor soul is easily separated from the body. Such also aught thy departure from men to be,

04:27:48.707 --> 04:27:51.707
for nature united thee to them, and associated thee.

04:27:52.667 --> 04:27:54.707
But does she now dissolve the union?

04:27:56.447 --> 04:28:00.867
Well, I am separated as from kinsmen, not, however, dragged resisting,

04:28:01.427 --> 04:28:06.287
but without compulsion, for this too is one of the things according to nature.

04:28:12.767 --> 04:28:17.587
Accustom thyself as much as possible on the occasion of anything being done by any person

04:28:17.587 --> 04:28:22.387
to inquire with thyself, for what object is this man doing this?

04:28:23.507 --> 04:28:26.787
But begin with thyself, and examine thyself first.

04:28:32.287 --> 04:28:36.327
Remember that this which pulls the strings is the thing which is hidden within.

04:28:36.927 --> 04:28:42.727
This is the power of persuasion. This is life. This, if one may say so, is man.

04:28:43.827 --> 04:28:47.687
In contemplating thyself never include the vessel which surrounds thee,

04:28:48.127 --> 04:28:54.587
and these instruments were attached about it, for they are like to an axe differing only in this,

04:28:55.327 --> 04:29:01.727
that they grow to the body. For indeed there is no more use in these parts without the cause

04:29:01.727 --> 04:29:08.367
which moves and checks them than in the weaver's shuttle, and the writer's pen, and the driver's whip.

04:29:12.727 --> 04:29:14.407
Of section 10.

04:29:49.865 --> 04:29:56.845
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus

04:30:02.905 --> 04:30:05.725
These are the properties of the rational soul.

04:30:06.145 --> 04:30:11.825
It sees itself, analyzes itself, and makes itself such as it chooses.

04:30:12.525 --> 04:30:20.365
The fruit which it bears itself enjoys, for the fruit of plants and that in animals which corresponds to fruits others enjoy.

04:30:21.165 --> 04:30:25.625
It obtains its own end, wherever the limit of life may be fixed.

04:30:26.265 --> 04:30:34.705
Not as in a dance and in a play and in such like things, where the whole action is incomplete, if anything cuts it short.

04:30:35.225 --> 04:30:45.845
But in every part and wherever it may be stopped, it makes what has been set before it full and completes, so that it can say, I have what is my own.

04:30:46.665 --> 04:30:53.145
And further it traverses the whole universe and the surrounding vacuum and surveys its form.

04:30:53.705 --> 04:31:01.505
And it extends itself into the infinity of time and embraces and comprehends the periodical renovation of all things.

04:31:01.945 --> 04:31:09.705
And it comprehends that those who come after us will see nothing new, nor have those before us seen anything more.

04:31:10.345 --> 04:31:22.225
But in a manner he who is forty years old, if he has any understanding at all, has seen by virtue of the uniformity that prevails all things which have been and all that will be.

04:31:23.185 --> 04:31:34.925
This too is a property of the rational soul, love of one's neighbor, and truth and modesty, and to value nothing more than itself, which is also the property of law.

04:31:35.545 --> 04:31:40.005
Thus then, right reason differs not at all from the reason of justice.

04:31:42.905 --> 04:31:52.625
Thou wilt set little value on pleasing song and dancing in the pancreasium, if thou wilt distribute the melody of the voice into its several sounds,

04:31:53.085 --> 04:32:00.785
and ask thyself as to each if thou art mastered by this, for thou wilt be prevented by shame from confessing it.

04:32:00.785 --> 04:32:09.625
And in the matter of dancing, if at each movement and attitude thou wilt do the same, and the like also in the matter of the pancreasium.

04:32:10.625 --> 04:32:17.345
In all things then, except virtue and the acts of virtue, remember to apply thyself to their several parts,

04:32:17.905 --> 04:32:23.965
and by this division to come to value them little, and apply this rule also to thy whole life.

04:32:25.925 --> 04:32:37.105
What a soul that is which is ready, if at any moment it must be separated from the body, and ready to be extinguished, or dispersed, or continue to exist,

04:32:37.865 --> 04:32:45.165
but so that this readiness comes from a man's own judgment, not from mere obstinacy, as with the Christians,

04:32:45.725 --> 04:32:52.485
but considerably, and with dignity, and in a way to persuade another without tragic show.

04:32:54.825 --> 04:33:06.485
Have I done something for the general interest? Well then, I have had my reward. Let this always be present to thy mind, and never stop doing such good.

04:33:07.985 --> 04:33:14.285
What is thy art? To be good. And how is this accomplished well, except by general principles,

04:33:14.925 --> 04:33:20.165
some about the nature of the universe, and others about the proper constitution of man?

04:33:22.245 --> 04:33:29.165
At first tragedies were brought on the stage as means of reminding men of the things which happened to them,

04:33:29.525 --> 04:33:36.945
and that it is according to nature for things to happen so, and that if you are delighted with what is shown on the stage,

04:33:37.385 --> 04:33:41.005
you should not be troubled with that which takes place on the larger stage.

04:33:41.785 --> 04:33:48.405
For you see that these things must be accomplished thus, and that even they bear them who cry out, O Satheron.

04:33:49.125 --> 04:33:55.665
And indeed, some things are said well by the dramatic writers, of which kind is the following especially.

04:33:56.865 --> 04:34:02.305
Me and my children, if the gods neglect, this has its reason too.

04:34:02.905 --> 04:34:08.105
And again, we must not chafe and fret at that which happens.

04:34:09.705 --> 04:34:17.045
And, life's harvest reap like the wheat's fruitful ear, and other things of the same kind.

04:34:18.385 --> 04:34:24.405
After tragedy the old comedy was introduced, which had a magisterial freedom of speech,

04:34:24.845 --> 04:34:30.285
and by its very plainness of speaking was useful in reminding men to beware of insolence,

04:34:30.785 --> 04:34:34.345
and for this purpose too diogenes used to take from these writers.

04:34:35.545 --> 04:34:40.545
But as to the middle comedy which came next, observe what it was, and again,

04:34:40.545 --> 04:34:47.225
for what object the new comedy was introduced, which gradually sunk down into a mere mimic artifice.

04:34:48.025 --> 04:34:51.745
That some good things are said even by these writers everybody knows,

04:34:52.465 --> 04:34:57.165
but the whole plan of such poetry and dramaturgy, to what end does it look?

04:35:00.245 --> 04:35:06.465
How plain does it appear that there is not another condition of life so well suited for philosophizing

04:35:06.465 --> 04:35:09.725
as this in which thou now happenest to be.

04:35:11.565 --> 04:35:17.825
A branch cut off from the adjacent branch must of necessity be cut off from the whole tree also.

04:35:18.805 --> 04:35:24.465
So too a man when he is separated from another man has fallen off from the whole social community.

04:35:25.725 --> 04:35:32.425
Now as to a branch, another cuts it off, but a man by his own act separates himself from his neighbor

04:35:32.425 --> 04:35:37.885
when he hates him and turns away from him, and he does not know that he has at the same time

04:35:37.885 --> 04:35:40.305
cut himself off from the whole social system.

04:35:41.425 --> 04:35:44.965
Yet he has this privilege certainly from Zeus who frames society,

04:35:45.745 --> 04:35:49.525
for it is in our power to grow again to that which is near to us,

04:35:49.985 --> 04:35:53.225
and again to become a part which helps us to make up the whole.

04:35:54.125 --> 04:35:57.385
However if it often happens, this kind of separation,

04:35:57.385 --> 04:36:01.985
it makes it difficult for that which detaches itself to be brought to unity

04:36:01.985 --> 04:36:04.645
and to be restored to its former condition.

04:36:05.745 --> 04:36:09.885
Finally the branch, which from the first grew together with the tree

04:36:09.885 --> 04:36:12.365
and has continued to have one life with it,

04:36:12.845 --> 04:36:16.645
is not like that which after being cut off is then ingrafted,

04:36:16.865 --> 04:36:21.685
for this is something like what the gardeners mean when they say that it grows with the rest of the tree,

04:36:22.125 --> 04:36:24.705
but that it has not the same mind with it.

04:36:27.085 --> 04:36:32.505
As those who try to stand in thy way when thou art proceeding according to right reason,

04:36:33.005 --> 04:36:36.165
will not be able to turn thee aside from thy proper action,

04:36:36.865 --> 04:36:40.525
so neither let them drive thee from thy benevolent feelings towards them,

04:36:41.085 --> 04:36:43.585
but be on thy guard equally in both matters,

04:36:43.965 --> 04:36:46.585
not only in the matter of steady judgment and action,

04:36:47.025 --> 04:36:52.585
but also in the matter of gentleness towards those who try to hinder or otherwise trouble thee.

04:36:53.185 --> 04:36:56.465
For this is also a weakness, to be vexed at them,

04:36:56.725 --> 04:36:59.245
as well as to be diverted from thy course of action,

04:36:59.545 --> 04:37:01.065
and to give way through fear,

04:37:01.685 --> 04:37:04.105
for both are equally deserters from their post,

04:37:04.605 --> 04:37:06.205
the man who does it through fear,

04:37:06.625 --> 04:37:10.845
and the man who is alienated from him who is by nature a kinsman and a friend.

04:37:13.665 --> 04:37:16.605
There is no nature which is inferior to art,

04:37:17.065 --> 04:37:19.405
for the arts imitate the natures of things,

04:37:19.405 --> 04:37:23.585
but if this is so, that nature which is the most perfect

04:37:23.585 --> 04:37:26.345
and the most comprehensive of all natures,

04:37:26.605 --> 04:37:28.725
cannot fall short of the skill of art.

04:37:29.685 --> 04:37:33.565
Now all arts do the inferior things for the sake of the superior,

04:37:34.405 --> 04:37:37.285
therefore the universal nature does so too,

04:37:38.045 --> 04:37:40.985
and indeed hence is the origin of justice,

04:37:41.565 --> 04:37:44.625
and in justice the other virtues have their foundation,

04:37:44.625 --> 04:37:49.705
for justice will not be observed if we either care for middle things,

04:37:49.885 --> 04:37:54.785
things indifferent, or are easily deceived and careless and changeable.

04:37:57.385 --> 04:37:59.805
If the things do not come to thee,

04:38:00.225 --> 04:38:03.205
the pursuits and avoidances of which disturb thee,

04:38:03.645 --> 04:38:06.465
still in a manner thou goest to them,

04:38:07.185 --> 04:38:09.925
let then thy judgment about them be at rest,

04:38:10.245 --> 04:38:12.105
and they will remain quiet,

04:38:12.105 --> 04:38:16.105
and thou wilt not be seen either pursuing or avoiding.

04:38:18.505 --> 04:38:21.525
The spherical form of the soul maintains its figure,

04:38:21.985 --> 04:38:24.385
when it is neither extended toward any object,

04:38:24.725 --> 04:38:28.345
nor contracted inwards, nor dispersed, nor sinks down,

04:38:28.945 --> 04:38:32.865
but is illuminated by light, by which it sees the truth,

04:38:33.245 --> 04:38:36.885
the truth of all things, and the truth that is in itself.

04:38:39.665 --> 04:38:42.185
Suppose any man shall despise me,

04:38:42.705 --> 04:38:44.305
let him look to that himself,

04:38:45.005 --> 04:38:46.605
but I will look to this,

04:38:46.905 --> 04:38:51.285
that I be not discovered doing or saying anything deserving of contempt.

04:38:52.445 --> 04:38:55.565
Shall any man hate me, let him look to it,

04:38:55.765 --> 04:38:59.145
but I will be mild and benevolent towards every man,

04:38:59.665 --> 04:39:02.045
and ready to show even him his mistake,

04:39:02.645 --> 04:39:03.785
not reproachfully,

04:39:03.785 --> 04:39:06.825
nor yet as making a display of my endurance,

04:39:07.445 --> 04:39:10.625
but nobly and honestly like the great Phocion,

04:39:11.245 --> 04:39:13.425
unless indeed he only assumed it.

04:39:14.045 --> 04:39:16.665
For the interior parts ought to be such,

04:39:17.125 --> 04:39:19.345
and a man ought to be seen by the gods

04:39:19.345 --> 04:39:22.625
neither dissatisfied with anything, nor complaining.

04:39:23.665 --> 04:39:25.405
For what evil is it to thee,

04:39:25.705 --> 04:39:28.925
if thou art now doing what is agreeable to thy own nature,

04:39:29.505 --> 04:39:31.865
and art satisfied with that which at this moment

04:39:31.865 --> 04:39:34.125
is suitable to the nature of the universe,

04:39:35.065 --> 04:39:37.765
since thou art a human being placed at thy post,

04:39:38.225 --> 04:39:40.445
in order that what is for the common advantage

04:39:40.445 --> 04:39:42.285
may be done in some way.

04:39:43.885 --> 04:39:47.065
Men despise one another and flatter one another,

04:39:47.505 --> 04:39:50.325
and men wish to raise themselves above one another,

04:39:50.765 --> 04:39:52.805
and crouch before one another.

04:39:55.465 --> 04:39:58.605
How unsound and insincere is he who says,

04:39:58.605 --> 04:40:01.565
I have determined to deal with thee in a fair way.

04:40:02.385 --> 04:40:03.845
What art thou doing, man?

04:40:04.185 --> 04:40:06.165
There is no occasion to give this notice.

04:40:06.525 --> 04:40:08.565
It will soon show itself by acts.

04:40:09.465 --> 04:40:12.105
The voice ought to be plainly written on the forehead.

04:40:13.085 --> 04:40:14.785
Such as a man's character is,

04:40:14.825 --> 04:40:16.905
he immediately shows it in his eyes,

04:40:17.365 --> 04:40:20.245
just as he who is beloved forthwith reads everything

04:40:20.245 --> 04:40:21.525
in the eyes of lovers.

04:40:22.665 --> 04:40:26.085
The man who is honest and good ought to be exactly like a man

04:40:26.085 --> 04:40:29.085
who smells strong, so that the bystander,

04:40:29.085 --> 04:40:30.345
as soon as he comes near him,

04:40:30.625 --> 04:40:32.685
must smell whether he chews or not.

04:40:33.545 --> 04:40:36.845
But the affectation of simplicity is like a crooked stick.

04:40:37.525 --> 04:40:40.085
Nothing is more disgraceful than a wolfish friendship.

04:40:41.025 --> 04:40:42.685
Avoid this most of all.

04:40:43.105 --> 04:40:46.845
The good and simple and benevolent show all these things

04:40:46.845 --> 04:40:49.765
in the eyes, and there is no mistaking.

04:40:52.005 --> 04:40:53.985
As to living in the best way,

04:40:53.985 --> 04:40:55.985
this power is in the soul,

04:40:56.545 --> 04:40:59.065
if it be indifferent to things which are indifferent.

04:40:59.765 --> 04:41:01.125
And it will be indifferent,

04:41:01.345 --> 04:41:04.485
if it looks on each of these things separately and altogether,

04:41:04.485 --> 04:41:07.985
and if it remembers that not one of them produces in us

04:41:07.985 --> 04:41:11.125
an opinion about itself, nor comes to us.

04:41:11.485 --> 04:41:13.625
But these things remain immovable,

04:41:13.945 --> 04:41:17.685
and it is we ourselves who produce the judgments about them,

04:41:17.865 --> 04:41:21.005
and, as we may say, write them in ourselves,

04:41:21.005 --> 04:41:23.845
it being in our power not to write them,

04:41:24.005 --> 04:41:26.865
and it being in our power, if perchance these judgments

04:41:26.865 --> 04:41:29.745
haven't perceptibly got a mission to our minds,

04:41:30.205 --> 04:41:31.425
to wipe them out.

04:41:31.865 --> 04:41:35.365
And if we remember also that such attention will only be

04:41:35.365 --> 04:41:39.125
for a short time, and then life will be at an end.

04:41:40.125 --> 04:41:43.245
Besides, what trouble is there at all in doing this?

04:41:43.665 --> 04:41:46.825
For if these things are according to nature, rejoice in them,

04:41:46.965 --> 04:41:48.525
and they will be easy to thee.

04:41:48.525 --> 04:41:50.825
But if contrary to nature,

04:41:51.185 --> 04:41:53.525
seek what is conformable to thy own nature,

04:41:53.945 --> 04:41:57.445
and strive towards this, even if it bring no reputation,

04:41:58.005 --> 04:42:00.705
for every man is allowed to seek his own good.

04:42:03.625 --> 04:42:05.905
Consider whence each thing has come,

04:42:06.385 --> 04:42:09.525
and of what it consists, and into what it changes,

04:42:10.105 --> 04:42:13.145
and what kind of a thing it will be when it is changed,

04:42:13.625 --> 04:42:15.665
and that it will sustain no harm.

04:42:18.565 --> 04:42:22.245
If any have offended against thee, consider first.

04:42:23.445 --> 04:42:27.225
What is my relation to men, and that we are made for one another,

04:42:27.825 --> 04:42:31.025
and in another respect I was made to be said over them,

04:42:31.425 --> 04:42:34.285
as a ram over the flock, or a bull over the herd.

04:42:35.125 --> 04:42:38.325
But examine the matter from first principles, from this.

04:42:38.825 --> 04:42:43.065
If all things are not mere atoms, it is nature which orders all things.

04:42:43.565 --> 04:42:47.885
If this is so, the inferior things exist for the sake of the superior,

04:42:47.885 --> 04:42:50.485
and these for the sake of one another.

04:42:51.825 --> 04:42:56.345
Second, consider what kind of men they are at table, in bed, and so forth,

04:42:56.885 --> 04:43:01.405
and particularly, under what compulsions in respect of opinions they are,

04:43:01.705 --> 04:43:05.745
and as to their acts, consider with what pride they do what they do.

04:43:07.205 --> 04:43:12.085
Third, that if men do rightly what they do, we ought not to be displeased,

04:43:12.405 --> 04:43:16.745
but if they do not right, it is plain that they do so involuntarily,

04:43:16.745 --> 04:43:18.305
and in ignorance.

04:43:19.205 --> 04:43:22.725
For as every soul is unwillingly deprived of the truth,

04:43:23.245 --> 04:43:26.645
so also it is unwillingly deprived of the power of behaving

04:43:26.645 --> 04:43:29.725
to each man according to his deserts.

04:43:30.325 --> 04:43:34.345
Accordingly, men are pained when they are called unjust, ungrateful, and greedy,

04:43:34.785 --> 04:43:36.885
and in a word wrongdoers to their neighbors.

04:43:38.345 --> 04:43:42.405
Fourth, consider that thou also doest many things wrong,

04:43:42.825 --> 04:43:44.865
and that thou art a man like others,

04:43:44.865 --> 04:43:48.045
and even if thou dost abstain from certain faults,

04:43:48.425 --> 04:43:50.905
still thou hast the disposition to commit them,

04:43:51.325 --> 04:43:54.225
though either through cowardice or concern about reputation,

04:43:54.665 --> 04:43:58.105
or some such mean motive thou dost abstain from such faults.

04:43:59.445 --> 04:44:02.065
Fifth, consider that thou dost not even understand

04:44:02.065 --> 04:44:04.125
whether men are doing wrong or not,

04:44:04.485 --> 04:44:07.785
for many things are done with a certain reference to circumstances,

04:44:08.525 --> 04:44:11.225
and in short, a man must learn a great deal

04:44:11.225 --> 04:44:15.245
to enable him to pass a correct judgment on another man's acts.

04:44:18.005 --> 04:44:21.265
Sixth, consider when thou art much vexed or grieved

04:44:21.265 --> 04:44:23.525
that man's life is only a moment,

04:44:24.045 --> 04:44:27.365
and after a short time we are all laid out dead.

04:44:29.365 --> 04:44:32.985
Seventh, that it is not men's acts which disturb us,

04:44:33.305 --> 04:44:36.525
for those acts have their foundation in men's ruling principles,

04:44:36.525 --> 04:44:40.645
but it is our own opinions which disturb us.

04:44:41.385 --> 04:44:43.205
Take away these opinions then,

04:44:43.485 --> 04:44:46.165
and resolve to dismiss thy judgment about an act

04:44:46.165 --> 04:44:49.665
as if it were something grievous, and thy anger is gone.

04:44:50.445 --> 04:44:52.925
How then shall I take away these opinions?

04:44:53.405 --> 04:44:57.385
By reflecting that no wrongful act of another brings shame on thee.

04:44:58.105 --> 04:45:00.585
For unless that which is shameful is alone bad,

04:45:01.085 --> 04:45:04.065
thou also must of necessity do many things wrong,

04:45:04.065 --> 04:45:06.985
and become a robber and everything else.

04:45:08.725 --> 04:45:11.645
Eighth, consider how much more pain is brought on us

04:45:11.645 --> 04:45:15.185
by the anger and vexation caused by such acts

04:45:15.185 --> 04:45:19.585
than by the acts themselves at which we are angry and vexed.

04:45:20.605 --> 04:45:23.925
Ninth, consider that a good disposition is invincible,

04:45:24.485 --> 04:45:28.285
if it be genuine, and not an affected smile and acting apart.

04:45:29.305 --> 04:45:31.705
For what will the most violent man do to thee,

04:45:31.705 --> 04:45:35.105
if thou continuest to be of a kind disposition towards him,

04:45:35.365 --> 04:45:39.385
and if, as opportunity offers, thou gently admonishest him

04:45:39.385 --> 04:45:42.205
and calmly correctest his errors at the very time

04:45:42.205 --> 04:45:44.425
when he is trying to do thee harm, saying,

04:45:44.425 --> 04:45:48.965
Not so, my child, we are constituted by nature for something else.

04:45:49.345 --> 04:45:51.105
I shall certainly not be injured,

04:45:51.465 --> 04:45:53.845
but thou art injuring thyself, my child.

04:45:54.765 --> 04:45:59.265
And show him with gentle tact and by general principles that this is so,

04:45:59.265 --> 04:46:02.245
and that even bees do not do as he does,

04:46:02.405 --> 04:46:05.785
nor any animals which are formed by nature to be gregarious.

04:46:06.425 --> 04:46:09.765
And thou must not do this neither with any double meaning,

04:46:10.145 --> 04:46:13.065
nor in the way of reproach, but affectionately,

04:46:13.285 --> 04:46:15.325
and without any rancor in thy soul.

04:46:15.825 --> 04:46:18.085
And not as if thou were lecturing him,

04:46:18.445 --> 04:46:20.945
nor yet that any bystander may admire,

04:46:21.605 --> 04:46:24.325
but either when he is alone, and if others are present.

04:46:26.585 --> 04:46:28.225
Remember these nine rules,

04:46:28.605 --> 04:46:31.405
as if thou hast received them as a gift from the muses,

04:46:31.765 --> 04:46:35.385
and begin at last to be a man while thou livest.

04:46:36.525 --> 04:46:40.285
But thou must equally avoid flattering men and being vexed at them,

04:46:40.425 --> 04:46:42.785
for both are unsocial and lead to harm.

04:46:43.665 --> 04:46:46.625
And let this truth be present to thee in the excitement of anger,

04:46:46.985 --> 04:46:49.585
that to be moved by passion is not manly,

04:46:49.885 --> 04:46:51.745
but that mildness and gentleness,

04:46:51.745 --> 04:46:54.365
as they are more agreeable to human nature,

04:46:54.865 --> 04:46:57.025
so also are they more manly.

04:46:57.545 --> 04:47:02.385
And he who possesses these qualities possesses strength, nerves, and courage,

04:47:02.885 --> 04:47:06.705
and not the man who is subject to fits of passion and discontent.

04:47:07.425 --> 04:47:11.645
For in the same degree in which a man's mind is nearer to freedom from all passion,

04:47:12.305 --> 04:47:15.085
in the same degree also is it nearer to strength.

04:47:15.645 --> 04:47:18.705
And as the sense of pain is a characteristic of weakness,

04:47:19.285 --> 04:47:20.885
so also is anger.

04:47:20.885 --> 04:47:25.585
For he who yields to pain, and he who yields to anger,

04:47:26.085 --> 04:47:28.605
both are wounded, and both submit.

04:47:30.265 --> 04:47:35.765
But if thou wilt, receive also a tenth present from the leader of the muses, Apollo,

04:47:36.445 --> 04:47:41.185
and it is this, that to expect bad men not to do wrong is madness,

04:47:41.665 --> 04:47:44.565
for he who expects this desires an impossibility.

04:47:45.325 --> 04:47:47.825
But to allow men to behave so to others,

04:47:47.825 --> 04:47:52.485
to expect them not to do thee any wrong, is irrational and tyrannical.

04:47:55.265 --> 04:47:58.965
There are four principal aberrations of the superior faculty,

04:47:59.625 --> 04:48:02.225
against which thou shouldst be constantly on thy guard.

04:48:02.765 --> 04:48:06.485
And when thou hast detected them, thou shouldst wipe them out,

04:48:06.585 --> 04:48:08.145
and say on each occasion thus,

04:48:08.585 --> 04:48:10.245
This thought is not necessary.

04:48:10.805 --> 04:48:13.165
This tends to destroy social union.

04:48:13.845 --> 04:48:16.725
This which thou art going to say comes not from the real thoughts.

04:48:16.725 --> 04:48:20.445
For thou shouldst consider it among the most absurd of things,

04:48:20.845 --> 04:48:22.925
for a man not to speak from his real thoughts.

04:48:23.805 --> 04:48:26.905
But the fourth is when thou shalt reproach thyself for anything.

04:48:27.625 --> 04:48:30.285
For this is an evidence of the diviner part within thee,

04:48:30.625 --> 04:48:33.825
being overpowered, and yielding to the less honorable,

04:48:34.265 --> 04:48:38.445
and to the perishable part, the body, and to its gross pleasures.

04:48:41.965 --> 04:48:45.925
Thy aerial part, and all the fiery parts which are mingled in thee,

04:48:45.925 --> 04:48:48.525
though by nature they have an upward tendency,

04:48:49.225 --> 04:48:51.965
still in obedience to the disposition of the universe

04:48:51.965 --> 04:48:55.585
they are overpowered here in the compound mass, the body.

04:48:56.305 --> 04:48:59.565
And also the whole of the earthy part and the watery,

04:49:00.065 --> 04:49:01.765
though their tendency is downwards,

04:49:02.305 --> 04:49:05.965
still are raised up and occupy a position which is not their natural one.

04:49:07.085 --> 04:49:10.265
In this manner then the elemental parts obey the universal,

04:49:10.865 --> 04:49:14.245
for when they have been fixed in any place perforce they remain there,

04:49:14.245 --> 04:49:17.505
until again the universal shall sound the signal for dissolution.

04:49:19.045 --> 04:49:22.125
Is it not then strange that thy intelligent part only

04:49:22.125 --> 04:49:25.945
should be disobedient and discontented with its own place?

04:49:26.845 --> 04:49:28.925
And yet no force is imposed on it,

04:49:28.945 --> 04:49:31.845
but only those things which are conformable to its nature.

04:49:32.745 --> 04:49:36.625
Still it does not submit, but is carried in the opposite direction.

04:49:37.545 --> 04:49:40.545
For the movement toward injustice and intemperance,

04:49:40.545 --> 04:49:42.785
and to anger and grief and fear,

04:49:43.265 --> 04:49:46.345
is nothing else than the act of one who deviates from nature.

04:49:47.165 --> 04:49:51.165
And also when the ruling faculty is discontented with anything that happens,

04:49:51.685 --> 04:49:53.485
then too it deserts its post.

04:49:54.045 --> 04:49:57.445
For it is constituted for piety and reverence toward the gods,

04:49:57.905 --> 04:49:59.305
no less than for justice.

04:50:00.545 --> 04:50:04.645
For these qualities also are comprehended under the generic term of contentment

04:50:04.645 --> 04:50:06.465
with the constitution of things,

04:50:06.885 --> 04:50:09.605
and indeed they are prior to acts of justice.

04:50:12.485 --> 04:50:15.905
He who has not one and always the same object in life

04:50:15.905 --> 04:50:18.645
cannot be one and the same all through his life.

04:50:19.305 --> 04:50:23.145
But what I have said is not enough, unless this also is added,

04:50:23.545 --> 04:50:25.365
what this object ought to be.

04:50:26.125 --> 04:50:30.185
For as there is not the same opinion about all the things which in some way or other

04:50:30.185 --> 04:50:32.705
are considered by the majority to be good,

04:50:32.945 --> 04:50:34.765
but only about some certain things,

04:50:34.865 --> 04:50:37.125
that is, things which concern the common interest,

04:50:37.705 --> 04:50:40.425
so also we ought to propose to ourselves

04:50:40.425 --> 04:50:43.105
an object which shall be of a common kind,

04:50:43.365 --> 04:50:44.725
social and political.

04:50:45.685 --> 04:50:48.525
For he who directs all his own efforts to this object

04:50:48.525 --> 04:50:50.325
will make all his acts alike,

04:50:51.005 --> 04:50:53.325
and thus will always be the same.

04:50:55.785 --> 04:50:59.065
Think of the country mouse and of the town mouse,

04:50:59.505 --> 04:51:03.045
and of the alarm and trepidation of the town mouse.

04:51:05.645 --> 04:51:08.245
Socrates used to call the opinions of the many

04:51:08.245 --> 04:51:10.445
by the name of Lameae,

04:51:10.865 --> 04:51:12.705
bug-bears to frighten children.

04:51:14.045 --> 04:51:16.215
The Lacedaemonians, at their public spectacles,

04:51:17.285 --> 04:51:19.315
used to set seats in the shade for strangers,

04:51:20.185 --> 04:51:22.345
but themselves sat down anywhere.

04:51:25.085 --> 04:51:27.405
Socrates excused himself to Perticus,

04:51:27.765 --> 04:51:28.925
for not going to him,

04:51:28.925 --> 04:51:33.005
saying it is because I would not perish by the worst of all ends,

04:51:33.565 --> 04:51:36.025
that is, I would not receive a favor,

04:51:36.365 --> 04:51:38.905
and then be unable to return it.

04:51:41.105 --> 04:51:44.165
In the writings of the Ephesians there was this precept,

04:51:44.865 --> 04:51:48.005
constantly to think of someone of the men of former times

04:51:48.005 --> 04:51:49.245
who practiced virtue.

04:51:51.965 --> 04:51:54.365
The Pythagoreans bid us in the morning,

04:51:54.605 --> 04:51:55.525
look to the heavens,

04:51:55.525 --> 04:52:00.385
that we may be reminded of those bodies which continually do the same things

04:52:00.385 --> 04:52:02.725
and in the same manner perform their work,

04:52:03.185 --> 04:52:06.305
and also be reminded of their purity and nudity,

04:52:06.745 --> 04:52:09.225
for there is no veil over a star.

04:52:12.165 --> 04:52:16.045
Consider what a man Socrates was when he dressed himself in a skin

04:52:16.045 --> 04:52:19.425
after Xanthippe had taken his cloak and gone out,

04:52:19.685 --> 04:52:22.945
and what Socrates said to his friends who were ashamed of him

04:52:22.945 --> 04:52:25.965
and drew back from him when they saw him dressed thus.

04:52:28.765 --> 04:52:33.185
Neither in writing nor in reading will thou be able to lay down rules for others

04:52:33.185 --> 04:52:36.925
before thou shalt have learned to obey rules thyself.

04:52:37.385 --> 04:52:39.645
Much more is this so in life.

04:52:41.525 --> 04:52:45.425
A slave thou art, free speech is not for thee.

04:52:47.085 --> 04:52:51.985
And my heart laughed within. Odyssey 9.4.13

04:52:53.345 --> 04:52:56.425
In virtue they will curse speaking harsh words.

04:52:57.485 --> 04:52:59.425
Hesiod works in days 184.

04:53:01.325 --> 04:53:04.225
To look for the fig in winter is a madman's act,

04:53:04.625 --> 04:53:08.185
such as he who looks for his child when it is no longer allowed.

04:53:08.925 --> 04:53:11.445
Epictetus 3.24.87

04:53:13.105 --> 04:53:16.265
When a man kisses his child, said Epictetus,

04:53:16.645 --> 04:53:18.205
he should whisper to himself,

04:53:18.865 --> 04:53:21.045
Tomorrow perchance thou wilt die.

04:53:21.565 --> 04:53:23.785
But those are words of bad omen.

04:53:24.525 --> 04:53:27.485
No word is a word of bad omen, said Epictetus,

04:53:28.125 --> 04:53:30.005
which expresses any work of nature.

04:53:30.605 --> 04:53:33.945
Or, if it is so, it is also a word of bad omen

04:53:33.945 --> 04:53:36.845
to speak of the ears of corn being reaped.

04:53:37.925 --> 04:53:40.305
Epictetus 3.24.88

04:53:42.305 --> 04:53:46.625
The unripe grape, the ripe bunch, the dried grape,

04:53:47.065 --> 04:53:49.305
all are changes, not into nothing,

04:53:49.805 --> 04:53:52.605
but into something which exists not yet.

04:53:53.245 --> 04:53:55.445
Epictetus 3.24.

04:53:57.685 --> 04:53:59.925
No man can rob us of our free will.

04:54:00.805 --> 04:54:03.445
Epictetus 3.22.105

04:54:05.765 --> 04:54:07.385
Epictetus also said,

04:54:07.385 --> 04:54:10.425
A man must discover an art, or rules,

04:54:10.925 --> 04:54:12.885
with respect to giving his assent.

04:54:13.505 --> 04:54:15.165
And in respect to his movements,

04:54:15.265 --> 04:54:18.745
he must be careful that they be made with regard to circumstances,

04:54:19.345 --> 04:54:21.485
that they be consistent with social interests,

04:54:22.105 --> 04:54:24.465
that they have regard to the value of the object.

04:54:25.185 --> 04:54:26.925
And as to sensual desire,

04:54:27.505 --> 04:54:29.725
he should altogether keep away from it.

04:54:30.005 --> 04:54:31.325
And as to avoidance,

04:54:31.565 --> 04:54:33.925
he should not show it with respect to any of the things

04:54:33.925 --> 04:54:35.485
which are not in our power.

04:54:38.245 --> 04:54:39.865
The dispute then, he said,

04:54:40.425 --> 04:54:42.125
is not about any common matter,

04:54:42.665 --> 04:54:44.965
but about being mad or not.

04:54:47.965 --> 04:54:49.305
Socrates used to say,

04:54:49.425 --> 04:54:52.805
What do you want, souls of rational men or irrational?

04:54:53.525 --> 04:54:54.905
Souls of rational men.

04:54:55.205 --> 04:54:58.525
Of what rational men? Sound or unsound? Sound.

04:54:59.145 --> 04:55:01.085
Why then do you not seek for them?

04:55:01.205 --> 04:55:02.445
Because we have them.

04:55:02.445 --> 04:55:06.485
Why then do you fight and quarrel?

04:55:43.591 --> 04:55:50.791
All those things at which thou wishest to arrive by a secuitous road, thou canst have now,

04:55:51.071 --> 04:55:58.751
if thou dost not refuse them to thyself. And this means, if thou wilt, take no notice of all the

04:55:58.751 --> 04:56:05.751
past, and trust the future to providence, and direct the present only conformably to piety and

04:56:05.751 --> 04:56:12.651
justice. Conformably to piety, that thou mayest be content with the lot which is assigned to thee,

04:56:13.011 --> 04:56:20.451
for nature designed it for thee, and thee for it. Conformably to justice, that thou mayest always

04:56:20.451 --> 04:56:26.351
speak the truth freely and without disguise, and do the things which are agreeable to law,

04:56:26.611 --> 04:56:32.451
and according to the worth of each. And let neither another man's wickedness hinder thee,

04:56:32.451 --> 04:56:39.231
nor opinion, nor voice, nor yet the sensations of the poor flesh which has grown about thee,

04:56:39.791 --> 04:56:46.591
for the passive part will look to this. If then, whatever the time may be when thou shalt be near

04:56:46.591 --> 04:56:52.611
to thy departure, neglecting everything else, thou shalt respect only thy ruling faculty,

04:56:53.171 --> 04:57:00.431
and the divinity within thee. And if thou shalt be afraid, not because thou must sometimes cease

04:57:00.431 --> 04:57:07.631
to live, but if thou shalt fear never to have begun to live according to nature, then thou wilt

04:57:07.631 --> 04:57:14.311
be a man worthy of the universe which has produced thee. And thou wilt cease to be a stranger in thy

04:57:14.311 --> 04:57:19.971
native land, and to wonder at things which happen daily as if they were something unexpected,

04:57:20.471 --> 04:57:30.411
and to be dependent on this or that. God sees the minds of all men, bared of the material vesture

04:57:30.411 --> 04:57:38.651
and rind and impurities. For with his intellectual part alone, he touches the intelligence only which

04:57:38.651 --> 04:57:45.991
has flowed and been derived from himself into these bodies. And if thou also usest thyself

04:57:45.991 --> 04:57:52.871
to do this, thou wilt rid thyself of thy much trouble. For he who regards not the poor flesh

04:57:52.871 --> 04:57:58.171
which envelops him, surely will not trouble himself by looking after raiment and dwelling

04:57:58.171 --> 04:58:08.031
and fame and such like externals and show. The things are three of which thou art composed,

04:58:08.571 --> 04:58:15.691
a little body, a little breath, intelligence. Of these the first two are thine so far as it is thy

04:58:15.691 --> 04:58:23.591
duty to take care of them. But the third alone is properly thine. Therefore, if thou shalt separate

04:58:23.591 --> 04:58:30.671
from thyself, that is, from thy understanding, whatever others do or say, and whatever thou

04:58:30.671 --> 04:58:36.631
hast done or said thyself, and whatever future things trouble thee because they may happen,

04:58:37.151 --> 04:58:42.951
and whatever in the body which envelops thee, or in the breath, which is by nature associated

04:58:42.951 --> 04:58:49.291
with the body, is attached to thee independent of thy will, and whatever the external circumfluid

04:58:49.291 --> 04:58:55.991
vortex whirls round, so that the intellectual power exempt from the things of fate can live

04:58:55.991 --> 04:59:03.811
pure and free by itself, doing what is just and accepting what happens and saying the truth.

04:59:04.331 --> 04:59:10.191
If thou wilt separate, I say, from this ruling faculty the things which are attached to it,

04:59:10.391 --> 04:59:16.211
by the impressions of sense, and the things of time to come and of time that is past,

04:59:16.211 --> 04:59:24.711
and wilt make thyself like in Petticles a sphere, all round and in its joyous rest reposing. And if

04:59:24.711 --> 04:59:31.631
thou shalt strive to live only what is really thy life, that is, the present, then thou wilt be able

04:59:31.631 --> 04:59:38.111
to pass that portion of life which remains for thee up to the time of thy death, free from

04:59:38.111 --> 04:59:42.671
perturbations, nobly and obedient to the God that is within thee.

04:59:45.251 --> 04:59:50.971
I have often wondered how it is that every man loves himself more than all the rest of men,

04:59:51.271 --> 04:59:58.691
but yet sets less value on his own opinion of himself than on the opinion of others. If then

04:59:58.691 --> 05:00:04.571
a god or a wise teacher should present himself to a man, and bid him to think of nothing,

05:00:04.911 --> 05:00:10.211
and to design nothing which he would not express as soon as he conceived it, he could not endure

05:00:10.211 --> 05:00:16.031
it even for a single day. So much more respect have we to what our neighbors shall think of

05:00:16.031 --> 05:00:25.391
us than to what we shall think of ourselves. How can it be that the gods, after having arranged

05:00:25.391 --> 05:00:32.771
all things well and benevolently for mankind, have overlooked this alone, that some men and

05:00:32.771 --> 05:00:39.371
very good men, and men who, as we may say, have had most communion with the divinity,

05:00:39.371 --> 05:00:45.711
and through pious acts and religious observances, have been most intimate with the divinity,

05:00:46.291 --> 05:00:52.331
when they have once died should never exist again, but should be completely extinguished?

05:00:53.431 --> 05:01:00.071
But if this is so, be assured that if it ought to have been otherwise, the gods would have done it.

05:01:00.771 --> 05:01:07.431
Or if it were just, it would also be possible. And if it were according to nature, nature would

05:01:07.431 --> 05:01:15.791
have had it so. But because it is not so, if in fact it is not so, be thou convinced that it

05:01:15.791 --> 05:01:23.071
ought not to have been so. For thou seest even of thyself that in this inquiry thou are disputing

05:01:23.071 --> 05:01:28.731
with the deity, and we should not thus dispute with the gods, unless they were most excellent

05:01:28.731 --> 05:01:35.071
and most just. But if this is so, they would not have allowed anything in the ordering of the

05:01:35.071 --> 05:01:44.751
universe to be neglected unjustly and irrationally. Practice thyself even in the things which thou

05:01:44.751 --> 05:01:50.911
despairest of accomplishing. For even the left hand, which is ineffectual for all other things,

05:01:51.051 --> 05:01:56.871
for want of practice, holds the bridle more vigorously than the right hand, for it has been

05:02:00.791 --> 05:02:09.111
Consider in what condition, both in body and soul, a man should be when he is overtaken by death.

05:02:10.011 --> 05:02:15.751
And consider the shortness of life, the boundless abyss of time, past and future,

05:02:16.151 --> 05:02:24.771
the feebleness of all matter. Contemplate the formative principles of things bare of their

05:02:24.771 --> 05:02:34.171
the purposes of actions. Consider what pain is, what pleasure is, and death and fame. Who is to

05:02:34.171 --> 05:02:41.451
himself the cause of his uneasiness, how no man is hindered by another, that everything is opinion.

05:02:44.471 --> 05:02:51.391
In the application of thy principles thou must be like the pancratiest, not like the gladiator.

05:02:51.391 --> 05:02:59.331
For the gladiator lets fall the sword which he uses and is killed, but the other always has his

05:02:59.331 --> 05:03:09.851
hand, and needs to do nothing else than use it. See what things are in themselves, dividing them

05:03:09.851 --> 05:03:20.171
into matter, form, and purpose. What a power man has to do nothing except what God will approve,

05:03:20.171 --> 05:03:29.511
and to accept all that God may give him. With respect to that which happens conformably to

05:03:29.511 --> 05:03:36.991
nature, we ought to blame neither gods, for they do nothing wrong either voluntarily or involuntarily,

05:03:37.651 --> 05:03:44.371
nor men, for they do nothing wrong except involuntarily. Consequently we should blame nobody.

05:03:47.031 --> 05:03:54.331
How ridiculous and what a stranger he is who is surprised at anything which happens in life.

05:03:57.091 --> 05:04:03.211
Either there is a fatal necessity and invincible order, or a kind providence,

05:04:03.811 --> 05:04:10.311
or a confusion without a purpose and without a director. If then there is an invincible

05:04:10.311 --> 05:04:17.171
necessity, why dost thou resist? But if there is a providence which allows itself to be propitiated,

05:04:17.751 --> 05:04:23.671
make thyself worthy of the help of the divinity. But if there is a confusion without a governor,

05:04:24.391 --> 05:04:31.011
be content that in such a tempest thou hast in thyself a certain ruling intelligence.

05:04:31.811 --> 05:04:38.071
And even if the tempest carry thee away, let it carry away the poor flesh, the poor breath,

05:04:38.071 --> 05:04:43.711
everything else, for the intelligence at least it will not carry away.

05:04:46.831 --> 05:04:52.151
Does the light of the lamp shine without losing its splendor until it is extinguished,

05:04:52.571 --> 05:04:59.051
and shall the truth which is in thee and justice and temperance be extinguished before thy death?

05:05:01.731 --> 05:05:06.451
When a man has presented the appearance of having done wrong, say,

05:05:06.851 --> 05:05:12.711
How then do I know if this is a wrongful act? And even if he has done wrong,

05:05:12.951 --> 05:05:18.631
how do I know that he has not condemned himself, and so this is like tearing his own face?

05:05:19.451 --> 05:05:25.711
Consider that he who would not have the bad man do wrong is like the man who would not have the

05:05:25.711 --> 05:05:31.271
fig-tree to bear juice in the figs, and infants to cry, and the horse to neigh,

05:05:31.831 --> 05:05:38.451
and whatever else must of necessity be. For what must a man do who has such a character,

05:05:39.231 --> 05:05:43.331
if then thou art irritable, cure this man's disposition?

05:05:46.111 --> 05:05:51.951
If it is not right, do not do it. If it is not true, do not say it.

05:05:54.611 --> 05:06:00.291
In everything, always observe what the thing is which produces for thee an appearance,

05:06:01.031 --> 05:06:06.391
and resolve it by dividing it into the formal, the material, the purpose,

05:06:06.671 --> 05:06:14.931
and the time within which it must end. Perceive at last that thou hast in thee

05:06:14.931 --> 05:06:20.471
something better and more divine than the things which cause the various effects,

05:06:20.471 --> 05:06:27.931
and as it were pull thee by the strings. What is there now in my mind? Is it fear,

05:06:28.311 --> 05:06:32.051
or suspicion, or desire, or anything of the kind?

05:06:35.151 --> 05:06:40.811
First, do nothing inconsiderately, nor without a purpose. Second,

05:06:41.171 --> 05:06:45.551
make thy acts refer to nothing else than to a social end.

05:06:48.471 --> 05:06:56.231
Consider that before long thou wilt be nobody and nowhere, nor will any of the things exist

05:06:56.231 --> 05:07:04.051
which thou now seest, nor any of those who are now living. For all things are formed by nature

05:07:04.051 --> 05:07:12.571
to change and be turned and to perish, in order that other things in continuous succession may exist.

05:07:15.391 --> 05:07:22.791
Consider that everything is opinion, and opinion is in thy power. Take away then,

05:07:22.931 --> 05:07:28.951
when thou choosest, thy opinion, and like a mariner who is double the promontory,

05:07:29.371 --> 05:07:33.871
thou wilt find calm, everything stable, and a wave-less bay.

05:07:36.611 --> 05:07:42.591
Any one activity, wherever it may be, when it is ceased at its proper time,

05:07:43.031 --> 05:07:48.051
suffers no evil because it is ceased. Nor he who has done this act,

05:07:48.371 --> 05:07:54.911
does he suffer any evil for this reason that the act has ceased. In like manner, then,

05:07:55.231 --> 05:08:01.811
the whole which consists of all the acts which is our life, if it ceased at its proper time,

05:08:01.811 --> 05:08:08.831
suffers no evil for this reason that it is ceased. Nor he who has terminated this series

05:08:08.831 --> 05:08:15.831
at the proper time, has he been ill dealt with. But the proper time and the limit nature fixes,

05:08:16.311 --> 05:08:22.791
sometimes, as in old age, the peculiar nature of man, but always the universal nature,

05:08:23.291 --> 05:08:28.271
by the change of whose parts the whole universe continues ever young and perfect.

05:08:28.271 --> 05:08:36.491
And everything which is useful to the universal is always good and in season. Therefore the

05:08:36.491 --> 05:08:42.951
termination of life for every man is no evil, because neither is it shameful, since it is

05:08:42.951 --> 05:08:49.151
both independent to the will and not opposed to the general interest. But it is good,

05:08:49.351 --> 05:08:55.971
since it is seasonable and profitable too and congruent with the universal. For thus,

05:08:55.971 --> 05:09:01.231
too, he is moved by the Deity, who is moved in the same manner with the Deity,

05:09:01.611 --> 05:09:04.631
and moved towards the same things in his mind.

05:09:07.351 --> 05:09:14.251
These three principles thou must have in readiness. In the things which thou doest,

05:09:14.551 --> 05:09:21.451
do nothing either inconsiderately or otherwise as justice herself would act. But with respect

05:09:21.451 --> 05:09:27.811
to what may happen to thee from without, consider that it happens either by chance or according

05:09:27.811 --> 05:09:35.531
to providence, and thou must neither blame chance nor accuse providence. Second, consider

05:09:35.531 --> 05:09:42.331
what every being is, from the seed to the time of its receiving a soul, and from the reception

05:09:42.331 --> 05:09:47.931
of a soul to the giving back of the same, and of what things every being is compounded,

05:09:47.931 --> 05:09:55.291
and into what things it is resolved. Third, if thou shouldest suddenly be raised up above

05:09:55.291 --> 05:10:01.071
the earth, and shouldest look down on human beings, and observe the variety of them how

05:10:01.071 --> 05:10:07.291
great it is, and at the same time also shouldest see at a glance how great is the number of

05:10:07.291 --> 05:10:12.971
beings who dwell all around in the air and the ether, consider that as often as thou

05:10:12.971 --> 05:10:19.131
shouldest be raised up, thou wouldest see the same things, sameness of form, and shortness

05:10:19.131 --> 05:10:29.071
of duration. Are these things to be proud of? Cast away opinion, thou art saved. Who

05:10:29.071 --> 05:10:38.111
then hinders thee from casting it away? When thou art troubled about anything, thou hast

05:10:38.111 --> 05:10:46.151
this, that all things happen according to the universal nature, and forgotten this, that a man's

05:10:46.151 --> 05:10:52.351
wrongful act is nothing to thee, and further, thou hast forgotten this, that everything which

05:10:52.351 --> 05:11:00.131
happens always happens so and will happen so, and now happens so everywhere. Forgotten this,

05:11:00.511 --> 05:11:06.331
too, how close is the kinship between a man and the whole human race, for it is a community,

05:11:06.331 --> 05:11:14.391
not of a little blood or seed, but of intelligence. And thou hast forgotten this, too, that every

05:11:14.391 --> 05:11:22.311
man's intelligence is a god, and is an efflux of the deity. And forgotten this, that nothing is a

05:11:22.311 --> 05:11:30.251
man's own, but that his child and his body and his very soul came from the deity. Forgotten this,

05:11:30.251 --> 05:11:36.671
that everything is opinion. And lastly, thou hast forgotten that every man lives the present

05:11:36.671 --> 05:11:46.751
time only, and loses only this. Constantly bring to thy recollection those who have complained

05:11:46.751 --> 05:11:52.871
greatly about anything, those who have been most conspicuous by the greatest fame or misfortunes,

05:11:52.871 --> 05:12:01.671
or enmities or fortunes of any kind. Then think, where are they all now? Smoke and ash and a tail,

05:12:02.051 --> 05:12:08.231
or not even a tail. And let there be present to thy mind also everything of this sort,

05:12:08.691 --> 05:12:15.571
how Fabius Catalinus lived in the country, and Lucius Lupus in his gardens, and Stertinius at

05:12:15.571 --> 05:12:25.631
Ia, and Tiberius at Capri, and Rufus at Velia. And, and fine, think of the eager pursuit of

05:12:25.631 --> 05:12:32.831
anything conjoined with pride, and how worthless everything is after which men violently strain,

05:12:33.531 --> 05:12:39.031
and how much more philosophical it is for a man in the opportunities presented to him to show

05:12:39.031 --> 05:12:47.051
himself just, temperate, obedient to the gods, and to do this with all simplicity. For the pride

05:12:47.051 --> 05:12:56.731
which is proud of its want of pride is the most intolerable of all. To those who ask,

05:12:56.971 --> 05:13:03.251
where hast thou seen the gods, or how dost thou comprehend that they exist, and so worshipest them?

05:13:03.251 --> 05:13:11.051
I answer, in the first place, they may be seen even with the eyes. In the second place, neither

05:13:11.051 --> 05:13:19.211
have I seen even my own soul, and yet I honor it. Thus then, with respect to the gods, from what I

05:13:19.211 --> 05:13:25.971
constantly experience of their power, from this I comprehend that they exist, and I venerate them.

05:13:28.211 --> 05:13:35.431
The safety of life is this, to examine everything all through, what it is itself,

05:13:35.831 --> 05:13:43.431
what is its material, what the formal part, with all thy soul to do justice and to say the truth.

05:13:44.151 --> 05:13:50.971
What remains except to enjoy life, by joining one good thing to another, so as not to leave

05:13:50.971 --> 05:13:59.051
even the smallest intervals between. There is one light of the sun, though it is interrupted by

05:13:59.051 --> 05:14:06.231
walls, mountains, and other things infinite. There is one common substance, though it is

05:14:06.231 --> 05:14:12.111
distributed among countless bodies which have their several qualities. There is one soul,

05:14:12.571 --> 05:14:19.731
though it is distributed among infinite natures and individual circumscriptions. There is one

05:14:19.731 --> 05:14:26.171
intelligent soul, though it seems to be divided. Now, in the things which have been mentioned,

05:14:26.611 --> 05:14:32.891
all the other parts, such as those which are air and matter, are without sensation and have

05:14:32.891 --> 05:14:38.571
no fellowship, and yet even these parts the intelligent principle holds together, and the

05:14:38.571 --> 05:14:45.511
gravitation towards the same. But intellect in a peculiar manner tends to that which is of the

05:14:45.511 --> 05:14:50.871
same kin, and combines with it, and the feeling for communion is not interrupted.

05:14:52.731 --> 05:15:00.291
What dost thou wish to continue to exist? Well, dost thou wish to have sensation, movement,

05:15:00.791 --> 05:15:08.991
growth, and then again to cease to grow, to use thy speech, to think? What is there of all these

05:15:09.711 --> 05:15:18.071
to thee worth desiring? But if it is easy to set little value on all these things, turn to that

05:15:18.071 --> 05:15:24.991
which remains, which is to follow reason and God. But it is inconsistent with honoring reason and

05:15:24.991 --> 05:15:30.711
God to be troubled, because by death a man will be deprived of the other things.

05:15:32.671 --> 05:15:40.371
How small a part of the boundless and unfathomable time is assigned to every man, for it is very soon

05:15:40.371 --> 05:15:46.971
swallowed up in the eternal, and how small a part of the whole substance, and how small a part of

05:15:46.971 --> 05:15:53.991
the universal soul, and on what a small claw to the whole earth thou creepest. Reflecting on all

05:15:53.991 --> 05:16:01.231
this, consider nothing to be great, except to act as thy nature leads thee, and to endure that

05:16:01.231 --> 05:16:10.531
which the common nature brings. How does the ruling faculty make use of itself? For all lies in this,

05:16:10.971 --> 05:16:18.711
but everything else, whether it is in the power of thy will or not, is only lifeless ashes and smoke.

05:16:20.691 --> 05:16:27.371
This reflection is most adapted to move us to contempt of death, that even those who think

05:16:27.371 --> 05:16:36.351
pleasure to be a good, and pain an evil, still have despised it. The man to whom that only is

05:16:36.351 --> 05:16:43.111
good which comes in due season, and to whom it is the same thing whether he has done more or fewer

05:16:43.111 --> 05:16:49.071
acts conformable to right reason, and to whom it makes no difference whether he contemplates the

05:16:49.071 --> 05:16:55.851
world for a longer or a shorter time, for this man neither is death a terrible thing.

05:16:58.071 --> 05:17:05.391
Man, thou hast been a citizen in this great state, the world. What difference does it make to thee,

05:17:05.391 --> 05:17:13.491
whether for five years or three? For that which is conformable to the laws is just for all. Where

05:17:13.491 --> 05:17:19.951
is the hardship then, if no tyrant nor yet an unjust judge sends thee away from the state,

05:17:20.351 --> 05:17:27.071
but nature who brought thee into it? The same as if a praetor who is employed an actor dismisses

05:17:27.071 --> 05:17:33.351
him from the stage. But I have not finished the five acts, but only three of them. Thou sayest

05:17:33.351 --> 05:17:40.651
well, but in life the three acts are the whole drama. For what shall be a complete drama is

05:17:40.651 --> 05:17:47.851
determined by him who was once the cause of its composition, and now of its dissolution. But thou

05:17:47.851 --> 05:17:56.511
art the cause of neither. Depart then satisfied, for he also who releases thee is satisfied.

05:18:06.446 --> 05:18:31.286
CHAP. XIII. Marcus Aurelius Antoninus by George Long, M.A.

05:18:31.926 --> 05:18:38.326
Marcus Antoninus was born at Rome AD 121 on the 26th of April.

05:18:39.006 --> 05:18:44.886
His father Aeneas Verus died while he was praetor. His mother was Domitia Colvilla,

05:18:45.346 --> 05:18:52.286
also named Lucilla. The emperor Titus Antoninus Pius married Aenea Galeria Faustina,

05:18:52.746 --> 05:18:58.126
the sister of Aeneas Verus, and was consequently the uncle of Marcus Antoninus.

05:18:58.846 --> 05:19:04.366
When Hadrian adopted Antoninus Pius and declared him his successor in the empire,

05:19:05.026 --> 05:19:11.646
Antoninus Pius adopted both Lucius Sionius Commodus, the son of Aelius Caesar, and Marcus

05:19:11.646 --> 05:19:18.846
Antoninus, whose original name was Marcus Aeneas Verus. Antoninus then took the name of Marcus

05:19:18.846 --> 05:19:26.726
Aelius Aurelius Verus, to which was added the title of Caesar in AD 139. The name Aelius belonged

05:19:26.726 --> 05:19:33.606
to Hadrian's family, and Aurelius was the name of Antoninus Pius. When Marcus Antoninus became

05:19:33.606 --> 05:19:39.426
Augustus, he dropped the name of Verus and took the name of Antoninus. Accordingly,

05:19:39.506 --> 05:19:44.726
he is generally named Marcus Aurelius Antoninus, or simply Marcus Antoninus.

05:19:45.646 --> 05:19:50.886
The youth was most carefully brought up. He thanks the gods that he had good grandfathers,

05:19:50.886 --> 05:19:56.706
good parents, a good sister, good teachers, good associates, good kinsmen and friends,

05:19:57.186 --> 05:20:02.566
nearly everything good. He had the happy fortune to witness the example of his uncle

05:20:02.566 --> 05:20:08.886
and adoptive father Antoninus Pius, and he has recorded in his work the virtues of this excellent

05:20:08.886 --> 05:20:15.246
man and prudent ruler. Like many young Romans, he tried his hand at poetry and studied rhetoric.

05:20:15.806 --> 05:20:20.966
Herodes Atticus and Marcus Cornelius Fronto were his teachers in eloquence.

05:20:21.466 --> 05:20:26.266
There are extant letters between Fronto and Marcus, which show the great affection of the

05:20:26.266 --> 05:20:30.826
pupil for the master, and the master's great hopes of his industrious pupil.

05:20:32.726 --> 05:20:40.306
Marcus Corneliae Fontonis Reliquiae, Berlin 1816. There are a few letters between Fronto and

05:20:40.306 --> 05:20:48.446
Antoninus Pius. Marcus Antoninus mentions Fronto among those to whom he was indebted for his

05:20:48.446 --> 05:20:55.506
education. When he was 11 years old, he assumed the dress of philosophers, something plain and

05:20:55.506 --> 05:21:02.126
coarse, became a hard student, and lived a most laborious, abstemious life, even so far as to

05:21:02.126 --> 05:21:08.506
injure his health. Finally, he abandoned poetry and rhetoric for philosophy, and he attached

05:21:08.506 --> 05:21:14.966
himself to the sect the Stoics. But he did not neglect the study of law, which was a useful

05:21:14.966 --> 05:21:20.746
preparation for the high place which he was designed to fill. His teacher was Lucius Velassianus

05:21:20.746 --> 05:21:27.106
Mycenaeus, a distinguished jurist. We must suppose that he learned the Roman discipline of arms,

05:21:27.566 --> 05:21:33.226
which was a necessary part of the education of a man who afterwards led his troops to battle

05:21:33.226 --> 05:21:41.106
against a warlike race. Antoninus has recorded in his first book the names of his teachers and the

05:21:41.106 --> 05:21:46.166
obligations which he owed to each of them. The way in which he speaks of what he learned from them

05:21:46.166 --> 05:21:51.726
might seem to savor a vanity or self-praise if we look carelessly at the way in which he has

05:21:51.726 --> 05:21:57.646
expressed himself. But if anyone draws this conclusion, he will be mistaken. Antoninus

05:21:57.646 --> 05:22:02.326
means to commemorate the merits of his several teachers, what they taught, and what a pupil

05:22:02.326 --> 05:22:08.306
might learn from them. Besides, this book, like the eleven other books, was for his own use,

05:22:08.586 --> 05:22:13.226
and if we may trust the note at the end of the first book, it was written during one of Marcus

05:22:13.226 --> 05:22:18.426
Antoninus's campaigns against the Quadi, at a time when the commemoration of the virtues of

05:22:18.426 --> 05:22:23.746
his illustrious teachers might remind him of their lessons and the practical uses which he

05:22:23.746 --> 05:22:31.026
might derive from them. Among his teachers of philosophy was Sextus of Chaeronea, a grandson

05:22:31.026 --> 05:22:37.786
of Plutarch. What he learned from this excellent man is told by himself. His favorite teacher was

05:22:37.786 --> 05:22:43.906
Quintus Junius Rusticus, a philosopher and also a man of practical good sense in public affairs.

05:22:44.746 --> 05:22:50.266
Rusticus was the advisor of Antoninus after he became emperor. Young men who are destined

05:22:50.266 --> 05:22:56.066
for high places are not often fortunate in those who are about them, their companions and teachers.

05:22:56.556 --> 05:23:01.806
I do not know any example of a young prince having had an education which can be compared

05:23:01.806 --> 05:23:07.046
with that of Marcus Antoninus. Such a body of teachers, distinguished by their requirements

05:23:07.046 --> 05:23:13.066
and their character, will hardly be collected again, and as to the pupil, we have not had one

05:23:13.066 --> 05:23:23.466
like him since. Hadrian died in July AD 138 and was succeeded by Antoninus Pius. Marcus Antoninus

05:23:23.466 --> 05:23:30.886
married Faustina, his cousin, the daughter of Pius, probably about AD 146, for he had a daughter

05:23:30.886 --> 05:23:38.246
born in 147. He received from his adoptive father the title of Caesar and was associated with him

05:23:38.246 --> 05:23:43.426
in the administration of the state. The father and the adopted son lived together in perfect

05:23:43.426 --> 05:23:50.426
friendship and confidence. Antoninus was a dutiful son and the emperor Pius loved and esteemed him.

05:23:52.166 --> 05:24:00.146
Antoninus Pius died in March AD 161. The senate, it is said, urged Marcus Antoninus to take the

05:24:00.146 --> 05:24:05.946
sole administration of the empire, but he associated with himself the other adopted son of Pius,

05:24:06.346 --> 05:24:12.826
Lucius Sianius Commodus, who is generally called Lucius Verus. Thus Rome, for the first time,

05:24:12.986 --> 05:24:19.766
had two emperors. Verus was an indolent man of pleasure and unworthy of his station. Antoninus,

05:24:19.766 --> 05:24:24.826
however, bore with him and it is said that Verus had enough sense to pay his colleague the respect

05:24:24.826 --> 05:24:30.886
due to his character. A virtuous emperor and a loose partner lived together in peace and their

05:24:30.886 --> 05:24:37.766
alliance was strengthened by Antoninus giving to Verus for wife his daughter Lucilla. The reign of

05:24:37.766 --> 05:24:43.466
Antoninus was first troubled by a Parthian war in which Verus was sent to command, but he did

05:24:43.466 --> 05:24:48.786
nothing and the success that was obtained by the Romans in Armenia and on the Euphrates and Tigris

05:24:48.786 --> 05:24:56.926
was due to his generals. This Parthian war ended in AD 165. Aurelius and Verus had a triumph,

05:24:57.246 --> 05:25:03.306
AD 166, for the victories in the east. A pestilence followed which carried off great

05:25:03.306 --> 05:25:09.926
numbers in Rome and Italy and spread to the west of Europe. The north of Italy was also threatened

05:25:09.926 --> 05:25:15.206
by the rude people beyond the Alps from the borders of Gallia to the eastern side of the

05:25:15.206 --> 05:25:21.426
Adriatic. These barbarians attempted a break into Italy as the Germanic nations had attempted near

05:25:21.426 --> 05:25:27.406
300 years before and the rest of the life of Antoninus, with some intervals, was employed

05:25:27.406 --> 05:25:34.266
in driving back the invaders. In 169, Verus suddenly died and Antoninus administered the

05:25:34.266 --> 05:25:41.366
state alone. During the German wars, Antoninus resided for three years on the Danube at Carnuntum.

05:25:41.366 --> 05:25:46.486
The Marco Mani were driven out of Pannonia and almost destroyed in their retreat across the

05:25:46.486 --> 05:25:54.586
Danube and in AD 174 the emperor gained a great victory over the Quadi. In AD 175,

05:25:54.866 --> 05:26:00.446
Avidius Cassius, a brave and skillful Roman commander who was at the head of the troops in Asia,

05:26:01.286 --> 05:26:07.266
revolted and declared himself Augustus, but Cassius was assassinated by some of his officers

05:26:07.266 --> 05:26:13.146
and so the rebellion came to an end. Antoninus showed his humanity by his treatment of the

05:26:13.146 --> 05:26:19.066
family and the partisans of Cassius and his letter to the senate in which he recommends mercy is

05:26:19.066 --> 05:26:26.586
extant. Antoninus set out for the east on hearing of Cassius's revolt. Though he appears to have

05:26:26.586 --> 05:26:32.786
returned to Rome in AD 174, he went back to prosecute the war against the Germans and it

05:26:32.786 --> 05:26:39.346
probable that he marched direct to the east from the German war. His wife Faustina who accompanied

05:26:39.346 --> 05:26:44.946
him into Asia died suddenly at the foot of the Taurus to the great grief of her husband.

05:26:46.186 --> 05:26:52.286
Cappatilinus who has written the life of Antoninus and also Dion Cassius accused the empress of

05:26:52.286 --> 05:26:58.186
scandalous infidelity to her husband and of abominable lewdness, but Cappatilinus says

05:26:58.186 --> 05:27:04.706
Antoninus either knew it not or pretended not to know it. Nothing is so common as such malicious

05:27:04.706 --> 05:27:11.426
reports in all ages and the history of imperial Rome is full of them. Antoninus loved his wife

05:27:11.426 --> 05:27:17.966
and he says that she was obedient, affectionate, and simple. The same scandal had been spread about

05:27:17.966 --> 05:27:24.446
Faustina's mother, the wife of Antoninus Pius, and yet he too was perfectly satisfied with his wife.

05:27:25.446 --> 05:27:31.126
Antoninus Pius says after her death in a letter to Fronto that he would rather have lived in exile

05:27:31.126 --> 05:27:37.466
with his wife than in his palace at Rome without her. There are not many men who would give their

05:27:37.466 --> 05:27:43.466
wives a better character than these two emperors. Cappatilinus wrote in the time of Diocletian.

05:27:44.026 --> 05:27:50.226
He may have intended to tell the truth, but he is a poor feeble biographer. Dion Cassius,

05:27:50.226 --> 05:27:56.466
the most malignant of historians, always reports and perhaps he believed any scandal against anybody.

05:27:58.686 --> 05:28:04.486
Antoninus continued his journey to Syria and Egypt and on his return to Italy through Athens

05:28:04.486 --> 05:28:11.106
he was initiated into the Eleusinian Mysteries. It was the practice of the emperor to conform to

05:28:11.106 --> 05:28:15.866
the established rites of the age and to perform religious ceremonies with due solemnity.

05:28:16.506 --> 05:28:21.006
We cannot conclude from this that he was a superstitious man, though we might perhaps

05:28:21.006 --> 05:28:27.746
do so if his book did not show that he was not. But this is only one among many instances that

05:28:27.746 --> 05:28:33.646
a ruler's public acts do not always prove his real opinions. A prudent governor will not roughly

05:28:33.646 --> 05:28:38.406
oppose even the superstitions of his people, and though he may wish that they were wiser,

05:28:38.746 --> 05:28:42.106
he will know that he cannot make them so by offending their prejudices.

05:28:43.446 --> 05:28:49.066
Antoninus and his son Commodus entered Rome in triumph, perhaps for some German victories,

05:28:49.666 --> 05:28:56.406
on the 23rd of December AD 176. In the following year Commodus was associated with his father in

05:28:56.406 --> 05:29:04.506
the empire and took the name of Augustus. This year AD 177 is memorable in ecclesiastical history.

05:29:05.186 --> 05:29:10.046
Attalus and others were put to death at Lyon for their adherence to the Christian religion.

05:29:10.846 --> 05:29:16.126
The evidence of this persecution is a letter preserved by Eusebius. The letter is from the

05:29:16.126 --> 05:29:21.766
Christians of Vienna and Lugdunum in Gallia, Vienna and Lyon, to their Christian brethren

05:29:21.766 --> 05:29:28.166
in Asia and Phrygia, and it is preserved perhaps nearly entire. It contains a very

05:29:28.166 --> 05:29:33.046
particular description of the tortures inflicted on the Christians in Gallia, and it states that

05:29:33.046 --> 05:29:38.486
while the persecution was going on, Attalus, a Christian and a Roman citizen, was loudly

05:29:38.486 --> 05:29:44.006
demanded by the populace and brought into the amphitheater, but the governor ordered him to be

05:29:44.006 --> 05:29:48.766
reserved with the rest who were in prison, until he had received instructions from the emperor.

05:29:49.766 --> 05:29:53.306
Many had been tortured before the governor thought of applying to Antoninus.

05:29:53.926 --> 05:29:58.366
The imperial rescript says the letter was that the Christians should be punished,

05:29:58.766 --> 05:30:08.466
but if they would deny their faith they must be released. On this the work began again. The

05:30:09.346 --> 05:30:14.686
amphitheater. Some modern writers in ecclesiastical history, when they use this letter,

05:30:15.106 --> 05:30:17.946
say nothing of the wonderful stories of the martyr's sufferings.

05:30:18.786 --> 05:30:25.686
Sanctus, as the letter says, was burnt with plates of hot iron, till his body was one sore and he had

05:30:25.686 --> 05:30:31.366
lost all human form, but on being put to the rack he recovered his former appearance under the

05:30:31.366 --> 05:30:37.206
torture, which was thus a cure instead of a punishment. He was afterwards torn by beasts

05:30:37.206 --> 05:30:41.326
and placed on an iron chair and roasted. He died at last.

05:30:42.346 --> 05:30:47.266
The letter is one piece of evidence. The writer, whoever he was that wrote in the name of the

05:30:47.266 --> 05:30:52.766
Gallic Christians, is our evidence both for the ordinary and the extraordinary circumstances of

05:30:52.766 --> 05:30:59.166
the story, and we cannot accept his evidence for one part and reject the other. We often receive

05:30:59.166 --> 05:31:04.106
small evidence as a proof of a thing which we believe to be within the limits of probability

05:31:04.106 --> 05:31:10.466
or possibility, and we reject exactly the same evidence when the thing to which it refers appears

05:31:10.466 --> 05:31:17.186
very improbable or impossible. But this is a false method of inquiry, though it is followed by some

05:31:17.186 --> 05:31:21.806
modern writers, who select what they like from a story and reject the rest of the evidence,

05:31:22.346 --> 05:31:27.666
or if they do not reject it they dishonestly suppress it. A man can only act consistently

05:31:27.666 --> 05:31:32.486
by accepting all this letter or rejecting it all, and we cannot blame him for either.

05:31:33.046 --> 05:31:37.606
But he who rejects it may still admit that such a letter may be founded on real facts,

05:31:38.146 --> 05:31:42.626
and he would make this admission as the most probable way of accounting for the existence

05:31:42.626 --> 05:31:48.466
of the letter. But if, as he would suppose, the writer has stated some things falsely,

05:31:48.746 --> 05:31:51.346
he cannot tell what part of his story is worthy of credit.

05:31:52.506 --> 05:31:57.366
The war on the northern frontier appears to have been uninterrupted during the visit of Antoninus

05:31:57.366 --> 05:32:02.506
to the east, and on his return the emperor again left Rome to oppose the barbarians.

05:32:03.226 --> 05:32:09.426
The Germanic people were defeated in a great battle AD 179. During this campaign the emperor

05:32:09.426 --> 05:32:15.966
was seized with some contagious malady, of which he died in the camp at Sirmium, Mitrovitz, on the

05:32:15.966 --> 05:32:23.186
Sava in Lower Pannonia, but at Vindabena, Vienna, according to other authorities, on the 17th March

05:32:23.186 --> 05:32:31.146
AD 180, in the 59th year of his age. His son Commodus was with him. The body or the ashes,

05:32:31.246 --> 05:32:35.666
probably of the emperor, were carried to Rome, and he received the honor of deification.

05:32:36.566 --> 05:32:41.086
Those who could afford it had his statue or bust, and when Cuppatilinus wrote,

05:32:41.426 --> 05:32:46.786
many people still had statues of Antoninus among the Deipinates, or household deities.

05:32:47.446 --> 05:32:52.166
He was in a manner made a saint. Commodus erected to the memory of his father the

05:32:52.166 --> 05:32:58.486
Antonine Column, which is now in the Piazza Colonna at Rome. The bas reliefs, which are

05:32:58.486 --> 05:33:03.106
placed in a spiral line around the shaft, commemorate the victories of Antoninus over

05:33:03.106 --> 05:33:08.226
the Marcomanni and the Quatti, and the miraculous shower of rain which refreshed the Roman soldiers

05:33:08.226 --> 05:33:13.926
and discomfited their enemies. The statue of Antoninus was placed on the capital of the Column,

05:33:14.246 --> 05:33:19.206
but it was removed at some time unknown, and a bronze statue of Saint Paul was put in the

05:33:19.206 --> 05:33:25.866
place of Pope Sixtus V. The historical evidence for the times of Antoninus is very defective,

05:33:26.306 --> 05:33:31.666
and some of that which remains is not credible. The most curious is the story about the miracle

05:33:31.666 --> 05:33:38.966
which happened in AD 174 during the war with the Quatti. The Roman army was in danger of perishing

05:33:38.966 --> 05:33:45.366
by thirst, but a sudden storm drenched them with rain, while it discharged fire and hail on their

05:33:45.366 --> 05:33:50.786
enemies, and the Romans gained a great victory. All the authorities which speak of the battle

05:33:50.786 --> 05:33:56.446
speak also of the miracle. The Gentile writers assigned it to their gods, and the Christians

05:33:56.446 --> 05:34:01.126
to the intercession of the Christian legion and the emperor's army. To confirm the Christian

05:34:01.126 --> 05:34:06.646
statement, it is added that the emperor gave the title of thundering to this legion, but Dossier

05:34:06.646 --> 05:34:11.286
and others who maintain the Christian report of the miracle admit that this title of thundering

05:34:11.286 --> 05:34:15.866
or lightning was not given to this legion because the Quatti were struck with lightning,

05:34:16.306 --> 05:34:20.566
but because there was a figure of lightning on their shields, and that this title of the

05:34:20.566 --> 05:34:26.246
legion existed in the time of Augustus. Scaliger also had observed that the legion was called

05:34:26.246 --> 05:34:32.166
thundering before the reign of Antoninus. We can learn this from Dion Cassius, who enumerates all

05:34:32.166 --> 05:34:38.026
the legions of Augustus's time. The name thundering or lightning also occurs on an inscription of the

05:34:38.026 --> 05:34:45.086
Trajan, which was found at Trieste. Eusebius, when he relates the miracle, quotes Apollinarius,

05:34:45.466 --> 05:34:51.086
bishop of Hierapolis, as authority for this name being given to the legion Melitini by the emperor

05:34:51.086 --> 05:34:56.306
in consequence of the success which he had obtained through their prayers, from which we may estimate

05:34:56.306 --> 05:35:01.886
the value of Apollinarius's testimony. Eusebius does not say in what book of Apollinarius the

05:35:01.886 --> 05:35:07.306
statement occurs. Dion says that the thundering legion was stationed in Cappadocia in the time

05:35:07.306 --> 05:35:12.586
of Augustus. Velasius also observes that in the notitia of the Imperium Romanum,

05:35:13.066 --> 05:35:17.386
there is mentioned under the commander of Armenia the prefectura of the 12th legion

05:35:17.386 --> 05:35:22.746
named thundering Melitini, and this position in Armenia will agree with what Dion says of

05:35:22.746 --> 05:35:28.646
its position in Cappadocia. Accordingly, Velasius concludes that Melitini was not the name of the

05:35:28.646 --> 05:35:34.986
legion, but of the town in which it was stationed. Melitini was also the name of the district in which

05:35:34.986 --> 05:35:40.066
this town was situated. The legions did not, he says, take their name from the place where they

05:35:40.066 --> 05:35:45.626
were on duty, but from the country in which they were raised, and therefore what Eusebius says about

05:35:45.626 --> 05:35:51.346
the Melitini does not seem probable to him. Yet Velasius, on the authority of Apollinarius and

05:35:51.346 --> 05:35:55.606
Tertullian, believed that the miracle was worked through the prayers of the Christian soldiers and

05:35:55.606 --> 05:36:01.126
the emperor's army. Rufinus does not give the name of Melitini to this legion, says Velasius,

05:36:01.126 --> 05:36:06.526
and probably he purposely omitted it, because he knew that Melitini was the name of a town in

05:36:06.526 --> 05:36:13.406
Armenia Minor, where the legion was stationed in his time. The emperor, it is said, made a report

05:36:13.406 --> 05:36:19.126
of his victory to the senate, which we may believe, for such was the practice. But we do not know what

05:36:19.126 --> 05:36:24.286
he said in his letter, for it is not extant. Dossier assumes that the emperor's letter was

05:36:24.286 --> 05:36:30.026
purposely destroyed by the senate, or the enemies of Christianity, that so honorable a testimony to

05:36:30.026 --> 05:36:36.006
Christians and their religion might not be perpetuated. The critic has, however, not seen

05:36:36.006 --> 05:36:41.146
that he contradicts when he tells us purported the letter, for he says that it was destroyed,

05:36:41.606 --> 05:36:47.066
and even Eusebius could not find it. But there does exist a letter in Greek addressed by Antoninus

05:36:47.066 --> 05:36:52.786
to the Roman people and the sacred senate after this memorable victory. It is sometimes printed

05:36:52.786 --> 05:36:58.406
after Justin's first apology, but is totally unconnected with the apologies. This letter is

05:36:58.406 --> 05:37:02.926
one of the most stupid forgeries of the many which exist, and it cannot be possibly founded

05:37:02.926 --> 05:37:07.806
even on the genuine report of Antoninus to the senate. If it were genuine, it would free the

05:37:07.806 --> 05:37:12.606
emperor from the charge of persecuting men because they were Christians. For he says in this false

05:37:12.606 --> 05:37:17.966
letter that if a man accused another only of being a Christian, and the accused confess and there is

05:37:17.966 --> 05:37:23.646
nothing else against him, he must be set free. With this monstrous addition, made by a man

05:37:23.646 --> 05:37:31.226
inconceivably ignorant, that the informer must be burnt alive. During the time of Antoninus Pius

05:37:31.226 --> 05:37:37.066
and Marcus Antoninus, there appeared the first apology of Justinus, and under Marcus Antoninus

05:37:37.066 --> 05:37:41.946
the oration of Tatian against the Greeks, which was a fierce attack on the established religions.

05:37:42.786 --> 05:37:48.586
The address of Athenagoras to Marcus Antoninus on behalf of the Christians and the apology of

05:37:48.586 --> 05:37:53.906
Plato, Bishop of Sardis, also addressed to the emperor and that of Apollinarius.

05:37:54.806 --> 05:38:00.726
The first apology of Justinus is addressed to Titus Antoninus Pius and his two adopted sons,

05:38:00.966 --> 05:38:05.276
Marcus Antoninus and Lucius Verus, but we do not know whether they read it.

05:38:06.026 --> 05:38:11.706
Footnote, Aureus says that Justinus the philosopher presented to Antoninus Pius his

05:38:11.706 --> 05:38:15.806
work in defense of the Christian religion, and made him merciful to the Christians.

05:38:16.366 --> 05:38:17.426
End footnote.

05:38:18.426 --> 05:38:22.346
The second apology of Justinus is entitled To the Roman Senate,

05:38:22.866 --> 05:38:29.206
but this superscription is from some copyist. In the first chapter Justinus addresses the Romans.

05:38:29.786 --> 05:38:34.706
In the second chapter he speaks of an affair that had recently happened in the time of Marcus

05:38:34.706 --> 05:38:44.026
Antoninus and Lucius Verus as it seems, and he also directly addresses the emperor, saying of

05:38:44.026 --> 05:38:46.566
emperor, and thou didst grant the petition.

05:38:48.026 --> 05:38:53.346
In other passages the writer addresses the two emperors, from which we must conclude that the

05:38:53.346 --> 05:38:58.466
apology was directed to them. Eusebius states that the second apology was addressed to the

05:38:58.466 --> 05:39:04.686
successor of Antoninus Pius, and he names him Antoninus Verus, meaning Marcus Antoninus.

05:39:05.286 --> 05:39:11.306
In one passage of the second apology, Justinus, or the writer whoever he may be, says that even

05:39:11.306 --> 05:39:15.826
men who followed the Stoic doctrines when they ordered their lives according to ethical reason

05:39:15.826 --> 05:39:22.546
were hated and murdered, such as Heraclitus, Musonius in his own times, and others. For all

05:39:22.546 --> 05:39:27.646
those who in any way labored to live according to reason and avoided wickedness were always hated,

05:39:28.106 --> 05:39:30.366
and this was the effect of the work of demons.

05:39:31.926 --> 05:39:40.966
Justinus himself is said to have been put to death at Rome because he refused to sacrifice to the

05:39:40.966 --> 05:39:46.886
states, nor in the time of Antoninus Pius, if the second apology was written in the time of Marcus

05:39:46.886 --> 05:39:52.646
Antoninus, and there was evidence that this event took place under Marcus Antoninus and Lucius Verus,

05:39:52.846 --> 05:39:54.906
when Rusticus was prefect of the city.

05:39:56.286 --> 05:40:01.806
The persecution in which Polycarp suffered at Smyrna belongs to the time of Marcus Antoninus.

05:40:02.246 --> 05:40:10.946
The evidence for it is the letter of the church of Smyrna to the churches of Philomelium and the

05:40:10.946 --> 05:40:14.306
But the critics do not agree about the time of Polycarp's death,

05:40:14.706 --> 05:40:17.506
differing in the two extremes to the amount of 12 years.

05:40:18.326 --> 05:40:23.246
The circumstances of Polycarp's martyrdom were accompanied by miracles, one of which Eusebius

05:40:23.246 --> 05:40:28.446
has omitted, but it appears in the oldest Latin version of the letter, which Usher published,

05:40:28.726 --> 05:40:32.386
and it is supposed that this version was made not long after the time of Eusebius.

05:40:33.066 --> 05:40:36.766
The notice at the end of the letter states that it was transcribed by Caius,

05:40:36.766 --> 05:40:42.946
from the copy of Irenaeus, the disciple of Polycarp, then transcribed by Socrates at Corinth,

05:40:44.266 --> 05:40:47.966
after which I, Pioneus, again wrote it out from the copy above mentioned,

05:40:48.406 --> 05:40:53.086
having searched it out by the revelation of Polycarp, who directed it to me, etc.

05:40:54.926 --> 05:40:58.766
The story of Polycarp's martyrdom is embellished with miraculous circumstances

05:40:58.766 --> 05:41:03.426
which some modern writers on ecclesiastical history take the liberty of omitting.

05:41:04.306 --> 05:41:04.906
Footnote.

05:41:05.166 --> 05:41:10.226
Conyers Middleton, An Inquiry into the Miraculous Powers, etc. page 126.

05:41:11.166 --> 05:41:16.106
Middleton says that Eusebius omitted to mention the dove, which flew out of Polycarp's body,

05:41:16.546 --> 05:41:19.206
and Dodwell and Archbishop Wake have done the same.

05:41:19.746 --> 05:41:24.746
Wake says, I am so little a friend to such miracles that I thought it better with Eusebius

05:41:24.746 --> 05:41:29.466
to omit that circumstance than to mention it from Bishop Usher's manuscript.

05:41:30.826 --> 05:41:36.106
Which manuscript, however, says Middleton, he afterwards declares to be so well attested

05:41:36.106 --> 05:41:39.126
that we need not any further assurance of the truth of it.

05:41:39.766 --> 05:41:40.646
End footnote.

05:41:42.066 --> 05:41:46.586
In order to form a proper notion of the condition of the Christians under Marcus Antoninus,

05:41:46.926 --> 05:41:48.786
we must go back to Trajan's time.

05:41:49.366 --> 05:41:54.026
When the younger Pliny was governor of Bithynia, the Christians were numerous in those parts,

05:41:54.386 --> 05:41:56.966
and the worshippers of the old religion were falling off.

05:41:56.966 --> 05:42:00.326
The temples were deserted, the festivals neglected,

05:42:00.806 --> 05:42:03.206
and there were no purchasers of victims for sacrifice.

05:42:04.166 --> 05:42:06.846
Those who were interested in the maintenance of the old religion

05:42:06.846 --> 05:42:09.186
thus found that their prophets were in danger.

05:42:10.066 --> 05:42:13.906
Christians of both sexes and of all ages were brought before the governor,

05:42:14.246 --> 05:42:15.586
who did not know what to do with them.

05:42:16.106 --> 05:42:18.346
He could come to know their conclusion in this,

05:42:18.646 --> 05:42:23.346
that those who confess to be Christians and persevered in their religion ought to be punished,

05:42:23.766 --> 05:42:26.366
if for nothing else for their invincible obstinacy.

05:42:26.966 --> 05:42:29.706
He found no crimes proved against the Christians,

05:42:30.166 --> 05:42:34.166
and he could only characterize their religion as a depraved and extravagant superstition,

05:42:34.546 --> 05:42:38.026
which might be stopped if the people are allowed the opportunity of recanting.

05:42:38.746 --> 05:42:40.826
Pliny wrote this in a letter to Trajan.

05:42:41.166 --> 05:42:41.706
Footnote.

05:42:42.006 --> 05:42:46.126
The Martyrium Ignatii, first published in Latin by Archbishop Usher,

05:42:46.566 --> 05:42:49.786
is the chief evidence for the circumstances of Ignatius's death.

05:42:50.426 --> 05:42:51.146
End footnote.

05:42:52.246 --> 05:42:55.846
In the time of Hadrian, it was no longer possible for the Roman government

05:42:55.846 --> 05:43:00.766
to overlook the great increase of the Christians and the hostility of the common sort to them.

05:43:01.526 --> 05:43:04.366
If the governors in the provinces were willing to let them alone,

05:43:04.706 --> 05:43:07.446
they could not resist the fanaticism of the heathen community,

05:43:07.886 --> 05:43:10.126
who looked on the Christians as atheists.

05:43:10.786 --> 05:43:13.586
The Jews, too, who were settled all over the Roman Empire,

05:43:13.986 --> 05:43:17.026
were as hostile to the Christians as the Gentiles were.

05:43:17.686 --> 05:43:18.166
Footnote.

05:43:18.366 --> 05:43:20.846
We have the evidence of Justinus to this effect.

05:43:21.626 --> 05:43:25.506
The Christians are attacked by the Jews as if they were men of a different race,

05:43:25.506 --> 05:43:27.486
and are persecuted by the Greeks,

05:43:28.026 --> 05:43:30.706
and those who hate them cannot give the reason of their enmity.

05:43:32.226 --> 05:43:33.266
End footnote.

05:43:34.306 --> 05:43:36.986
With the time of Hadrian began the Christian apologies,

05:43:37.566 --> 05:43:41.086
which show plainly what the popular feeling towards the Christians then was.

05:43:41.926 --> 05:43:46.366
A re-script of Hadrian to Manutius Fundanus, the proconsul of Asia,

05:43:46.766 --> 05:43:49.006
which stands at the end of Justin's first apology,

05:43:49.646 --> 05:43:52.346
instructs the governor that innocent people must not be troubled,

05:43:52.346 --> 05:43:55.706
and false accusers must not be allowed to extort money from them.

05:43:56.366 --> 05:43:59.266
The charges against the Christians must be made in due form,

05:43:59.726 --> 05:44:02.206
and no attention must be paid to popular clamors.

05:44:02.666 --> 05:44:06.226
When Christians were regularly prosecuted and convicted of illegal acts,

05:44:06.626 --> 05:44:08.966
they must be punished according to their deserts,

05:44:09.146 --> 05:44:11.286
and false accusers also must be punished.

05:44:11.926 --> 05:44:12.426
Footnote.

05:44:12.826 --> 05:44:17.966
And in Eusebius, Erosius says that Hadrian sent this re-script to Manutius Fundanus,

05:44:18.186 --> 05:44:19.226
proconsul of Asia,

05:44:19.226 --> 05:44:23.746
after being instructed in books written on the Christian religion by Quadratus,

05:44:24.186 --> 05:44:25.526
a disciple of the apostles,

05:44:26.106 --> 05:44:29.386
and Aristides, an Athenian, an honest and wise man,

05:44:29.926 --> 05:44:31.326
and Serenus Grineus.

05:44:31.926 --> 05:44:34.106
In the Greek text of Hadrian's re-script,

05:44:34.486 --> 05:44:38.946
there is mentioned Serenius Grineanus, the predecessor of Manutius Fundanus,

05:44:39.386 --> 05:44:40.706
in the government of Asia.

05:44:41.306 --> 05:44:45.466
This re-script of Hadrian has clearly been added to the apology by some editor.

05:44:46.126 --> 05:44:46.866
End footnote.

05:44:48.146 --> 05:44:51.706
Antonius Pius is said to have published re-scripts to the same effect.

05:44:52.226 --> 05:44:56.026
The terms of Hadrian's re-script seem very favorable to the Christians,

05:44:56.626 --> 05:44:58.426
but if we understand it in this sense,

05:44:58.726 --> 05:45:01.566
that they were only to be punished like other people for illegal acts,

05:45:02.026 --> 05:45:03.146
it would have no meaning,

05:45:03.606 --> 05:45:06.206
for that could have been done without asking the emperor's advice.

05:45:06.746 --> 05:45:09.926
The real purpose of the re-script is that Christians must be punished

05:45:09.926 --> 05:45:11.506
if they persisted in their belief,

05:45:11.966 --> 05:45:15.466
and would not prove their renunciation of it by acknowledging the heathen religion.

05:45:16.006 --> 05:45:17.686
This was Trajan's rule,

05:45:18.086 --> 05:45:20.526
and we have no reason for supposing that Hadrian

05:45:20.526 --> 05:45:22.946
granted more to the Christians than Trajan did.

05:45:23.586 --> 05:45:26.706
There is also printed at the end of Justin's first apology,

05:45:27.226 --> 05:45:30.866
a re-script of Antoninus Pius to the commune of Asia,

05:45:31.366 --> 05:45:33.106
and it is also in Eusebius.

05:45:33.506 --> 05:45:37.046
The date of the re-script is the third consulship of Antoninus Pius.

05:45:37.506 --> 05:45:40.266
The re-script declares that the Christians, for they are meant,

05:45:40.726 --> 05:45:43.246
though the name Christians does not occur in the re-script,

05:45:43.246 --> 05:45:47.446
were not to be disturbed unless they were attempting something against the Roman rule,

05:45:47.846 --> 05:45:50.486
and no man was to be punished simply for being a Christian.

05:45:51.326 --> 05:45:53.006
But this re-script is spurious.

05:45:53.546 --> 05:45:56.406
Any man moderately acquainted with Roman history

05:45:56.406 --> 05:46:00.766
will see by the style and tenor that it is a clumsy forgery.

05:46:02.466 --> 05:46:04.246
In the time of Marcus Antoninus,

05:46:04.366 --> 05:46:07.666
the opposition between the old and the new belief was still stronger,

05:46:08.186 --> 05:46:11.266
and the adherents of the heathen religion urged those in authority

05:46:11.266 --> 05:46:15.306
to a more regular resistance to the invasions of the Christian faith.

05:46:16.286 --> 05:46:18.966
Melito, in his apology to Marcus Antoninus,

05:46:19.366 --> 05:46:23.266
represents the Christians of Asia as persecuted under new imperial orders.

05:46:23.946 --> 05:46:28.166
Shameless informers, he says, men who were greedy after the property of others,

05:46:28.786 --> 05:46:32.146
used these orders as a means of robbing those who were doing no harm.

05:46:32.946 --> 05:46:36.386
He doubts if a just emperor could have ordered anything so unjust,

05:46:36.926 --> 05:46:39.366
and if the last order was really not from the emperor,

05:46:39.366 --> 05:46:42.406
the Christians entreat him not to give them up to their enemies.

05:46:43.286 --> 05:46:46.706
We conclude from this that there were at least imperial re-scripts

05:46:46.706 --> 05:46:51.806
or constitutions of Marcus Antoninus which were made the foundations of these persecutions.

05:46:52.406 --> 05:46:55.446
The fact of being a Christian was now a crime and punished

05:46:55.446 --> 05:46:57.746
unless the accused denied their religion.

05:46:58.566 --> 05:47:04.346
Then come the persecutions at Smyrna, which some modern critics place in AD 167,

05:47:04.566 --> 05:47:06.786
ten years before the persecution of Lyon.

05:47:06.786 --> 05:47:11.366
The governors of the provinces under Marcus Antoninus might have found enough

05:47:11.366 --> 05:47:14.966
even in Trajan's re-script to warrant them in punishing Christians,

05:47:15.586 --> 05:47:20.166
and the fanaticism of the people would drive them to persecution even if they were unwilling.

05:47:21.146 --> 05:47:24.826
But besides the fact of the Christians rejecting all the heathen ceremonies,

05:47:25.426 --> 05:47:29.646
we must not forget that they plainly maintained that all the heathen religions were false.

05:47:30.266 --> 05:47:33.086
The Christians thus declared war against the heathen rights,

05:47:33.086 --> 05:47:38.366
and it is hardly necessary to observe that this was a declaration of hostility against

05:47:38.366 --> 05:47:42.886
the Roman government, which tolerated all the various forms of superstition that existed in

05:47:42.886 --> 05:47:48.166
the empire and could not consistently tolerate another religion, which declared that all the

05:47:48.166 --> 05:47:53.086
rest were false, and all the splendid ceremonies of the empire only a worship of devils.

05:47:54.146 --> 05:47:59.746
If we had a true ecclesiastical history, we should know how the Roman empires attempted to

05:47:59.746 --> 05:48:03.866
the new religion, how they enforced their principle of finally punishing Christians,

05:48:04.326 --> 05:48:08.726
simply as Christians, which Justin in his apology affirms that they did,

05:48:09.026 --> 05:48:14.586
and I have no doubt that he tells the truth. How far popular clamor and riots went in this matter,

05:48:15.006 --> 05:48:19.166
and how far many fanatical and ignorant Christians, for there were many such,

05:48:19.586 --> 05:48:23.126
contributed to excite the fanaticism on the other side and to

05:48:23.126 --> 05:48:25.786
embedder the quarrel between the Roman government and the new religion.

05:48:26.566 --> 05:48:33.006
Our extant ecclesiastical histories are manifestly falsified, and what truth they contain is grossly

05:48:33.006 --> 05:48:38.926
exaggerated, but the fact is certain that in the time of Marcus Antoninus the heathen populations

05:48:38.926 --> 05:48:44.726
were an open hostility to the Christians, and that under Antoninus' rule men were put to death

05:48:44.726 --> 05:48:50.426
because they were Christians. Eusebius in the preface to his fifth book remarks that in the

05:48:50.426 --> 05:48:55.326
seventeenth year of Antoninus' reign in some parts of the world the persecution of the Christians

05:48:55.326 --> 05:49:01.266
became more violent and that it proceeded from the populace in the cities, and he adds in his

05:49:01.266 --> 05:49:07.306
usual style of exaggeration that we may infer from what took place in a single nation that myriads

05:49:07.306 --> 05:49:12.266
of martyrs were made in the habitable earth. The nation which he alludes to is Gallia,

05:49:12.626 --> 05:49:16.426
and he then proceeds to give the letter to the churches of Vienna and Lugdunum.

05:49:16.826 --> 05:49:25.166
It is probable that he has assigned the true cause of the persecutions, the fanaticism of

05:49:25.166 --> 05:49:30.546
with these disturbances. How far Marcus was cognizant of these cruel proceedings we do not

05:49:30.546 --> 05:49:35.786
know, for the historical records of his reign are very defective. He did not make the rule

05:49:35.786 --> 05:49:40.226
against the Christians, for Trajan did that, and if we admit that he would have been willing to let

05:49:40.226 --> 05:49:45.666
the Christians alone we cannot affirm that he was in his power, for it would be a great mistake to

05:49:45.666 --> 05:49:51.766
suppose that Antoninus had the unlimited authority which some modern sovereigns have had. His power

05:49:51.766 --> 05:49:57.106
was limited by certain constitutional forms, by the senate, and by the precedence of his predecessors.

05:49:58.006 --> 05:50:02.326
We cannot admit that such a man was an active persecutor, for there is no evidence that he

05:50:02.326 --> 05:50:07.266
was, though it is certain that he had no good opinion of the Christians, as appears from his

05:50:07.266 --> 05:50:14.006
own words. Footnote. Except that of Erosius, who says that during the Parthian War there were

05:50:14.006 --> 05:50:18.546
grievous persecutions of the Christians in Asia and Gallia under the orders of Marcus,

05:50:19.126 --> 05:50:26.486
prakepto aeius, and, quote, many were crowned with the martyrdom of saints, unquote. End footnote.

05:50:27.586 --> 05:50:32.866
But he knew nothing of them except their hostility to the Roman religion, and he probably thought

05:50:32.866 --> 05:50:37.506
that they were dangerous to the state, notwithstanding the professions false or true of some of the

05:50:37.506 --> 05:50:44.146
apologists. So much I have said, because it would be unfair not to state all that can be urged

05:50:44.146 --> 05:50:49.906
against a man whom his contemporaries in subsequent ages venerated as a model of virtue

05:50:49.906 --> 05:50:56.106
and benevolence. If I admitted the genuineness of some documents, he would be altogether clear

05:50:56.106 --> 05:51:01.826
from the charge of even allowing any persecutions. But as I seek the truth and am sure that they are

05:51:01.826 --> 05:51:09.166
false, I leave him to bear whatever blame is his due. Footnote. Dr. F.C. Bower, in his work entitled,

05:51:15.406 --> 05:51:18.826
etc., has examined this question with great good sense and fairness,

05:51:19.266 --> 05:51:23.326
and I believe he has stated the truth as near as our authorities enable us to reach it.

05:51:24.286 --> 05:51:29.926
End footnote. I add that it is quite certain that Antoninus did not derive any of his ethical

05:51:29.926 --> 05:51:44.126
principles from a religion of which he knew nothing. Footnote. In the digest there is the

05:51:57.346 --> 05:52:09.766
In the first book he speaks of himself, his family, and his teachers, and in other books

05:52:09.766 --> 05:52:16.846
himself. Suedas notices the work of Antoninus in 12 books, which he names the conduct of his own

05:52:16.846 --> 05:52:22.226
life, and he cites the book under several words in his dictionary, giving the emperor's name,

05:52:22.286 --> 05:52:27.526
but not the title of the work. There are also passages cited by Suedas from Antoninus

05:52:27.526 --> 05:52:32.446
without mention of the emperor's name. The true title of the work is unknown.

05:52:33.526 --> 05:52:38.306
Zylander, who published the first edition of this book with a Latin version, used a manuscript

05:52:38.306 --> 05:52:42.626
which contained the 12 books, but it is not known where the manuscript is now.

05:52:43.526 --> 05:52:49.546
The only other complete manuscript which is known to exist is in the Vatican Library, but it has

05:52:49.546 --> 05:52:54.346
no titles and no inscriptions of the several books. The 11th only has the inscription

05:52:54.346 --> 05:53:00.406
marked with an asterisk. The other Vatican manuscripts in the 3 Florentine contain only

05:53:00.406 --> 05:53:05.466
excerpts from the emperor's book. All the titles of the excerpts nearly agree with that which

05:53:05.466 --> 05:53:11.726
Zylander prefixed to his edition. This title has been used by all subsequent editors. We cannot

05:53:11.726 --> 05:53:17.306
tell whether Antoninus divided his work into books or somebody else did it. If the inscriptions at

05:53:17.306 --> 05:53:21.546
the end of the first and second books are genuine, he may have made the division himself.

05:53:22.366 --> 05:53:27.006
It is plain that the emperor wrote down his thoughts or reflections as the occasions arose,

05:53:27.426 --> 05:53:35.446
and since they were intended for his own use, it is no improbable conjecture that he left a

05:53:35.446 --> 05:53:39.426
manuscript, for it is not likely that so diligent a man would use the labor of a

05:53:39.426 --> 05:53:44.486
transcriber for such a purpose and expose his most secret thoughts to any other eye.

05:53:45.366 --> 05:53:50.566
He may have also intended the book for his son Eusebius Commodus, who however had no taste for

05:53:50.566 --> 05:53:56.366
his father's philosophy. Some careful hand preserved the precious volume, and a work by

05:53:56.366 --> 05:54:02.826
Antoninus is mentioned by other late writers besides Suidas. Many critics have labored on

05:54:03.666 --> 05:54:10.886
Antoninus. The most complete edition is that by Thomas Gattacher, 1652, quarto. The second edition

05:54:10.886 --> 05:54:18.166
of Gattacher was superintended by George Stanep, 1697, quarto. There is also an edition of 1704.

05:54:19.126 --> 05:54:24.026
Gattacher made and suggested many good corrections, and he also made a new Latin version,

05:54:24.326 --> 05:54:29.166
which is not a very good specimen of Latin, but it generally expresses the sense of the original,

05:54:29.166 --> 05:54:34.826
and often better than some of the more recent translations. He added in the margin opposite

05:54:34.826 --> 05:54:40.206
to each paragraph references to the other parallel passages, and he wrote a commentary,

05:54:40.606 --> 05:54:45.646
one of the most complete that has been written on any ancient author. This commentary contains

05:54:45.646 --> 05:54:50.686
the editor's exposition of the more difficult passages, and quotations from all the Greek and

05:54:50.686 --> 05:54:56.226
Roman writers for the illustration of the text. It is a wonderful monument of learning and labor,

05:54:56.226 --> 05:54:59.806
and certainly no Englishman has yet done anything like it.

05:55:00.326 --> 05:55:05.366
At the end of his preface, the editor says that he wrote it at Rotherhiss, near London in a severe

05:55:05.366 --> 05:55:12.966
winter, when he was in the 78th year of his age, 1651, a time when Milton, Seldon, and other great

05:55:12.966 --> 05:55:18.726
men of the Commonwealth time were living, and the great French scholar Somaz, Salmatius, with whom

05:55:18.726 --> 05:55:24.906
Gattacher corresponded and received help from him for his edition of Antoninus. The Greek text has

05:55:24.906 --> 05:55:32.326
also been edited by J.M. Schultz, Leipzig 1802, 8 volumes, and by the learned Greek Athamantinous

05:55:32.326 --> 05:55:39.986
Corais, Paris 1816, 8 volumes. The text of Schultz was republished by Tauchnitz, 1821.

05:55:40.946 --> 05:55:46.626
There are English, German, French, Italian, and Spanish translations of Marcus Antoninus,

05:55:46.746 --> 05:55:52.626
and there may be others. I have not seen all the English translations. There is one by Jeremy

05:55:52.626 --> 05:55:59.746
Collier, 1702, 8 volumes, a most coarse and vulgar copy of the original. The latest French

05:55:59.746 --> 05:56:05.966
translation by Alexis Pierron, in the collection of Charpentier, is better than Dossier's,

05:56:05.986 --> 05:56:13.726
which has been honored with an Italian version, Oudinay, 1772. There is an Italian version, 1675,

05:56:14.206 --> 05:56:20.866
which I have not seen. It is by a cardinal. Quote, A man illustrious in the church, the cardinal

05:56:20.866 --> 05:56:26.826
Francis Barberini the Elder, nephew of Pope Urban VII, occupied the last years of his life in

05:56:26.826 --> 05:56:31.766
translating into his native language the thoughts of the Roman emperor, in order to diffuse among

05:56:31.766 --> 05:56:38.466
the faithful the fertilizing and vivifying seeds. He dedicated this translation to his soul, to make

05:56:38.466 --> 05:56:43.766
it, as he says in his energetic style, redder than his purple at the sight of the virtues of this

05:56:43.766 --> 05:56:44.486
Gentile.

05:56:47.126 --> 05:56:52.266
I have made this translation at intervals, after having used the book for many years.

05:56:52.886 --> 05:56:57.566
It is made from the Greek, but I have not always followed one text, and I have occasionally

05:56:57.566 --> 05:57:03.666
compared other versions with my own. I made this translation for my own use, because I found that

05:57:03.666 --> 05:57:08.646
it was worth the labor, but it may be useful to others also, and therefore I determined to print

05:57:08.646 --> 05:57:14.726
it. As the original is sometimes very difficult to understand, and still more difficult to

05:57:14.726 --> 05:57:20.646
translate, it is not possible that I have always avoided error. But I believe that I have not often

05:57:20.646 --> 05:57:24.646
missed the meaning, and those who will take the trouble to compare the translation with the

05:57:24.646 --> 05:57:30.566
original should not hastily conclude that I am wrong if they do not agree with me. Some passages

05:57:30.566 --> 05:57:35.946
do give the meaning, though at first sight they may not appear to do so, and when I differ from

05:57:35.946 --> 05:57:41.686
I think in some places they are wrong, and in other places I am sure that they are.

05:57:42.246 --> 05:57:47.526
I have placed in some passages a plus sign, which indicates corruption in the text or great

05:57:47.526 --> 05:57:52.886
uncertainty in the meaning. I could have made the language more easy and flowing, but I have

05:57:52.886 --> 05:57:57.986
preferred a ruder style as being better suited to express the character of the original, and

05:57:57.986 --> 05:58:05.286
sometimes the obscurity which may appear in the version is a fair copy of the obscurity of the

05:58:05.286 --> 05:58:10.626
I have done the best that I could, and in the next text I have always given the same translation

05:58:10.626 --> 05:58:16.586
of the same word. The last reflection of the stoic philosophy that I have observed

05:58:16.586 --> 05:58:23.646
is in Simplicius's Commentary of the Incaridion of Epictetus. Simplicius was not a Christian,

05:58:24.386 --> 05:58:29.646
and such a man was not likely to be converted at a time when Christianity was grossly corrupted.

05:58:30.286 --> 05:58:35.506
But he was a really religious man, and he includes his commentary with a prayer to the deity,

05:58:35.946 --> 05:58:43.286
which no Christian could improve. From the time of Zeno to Simplicius, a period of about 900 years,

05:58:43.706 --> 05:58:47.746
the stoic philosophy formed the characters of some of the best and greatest men.

05:58:48.386 --> 05:58:53.506
Finally it became extinct, and we hear no more of it till the revival of letters in Italy.

05:58:54.566 --> 05:59:01.146
Angelo Poliziano met with two very inaccurate and incomplete manuscripts of Epictetus's

05:59:01.146 --> 05:59:07.106
Incaridion, which he had translated into Latin and dedicated to his great patron Lorenzo de Medici,

05:59:07.646 --> 05:59:12.146
in whose collection he had found the book. Poliziano's version was printed in the first

05:59:12.146 --> 05:59:20.066
ball edition of the Incaridion, AD 1531, op. Andraeum cartondrum. Poliziano recommends the

05:59:20.066 --> 05:59:25.946
Incaridion to Lorenzo as a work well suited to his temper, and useful in the difficulties

05:59:25.946 --> 05:59:32.626
by which he was surrounded. Epictetus and Antoninus have had readers ever since they were printed.

05:59:33.406 --> 05:59:38.566
The little book of Antoninus has been the companion of some great men. Machiavelli's

05:59:38.566 --> 05:59:43.626
Art of War and Marcus Antoninus were the two books which were used when he was a young man

05:59:43.626 --> 05:59:48.486
by Captain John Smith, and he could not have found two writers better fitted to form the

05:59:48.486 --> 05:59:54.946
of a soldier and a man. Smith is almost unknown and forgotten in England, his native country,

05:59:55.266 --> 06:00:01.226
but not in America where he saved the young colony of Virginia. He was great in his heroic mind and

06:00:01.226 --> 06:00:06.846
his deeds and arms, but greater still in the nobleness of his character. For a man's greatness

06:00:06.846 --> 06:00:12.846
lies not in wealth and station, as the vulgar believe, nor yet in his intellectual capacity,

06:00:13.246 --> 06:00:18.426
which is often associated with the meanest moral character, the most abject servility to those in

06:00:18.426 --> 06:00:25.206
high places, and arrogance to the poor lowly. But a man's true greatness lies in the consciousness

06:00:25.206 --> 06:00:30.546
of an honest purpose in life, founded on a just estimate of himself and everything else,

06:00:30.986 --> 06:00:36.586
on frequent self-examination, and a steady obedience to the rule which he knows to be right,

06:00:36.926 --> 06:00:43.086
without troubling himself, as the emperor says he should not, about what others may think or say,

06:00:43.086 --> 06:00:48.626
or whether they do or do not do, that which he thinks and says and does.

06:01:02.655 --> 06:01:10.095
the Meditations of Marcus Aurelius section 14 the philosophy of Antoninus by George long ma

06:01:23.315 --> 06:01:24.635
2007

06:01:25.355 --> 06:01:29.455
the philosophy of Antoninus by George long ma

06:01:31.875 --> 06:01:37.195
It has been said that stoic philosophy first showed its real value when it passed from Greece to Rome

06:01:38.035 --> 06:01:44.935
The doctrines of Zeno and his successors were well suited to the gravity and practical good sense of the Romans and even in the Republican

06:01:44.935 --> 06:01:52.095
Period we have an example of a man M. Cato Utensis who lived the life of a stoic and died consistently with the opinions

06:01:52.095 --> 06:01:54.095
which he professed

06:01:54.095 --> 06:02:01.055
He was a man says Cicero who embraced the stoic philosophy from conviction not for the purpose of vain discussion as most did

06:02:01.055 --> 06:02:06.315
but in order to make his life conformable to the stoic precepts in

06:02:06.315 --> 06:02:09.655
The wretched time from the death of Augustus to the murder of Domitian

06:02:09.655 --> 06:02:14.535
There was nothing but stoic philosophy which could console and support the followers of the old religion

06:02:14.535 --> 06:02:17.715
under imperial tyranny and amidst universal corruption

06:02:18.815 --> 06:02:27.415
There were even then noble minds that could dare and endure sustained by good conscious and elevated idea of the purposes of man's existence

06:02:28.095 --> 06:02:31.695
Such were paid as they see a held videos precious

06:02:31.695 --> 06:02:39.895
Cornutus see Mussonius refus and the poets Perseus and juvenile whose energetic language and manly thoughts may be as instructive to us

06:02:39.895 --> 06:02:41.975
Now as they might have been to their contemporaries

06:02:42.975 --> 06:02:45.195
Perseus died under Nero's bloody reign

06:02:45.195 --> 06:02:51.975
But juvenile had the good fortune to survive the tyrant Domitian and to see the better times of Nerva Trajan and Hadrian

06:02:51.975 --> 06:02:59.895
His best precepts are derived from the stoic school and they are enforced in his finest verses by the unrivaled vigor of the Latin language

06:03:01.535 --> 06:03:07.095
The two best expounders of the later stoical philosophy were a Greek slave and a Roman Emperor

06:03:07.735 --> 06:03:09.955
Epictetus a Phrygian Greek was brought to Rome

06:03:09.955 --> 06:03:14.655
We know not how he was there the slave and afterwards the freed man of an unworthy master

06:03:14.655 --> 06:03:18.515
Epaphroditus by name himself a free man and a favorite of Nero

06:03:19.675 --> 06:03:23.775
Epictetus may have been a hearer of see Mussonius Rufus while he was still a slave

06:03:23.775 --> 06:03:26.835
But he could hardly have been a teacher before he was made free

06:03:26.835 --> 06:03:31.055
He was one of the philosophers whom Domitian's order banished from Rome

06:03:31.815 --> 06:03:35.595
He retired to Nicopolis and Nippuris and he may have died there

06:03:36.635 --> 06:03:37.975
Like other great teachers

06:03:37.975 --> 06:03:44.355
He wrote nothing and we are indebted to his grateful pupil Arian for what we have of Epictetus's discourses

06:03:44.355 --> 06:03:49.795
Arian wrote eight books of the discourses of Epictetus of which only four remain and some fragments

06:03:49.795 --> 06:03:56.175
We also have from Arian's hand the small Enchiridion or manual or the chief precepts of Epictetus

06:03:56.175 --> 06:04:01.835
There is a valuable commentary on the Enchiridion by Simplicis who lived at the time of the Emperor Justinian

06:04:03.195 --> 06:04:05.875
Antoninus in his first book in which he gratefully

06:04:05.875 --> 06:04:12.815
Commentaries his obligations to his teachers says that he was made acquainted by Junius Rusticus with the discourses of Epictetus

06:04:12.815 --> 06:04:15.015
Whom he mentions also in other passages

06:04:15.635 --> 06:04:20.775
indeed the doctrines of Epictetus and Antoninus are the same and

06:04:20.775 --> 06:04:27.495
Epictetus is the best authority for the explanation of the philosophical language of Antoninus and the exposition of his opinions

06:04:27.495 --> 06:04:31.315
But the method of the two philosophers is entirely different

06:04:31.315 --> 06:04:37.295
Epictetus addressed himself to his hearers in a continuous discourse and in a familial and simple manner

06:04:37.295 --> 06:04:41.615
Antoninus wrote down his reflections for his own use only in

06:04:41.615 --> 06:04:44.295
Short-unconnected paragraphs which are often obscure

06:04:45.255 --> 06:04:47.955
The Stoics made three divisions of philosophy

06:04:47.955 --> 06:04:50.735
Physic, Ethic and Logic

06:04:51.455 --> 06:04:58.515
This division we are told by Diogenes was made by Zeno of Sidium the founder of the Stoic sect and by Chrysippus

06:04:58.515 --> 06:05:02.035
But these philosophers placed the three divisions in the following order

06:05:02.035 --> 06:05:04.075
Logic, Physic, Ethic

06:05:04.075 --> 06:05:10.655
It appears however that this division was made before Zeno's time and acknowledged by Plato as Cicero remarks

06:05:10.655 --> 06:05:15.065
Logic is not synonymous with our term logic in the narrow sense of that word

06:05:17.335 --> 06:05:20.505
Cleanthes, a Stoic subdivided the three divisions and made six

06:05:21.455 --> 06:05:24.215
Dialectic and rhetoric comprised in logic

06:05:24.215 --> 06:05:31.775
Ethic and politic, Physic and theology. This division was merely for practical use for all philosophy as one

06:05:32.415 --> 06:05:38.015
Even among the earliest Stoics logic or dialectic does not occupy the same place as in Plato

06:05:38.015 --> 06:05:42.915
It is considered only as an instrument which is to be used for the other divisions of philosophy

06:05:44.075 --> 06:05:49.175
An exposition of the earlier Stoic doctrines and of their modifications would require a volume

06:05:49.175 --> 06:05:55.135
My object is to explain only the opinions of Antoninus so far as they can be collected from his book

06:05:56.575 --> 06:05:58.935
According to the subdivision of Cleanthes

06:05:58.935 --> 06:06:05.015
Physic and theology go together or the study of the nature of things and the study of the nature of the deity

06:06:05.015 --> 06:06:09.915
So far as man can understand the deity and of his government of the universe

06:06:11.175 --> 06:06:16.415
This division or subdivision is not formally adopted by Antoninus for as already observed

06:06:16.415 --> 06:06:20.735
There is no method in his book, but it is virtually contained in it

06:06:22.915 --> 06:06:30.375
Cleanthes also connects ethic and politic or the study of principles of morals and the study of the Constitution of civil society and

06:06:30.375 --> 06:06:33.755
Undoubtedly he did well in subdividing ethic into two parts

06:06:33.755 --> 06:06:38.475
Ethic in a narrower sense and politic for though the two are intimately connected

06:06:38.475 --> 06:06:44.775
They are also very distinct and many questions can only be properly discussed by carefully observing the distinction

06:06:46.515 --> 06:06:53.595
Antoninus does not treat of politic his subject is ethic an ethic in its practical application to his own

06:06:53.595 --> 06:06:56.635
Conduct in life as a man and as a governor

06:06:56.635 --> 06:07:03.735
His ethic is founded on the doctrines about man's nature the universal nature and the relations of every man

06:07:03.755 --> 06:07:05.035
to everything else

06:07:05.035 --> 06:07:12.495
It is therefore intimately and inseparably connected with physics or the nature of things and with theology or the nature of the deity

06:07:12.495 --> 06:07:19.455
He advises us to examine well all the impressions on our minds and to form a right judgment of them to make just

06:07:19.455 --> 06:07:24.515
Conclusions and to inquire into the meanings of words and so far to apply dialectic

06:07:24.515 --> 06:07:30.595
But he has no attempt at any exposition of dialectic and his philosophy is in substance purely moral and practical

06:07:30.595 --> 06:07:32.275
He says quote

06:07:32.875 --> 06:07:40.895
Constantly and if it be possible on the occasion of every impression on the soul apply it to the principles of physics of ethic and of

06:07:40.895 --> 06:07:42.155
dialectic end quote

06:07:42.895 --> 06:07:47.175
Which is only another way of telling us to examine the impression in every possible way

06:07:48.935 --> 06:07:54.935
In another passage he says quote to the age which had been mentioned let this one still be added

06:07:54.935 --> 06:08:00.375
Make for thyself a definition or description of the object which is presented to thee so as to see

06:08:00.375 --> 06:08:07.435
Distinctly what kind of a thing it is in its substance in its nudity in its complete entirety and tell thyself its proper name and the

06:08:07.435 --> 06:08:12.555
Names of the things which it has been compounded and into which it will be resolved end quote

06:08:13.795 --> 06:08:21.035
Such an examination implies a use of dialectic which Antoninus accordingly employed as a mean towards establishing his physical

06:08:21.035 --> 06:08:23.215
